{[%evp 0,23,19,31,14,-14,-11,0,0,-14,8,7,17,24,26,21,15,18,17,14,16,-13,10,17,24,23]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Bxd2+ ({Now and then, the jump} 5... Nc6 $6 {should be used by Black with great care, for example} 6. Bxb4 Nxb4 7. Bg2 (7. Qa4+ {is also possible, although the knight will have to retreat anyway -} Nc6 8. Bg2) (7. a3 Nc6 8. Nbd2 {will transpose to the text}) 7... O-O ({Black is far away from the liberating e6-e5 after} 7... a5 8. O-O O-O 9. a3 Nc6 10. Qc2 $16 {[%cal Gb1d2] as well}) 8. a3 Nc6 9. Nbd2 b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Rc1 $16 {with the same verdict}) (5... c5 6. Bxb4 cxb4 7. Nbd2 (7. Bg2 dxc4 8. Ne5 {transposes to 4...dxc4 5.Bg2 Bb4+6.Bd2, which has been covered in Part 1, White is by no means obliged to leave the c4-pawn}) 7... Nc6 (7... O-O 8. Bg2 {is likely to transpose to the following lines}) ({in case of} 7... dxc4 8. Nxc4 b5 9. Nce5 O-O 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. O-O {the extra central pawn can be a huge asset in the long run -} Qb6 12. Rc1 Nbd7 13. Nd3 $14 ({fighting for the e4-square with} 13. Qd3 $14 {may well be White's best})) 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O b6 10. Rc1 Bb7 11. e3 $14) (5... Qe7 {is yet another idea in the spirit of the Bogo-Indian. Just like in the line from above, Black has already committed his d-pawn and is therefore lacking the restrained d7-d6.} 6. Bg2 (6. Qa4+ {forces} Nc6 {, but Black seems to be in good shape with timely central exchanges, e.g.} 7. a3 Bxd2+ 8. Nbxd2 O-O 9. Bg2 Rd8 (9... e5 {is perhaps a bit premature -} 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Qe4 $1 Qxe4 14. Nxe4 c6 15. O-O-O $14) 10. O-O dxc4 11. e3 a6 12. Qxc4 e5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Nf3 Qe7 16. Nd4 c6 $11) 6... O-O ({going after the pair of bishops by} 6... Ne4 $6 {is too time-consuming -} 7. O-O Nxd2 8. Nbxd2 c6 9. a3 Ba5 10. e4 O-O 11. Qc2 $16) (6... dxc4 $2 7. Qa4+ Nc6 8. Ne5 $16) 7. O-O dxc4 (7... c5 8. Bxb4 cxb4 9. Nbd2 $14) (7... a5 $6 {is inaccurate in the view of} 8. Bg5 $1 dxc4 (8... h6 $2 {is losing at least a pawn after} 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. c5 $16 {[%csl Rb4]}) 9. e4 h6 10. Bh4 g5 11. a3 $1 (11. Nxg5 hxg5 12. Bxg5 e5 {is worth checking, for} 13. a3 {may transpose to 12.Nxg5, see below}) 11... Bd6 (11... gxh4 12. axb4 hxg3 13. fxg3 Nxe4 14. Ne5 Nd6 15. bxa5 $16) 12. Bxg5 $1 (12. Nxg5 hxg5 13. Bxg5 e5 14. f4 $40) 12... hxg5 13. e5 Nc6 14. exd6 cxd6 15. Nxg5 d5 16. Nc3 $16) (7... Bxd2 8. Nbxd2 {transposes to the leading text with 5...Bxd2}) (7... c6 {does not correspond well with the bishop still on the b4-square -} 8. Qc2 $16) 8. Qc2 Nc6 (8... Rd8 $6 9. Qxc4 Bxd2 10. Nbxd2 c6 {as in Nihal - Sarana, Chess. com INT 2020, limits the scope of Bg2, but Black remains passive, especially when the essential advance e6-e5 is not yet in sight. White has many promising continuations to choose from -} 11. Ne5 (11. e4 $16) (11. Rfd1 $16) 11... Nbd7 12. Rfd1 $16) 9. Qxc4 Bd6 10. Nc3 $14 ({for} 10. Rd1 {, which transposes to Ding Liren- Mamedyarov, Chess.com INT, 2021, see the notes in the next Chapter.})) 6. Nbxd2 O-O 7. Bg2 b6 {Black can hardly do without this plan:} (7... Qe7 8. O-O {reaches the next crossroads:} c5 (8... b6 9. Rc1 Bb7 10. Re1 $5 {[%cal Ge2e4]} ({White is staying on top by} 10. Qa4 {as well, for instance} c5 11. dxc5 bxc5 12. Nb3 Nbd7 13. Na5 Rab8 14. Nxb7 Rxb7 15. Qa3 Rc8 16. e3 $14) 10... c5 {is instructively met by} (10... Na6 11. c5 $5 (11. Qa4 c5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. e3 $14) 11... bxc5 12. Qb3 Rab8 (12... Rfb8 13. Qa3) 13. Qa3 Rfd8 14. Nb3 Ne4 15. dxc5 $16 {[%csl Ra6]}) 11. cxd5 exd5 12. e4 $1 Nxe4 (12... dxe4 $6 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Ng5 $16) 13. Nh4 $1 Qf6 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxe4 16. Rxe4 $16) (8... Rd8 9. Rc1 $16) 9. dxc5 Qxc5 10. Rc1 Qb6 11. Qb3 Nc6 (11... Qxb3 12. Nxb3 $16) 12. Rfd1 Bd7 13. cxd5 $1 {Fixing the central structure with favourable endgame on two results:} exd5 (13... Nxd5 $6 14. Qxb6 axb6 (14... Nxb6 15. Ne4 $16 {[%cal Ge4c5]}) 15. a3 $16) 14. Qxb6 axb6 15. a3 $14) (7... Nbd7 8. O-O c5 $6 ({as said, without the dark-squared bishops on the board the set-ups with} 8... c6 $6 {are passive and therefore not much in the spirit of the position; White can achieve a considerable advantage by simple means -} 9. Qc2 {[%cal Ge2e4]} b6 10. e4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Qxe4 Bb7 13. Rac1 Qe7 14. c5 $16 {Cheparinov - Demchenko, Jerusalem, 2015}) (8... b6 {transposes to 7...b6 in the leading text}) 9. dxc5 $1 {is even stronger, e.g.} (9. cxd5 Nxd5 $6 (9... exd5 $142 $14) 10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. e4 $1 ({too soft is} 11. Rc1 b6 12. a3 a5 13. Nb3 Nxb3 14. Qxb3 $14 {Cheparinov - Naiditsch, Bol, 2013}) 11... Nf6 12. Qc2 $16) 9... Nxc5 10. b4 Nce4 (10... Ncd7 11. Rc1 Qe7 12. Qb3 $16) 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 (11... dxe4 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Ng5 $16) 12. Qd4 $16 (12. Rc1 $5) (12. Qb3 $5)) 8. O-O Nbd7 ({To} 8... c5 {a logical reaction is} 9. dxc5 bxc5 {and, after the mobilization of the heavy pieces, White has good prospects against the  (hanging) central pawns:} 10. Qc2 $5 (10. cxd5 exd5 11. Qc2 Na6 12. e4 (12. a3 Rb8 {[%cal Gd8b6]}) 12... Nxe4 (12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Bf5 14. Nfd2 $14) 13. Nxe4 Bf5 14. Qa4 dxe4 15. Nh4 Bc8 16. Qxe4 Rb8 17. b3 $14) 10... Na6 {can either transpose to the last line or White may prefer to keep more tension in the centre by} 11. a3 Bb7 12. e3 Rc8 13. Rfd1 Qb6 14. Rac1 $14) ({After} 8... Bb7 {White is presented with a pleasant choice -} 9. Rc1 $1 ({or} 9. b4 {with a likely transposition to the leading text}) 9... Nbd7 ({in reply to} 9... Na6 $6 10. c5 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7] is even stronger}) 10. c5 $1 bxc5 (10... c6 $6 11. Re1 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4]}) 11. dxc5 Nb8 ({as well as on the previous move,} 11... c6 {is met by} 12. Re1 Qc7 13. e4 $16) 12. b4 $16) 9. b4 $5 {A curious approach against} (9. Rc1 c5 {, when Black can take with the knight.}) 9... Bb7 {It seems necessary to precede any queenside action by this:} ({The queenside remains under typical pressure after} 9... c5 10. bxc5 bxc5 11. Qa4 $1 {, for example} Bb7 (11... Nb6 12. Qa3 $16) (11... dxc4 12. Nxc4 Bb7 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Qa3 Rc8 15. Rac1 $16) 12. Rab1 Qc7 13. Rfc1 $16) ({So is with} 9... a5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. b5 {[%csl Rc6]} Bb7 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. Nc4 $16) 10. c5 {[%csl Rb7]} ({White can claim a long-term playing initiative by fixing the centre by} 10. cxd5 $5 Nxd5 (10... exd5 11. b5 $14) 11. Qb3 $14 {as well.}) 10... a5 11. Qc2 c6 12. a3 $14 *

