{[%evp 0,45,14,36,20,0,0,0,2,-28,15,12,25,16,73,69,37,30,86,54,61,39,54,62,62,36,34,45,50,48,54,32,26,29,29,0,31,40,37,42,39,27,14,26,37,49,37,37]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Bd6 6. Bg2 ({Another popular line is} 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Bg5) 6... c6 (6... O-O 7. O-O (7. Nc3 dxc4 $1 8. e4 Be7 $13) 7... c6 {is a part of Black's set-up and, analogously to the main text, it is useful to take the e4-square under control by} (7... Nbd7 8. c5 $1 (8. Qc2 c6) (8. Nc3 {is once again running into} dxc4 $1) 8... Be7 9. Nc3 Ne4 ({both} 9... b6 $2 10. c6 $1 Nb8 11. Ne5 $16) ({and} 9... c6 10. Qc2 {are examined in the annotations to 6...Nbd7, see below}) 10. Bf4 $5 ({it is possible just to expand further on the queenside with} 10. b4 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4]}) ({as Black has already jumped in the centre, then} 10. Qc2 $5 {is less flexible -} f5 11. Bf4 g5 12. Be3 $14 {- a position, which should be compared to the branch with 10...g5}) 10... Nxc3 (10... f5 $2 11. Nb5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rc7]}) (10... c6 $2 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Ne5 $16) (10... g5 11. Be3 f5 {is quite similar to 10.Qc2 from above, here White can take advantage of his turn to move by} 12. Qc1 $1 {[%csl Rg5]} h6 (12... g4 $6 13. Ne1 $16) 13. h4 $1 gxh4 14. gxh4 Kh8 (14... Rf6 15. Kh1 Kh7 16. Rg1 Qe8 17. Bh3 $40 {[%cal Gg1g2]}) 15. Kh2 (15. Bxh6 $5 Rg8 16. Bf4 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gf3g5]}) 15... Rg8 (15... Bxh4 16. Bh3) 16. Bh3 Bxh4 17. Rg1 $16) 11. bxc3 {is providing White with an additional idea for c3-c4 break:} b6 (11... c6 12. c4 dxc4 13. Qc2 b5 14. a4 $1 (14. cxb6 axb6 $11) 14... Bb7 15. Rfd1 {[%csl Rb7]} a6 16. e4 Nf6 17. h3 $14 {[%cal Ga1b1]}) 12. c4 $1 Bb7 (12... bxc5 13. cxd5 exd5 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Ne5 Bb7 16. Rb1 $36 {[%cal Gb1b7,Gg2d5]}) 13. cxd5 (13. Qc2 dxc4 {may transpose}) 13... Bxd5 14. Qc2 bxc5 (14... f5 15. Rfd1 $14) (14... Nf6 15. Rac1 $14) 15. e4 Bb7 16. Rfb1 $5 {A highly unexpected answer to the eternal question "Which rook?"} Rb8 17. dxc5 Nxc5 18. Ne5 f6 19. Rd1 Qe8 20. Be3 fxe5 21. Bxc5 Qc6 22. Rdc1 $16 {Had the other rook been still on the b1-square, then Black would have had the tricky 22....Ba6! with useful simplifications.}) (7... dxc4 8. Qc2 (8. Bg5 $5 {[%cal Gb1d2]}) 8... Nc6 9. Rd1 Qe7 (9... Re8 10. Bc3 $5 ({Black's task is easier after} 10. Qxc4 e5 11. d5 Nd4 $13 {Ding Liren - Mamedyarov, chess24. com INT, 2021}) 10... Nd5 11. Ne5 Bxe5 12. dxe5 Qe7 13. Na3 $14) 10. Qxc4 e5 11. dxe5 (11. d5 Nb8) 11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 (12... Bxe5 $6 13. Bb4 $1) 13. Bc3 Qe7 14. Nd2 Be6 {So far in another game Ding Liren - Mamedyarov, Chess.com INT, 2021, with higher prospects for White after} 15. Qa4 c6 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Qc2 $14 {because of the safer king.}) (7... Nc6 8. Qc2 $14 dxc4 {- 7. ..dxc4}) (7... Ne4 8. Nc3 c6 {might be not the exact order for building the Stonewall:} 9. Nxe4 $5 (9. Qc2 {is not the most demanding -} Nxd2 (9... f5 10. Be3 $14 {[%cal Gf3e1,Ge1d3]}) 10. Nxd2 f5 11. e3 $14) 9... dxe4 10. Ne1 f5 {Now critical is} 11. f3 $1 e5 (11... exf3 $6 12. Nxf3 $16) 12. fxe4 fxe4 (12... exd4 $6 13. exf5 Bxf5 {took place in Bartodziej - Dziewonski, Poland, 2022, which could have seen the powerful sequence} 14. c5 $1 Bxc5 15. Qb3+ Kh8 16. Nd3 $1 ({much stronger than} 16. Qxb7 d3+ 17. e3 Nd7 $13) 16... Bb6 (16... Nd7 17. Qxb7 $16) 17. a4 $1 a5 18. g4 $1 Bxd3 19. Rxf8+ Qxf8 20. Rf1 Qg8 21. Qxb6 Bxe2 22. Qxb7 Na6 23. Rf2 Bc4 24. Qxc6 Rc8 25. Qd6 $16) 13. Rxf8+ Bxf8 (13... Qxf8 $6 14. Bxe4 exd4 15. Qc2 $16 {[%cal Ge1f3,Gc4c5]}) 14. Bc3 exd4 (14... Bf5 15. dxe5 Nd7 16. Nc2 Qg5 17. Qc1 $14) 15. Bxe4 $1 (15. Bxd4 Bf5 16. Nc2 Na6 $11) (15. Qxd4 Qxd4+ 16. Bxd4 Bf5 17. Nc2 Na6 18. Ne3 Bg6 $14) 15... Na6 16. Bxd4 Nc5 17. Bc2 $5 (17. Bg2 Bf5 18. Nf3 Qe7 $44) 17... Bh3 18. Nf3 $14 {White has prevailed in the opening phase and is a pawn up with every chance to convert it.}) 8. Nc3 $1 ({indeed,} 8. b3 {allows} Ne4 {[%cal Gf7f5]}) (8. Qc2 Nbd7 {keeps the same option open}) 8... dxc4 $5 (8... Nbd7 9. b3 {is ultimately transposing to 6. ..c6}) 9. e4 (9. Ne5 $5 Bxe5 ({passive is} 9... Be7 10. e3) 10. dxe5 Nd5 {and White can rely on a long-term initiative on the dark squares (and mostly the one on d6) after} 11. b3 ({or} 11. Qc2 Nd7 12. f4 b5 13. Ne4 $44) 11... cxb3 12. axb3 $44) 9... Be7 (9... Bc7 $2 10. e5 Nd5 11. Qc2 $16) 10. a4 $1 ({more pragmatic than} 10. e5 Nd5 11. Ne4 b5 12. Qc2 $44 {[%cal Ge4g5,Gh2h4]}) 10... c5 (10... b6 $6 11. Bf4 $36 {[%cal Gf3e5]}) 11. e5 (11. dxc5 Nc6 $13) 11... Nd5 (11... cxd4 $2 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Ne4 $18) (11... Nfd7 $2 12. d5 exd5 13. Nxd5 $16) 12. dxc5 $1 Nd7 (12... Bxc5 $6 13. Qe2 $16 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gc3e4]}) (12... Na6 13. Ne4 Nxc5 {- 12.. .Nd7 13.Ne4 Nxc5}) 13. Ne4 {looks more principled:} (13. Qe2 Nxc5 14. Qxc4 Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Bd7 16. Rfd1 Rc8 17. a5 Qe8 {[%cal Gc5a4]} 18. Nd4 ({Black is close to full equality after} 18. Qg4 Nb3 19. Rab1 Bc6 {either, as Qg4 is lacking support for creating threats against the enemy king}) 18... Na4 19. Qb3 Nxc3 20. bxc3 b6 21. axb6 axb6 22. Ra7 Bc5 $11) 13... Qc7 (13... Nxc5 14. Nxc5 Bxc5 15. Qc2 Be7 ({a necessary precaution, for} 15... Bd7 $2 {is giving to White a free hand on the kingside -} 16. Ng5 $1 g6 17. Qxc4 Rc8 18. Qh4 h5 19. g4 $16) 16. Qxc4 Bd7 17. Qg4 Kh8 18. Rfd1 $14) 14. Qc2 $1 Nxc5 (14... Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. Rfe1 Qc7 17. Qxc4 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1]}) 15. Neg5 $1 (15. Qxc4 b6 $11 {[%cal Gc8a6]}) 15... Nd3 16. b3 g6 17. Ne4 $14) (6... Nbd7 {is met again by} 7. Nc3 (7. c5 $5 Be7 8. Nc3 Ne4 9. Bf4 Nxc3 10. bxc3 b6 11. c4 $14) 7... dxc4 ({after} 7... O-O {Black must reckon with} 8. c5 $1 Be7 9. Qc2 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf6e4] and now:} c6 (9... b6 $6 10. c6 $1 Nb8 11. Ne5 Ne8 12. e4 {puts him into a delicate situation:} f6 (12... dxe4 {and Black's queenside leaves a sad impression after both} 13. O-O-O $16 ({and} 13. Nxe4 Qxd4 14. Bc3 Bb4 15. O-O Bxc3 16. Qxc3 Qxc3 17. Nxc3 $16 {[%csl Gc6]})) 13. Nd7 $1 ({it is hard to disentangle after} 13. exd5 $5 fxe5 14. dxe5 Bc5 15. O-O $36 {[%csl Ra8,Rb8,Rc8] as well}) 13... Nxd7 14. cxd7 Qxd7 (14... Bxd7 15. exd5 e5 16. O-O $16) 15. exd5 Bb7 16. Qb3 exd5 17. Nxd5 Kh8 18. O-O $16) 10. O-O {and only here} b6 {is the lesser evil -} 11. b4 a5 12. a3 Ba6 13. Rfb1 $14) (7... c6 {leads to the main text 6...c6 7.Nc3 Nbd7 etc.}) 8. Qa4 O-O (8... a6 $6 {is inaccurate in the view of} 9. Ne5 $1 O-O 10. Nxc4 Be7 11. O-O $16) (8... c6 9. Qxc4 e5 10. O-O O-O 11. Rad1 Qe7 12. Be3 $5 (12. Qb3 $14) 12... Nb6 (12... e4 $6 13. Nd2 Nb6 14. Qb3 Be6 15. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Re4]}) (12... exd4 13. Bxd4 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4]}) (12... Rd8 13. Qb3 exd4 14. Nxd4 Ne5 15. Qc2 h6 16. h3 $14) 13. Qb3 Be6 14. Qc2 exd4 15. Bxd4 (15. Nxd4 Be5 16. Nxe6 Qxe6 $14) 15... Nfd7 {Romanishin - Fragiadakis, Athens, 2005} 16. h3 $1 Rad8 17. e4 $14) 9. Qxc4 e5 ({here, in reply to} 9... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] the subtle retreat} 10. Qd3 $1 {limits Black's options like 9...b5 -} c5 11. O-O Rb8 12. Rfd1 $14 ({or} 12. dxc5 $5 Nxc5 13. Qd4 {[%cal Gd2g5,Ga1d1]})) 10. O-O Qe7 (10... Nb6 11. Qd3 exd4 12. Qxd4 c6 13. Rad1 Re8 14. Bg5 Be7 15. Qh4 Nbd7 16. Qa4 h6 17. Bf4 $14) 11. Qb3 (11. e4 $5) 11... c6 12. Rad1 Re8 {Cheparinov - Moiseenko, Kocaeli, 2015, when} 13. Qc2 $14 {is yet another good prophylaxis.}) (6... dxc4 {at once is probably less recommendable:} 7. Qa4+ (7. Ne5 $5 O-O 8. Nxc4 Be7 9. e3 c5 {is apparently a better version of the deviation from the leading text 7. ..dxc4 8.Ne5!, see below, but it is nevertheless insufficient for full equality -} 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. b4 (11. Nc3 $14) 11... Be7 12. O-O $14) 7... Nc6 (7... Bd7 8. Qxc4 Bc6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 Nbd7 11. Qd3 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Bb4 12. Rfd1 $14) 8. Na3 $1 ({Here is the real problem for Black rather than} 8. Qxc4 e5) 8... Ne4 (8... O-O $6 9. Nxc4 Be7 10. e3 $16) ({it is not easy for Black to justify} 8... Bxa3 9. Qxa3 {, as shown by:} Ne4 {is usually time-consuming, White has a choice:} ({accepting a second pawn} 9... Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 {is like a play with the fire -} 11. Rd1 {[%cal Ga3f8]} a5 (11... Qb6 12. Ba5 $16) (11... Qd6 12. Bb4 $16) 12. Be3 (12. Bh6 {is less convincing because of} Qg4 {and Black is able to counter 13.Bf4 with 13...Nd5}) 12... Qe5 13. Bf4 Qb5 14. Bxc7 Bd7 15. O-O Bc6 16. Bxc6+ Qxc6 17. Be5 $1 $36 {[%csl Re8]}) (9... Qd6 {is much more reasonable, the only example with it has seen} 10. Rc1 $5 Qxa3 11. bxa3 Bd7 12. Rxc4 O-O-O 13. O-O Nd5 {Shimanov - Nakhapetiane, Moscow, 2011, here worth of attention is} 14. Rc5 $5 Be8 15. e3 $14 {[%cal Gf1c1]}) 10. Bf4 {preserves the pair of bishops -} (10. Qe3 $5 Nxd2 (10... Nd6 11. Ne5 $14) 11. Qxd2 O-O 12. Rc1 Qd5 13. O-O Rd8 14. Rfd1 $14 {, preparing to regain the pawn with interest}) 10... Nd6 (10... Qe7 $6 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 12. Ne5 $16) 11. O-O O-O 12. Rfc1 (12. b3 $5 cxb3 13. Qxb3 $36 {[%csl Gf4,Gg2][%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1]}) 12... a5 {and here it makes sense to transform it into a promising version of the Bogo-Indian by} 13. Bxd6 cxd6 14. Rxc4 $14 {and a permanent pressure on the queenside}) 9. Nxc4 Nxd2 10. Nfxd2 Bd7 {and White has a good reason to go for the structure from above by} (10... O-O $6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Rc1 $16 {[%csl Rc6]}) 11. Nxd6+ $5 ({alternatively, White can just establish the control over the c5- and e5-squares by} 11. e3 O-O 12. Qc2 $14) ({or} 11. Na5 Nxa5 12. Qxa5 c6 13. Qc3 $14 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gd2c4] and rely on his space advantage in the long run}) 11... cxd6 {, especially in the view of} 12. Nc4 $1 {, practically forcing the opponent to} O-O (12... Qc7 $2 13. Qa3 $16) 13. Nxd6 Qc7 14. Ne4 Rfd8 15. O-O $1 ({Clearly the best, as the development should not be neglected - for instance} 15. e3 e5 $132) 15... Be8 16. Qc2 $1 Rxd4 17. Ng5 g6 18. e3 Rdd8 19. Ne4 Qe7 20. Rac1 $16) 7. Nc3 $1 {A small refinement of the move order, now the e4-square is under control.} ({White should take care about his c4-pawn after} 7. O-O Nbd7 {, even though this line and}) (7. Qc2 Nbd7 {will most probably transpose, see 8...0-0 below.}) 7... Nbd7 (7... O-O 8. O-O {- 6.. .0-0.}) (7... dxc4 {is strongly met by} 8. Ne5 $1 Bc7 ({after} 8... Be7 9. e3 {Black is a tempo (and this extra move is Nb1-c3!) down in comparison with the 4...dxc4 5. Bg2 c6!? variation and can therefore hardly equalize, e.g.} c5 10. dxc5 Nbd7 11. Nxc4 Nxc5 12. O-O O-O 13. Qe2 $16 {[%cal Gf1d1,Ge3e4]}) 9. Bg5 (9. e3 $5 Nbd7 10. f4 (10. Nxc4 e5 $11) 10... c5 (10... O-O 11. Nxc4) (10... Nxe5 11. fxe5 Nd5 12. Qe2 $14) 11. Nxc4 a6 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. O-O O-O 14. Qe2 $14) 9... h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Nxc4 O-O 12. O-O Nd7 13. e3 $14) 8. b3 $5 (8. O-O dxc4 $1) 8... dxc4 {The start of a concrete move order before White has managed to castle.} ({In case of} 8... O-O 9. O-O {the e2-e4 advance is already in the air:} Re8 (9... b6 $6 10. e4 $1 Nxe4 (10... dxe4 11. Ng5 Bb7 12. Ngxe4 $16) 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Ng5 Nf6 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Bb7 15. Qc2 h6 16. b4 $16 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gc4c5]}) (9... dxc4 10. bxc4 e5 11. e3 Re8 {is likely to reach the line with 9...Re8, see below}) 10. Qc2 {is a sort of Anti-Meran with fianchettoed Bg2 -} dxc4 (10... e5 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Nb5 Bb8 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Rac1 $14) 11. bxc4 e5 12. e3 h6 (12... exd4 13. exd4 Nf8 14. Nd1 $5 {[%cal Gd1e3]} (14. Rab1 Rb8 15. d5 cxd5 16. cxd5 $14 {Cheparinov - Zubov, Ankara, 2018}) 14... Bg4 15. Ne3 Bh5 16. Rad1 $14 {[%cal Gd2c3,Ge3f5]}) 13. Rad1 Qe7 14. Bc1 $14 {[%cal Gc1b2] is a proper way to anticipate the possible e5-e4.}) ({The other alternatives are failing to impress, for example} 8... Ne4 $6 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Ng5 f5 11. f3 $1 (11. Nxe6 Qf6 12. d5 cxd5 13. cxd5 Nb6 $11) 11... h6 (11... exf3 12. exf3 O-O 13. f4 $16) 12. c5 $1 Bb8 (12... hxg5 13. cxd6 $16) 13. Nxe6 Qf6 14. Nf4 O-O 15. Qc1 $16) (8... b6 $6 9. O-O Bb7 {is running into} 10. e4 $1 Nxe4 (10... dxe4 11. Ng5 $16) 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Ng5 f5 13. f3 h6 14. Nxe6 Qf6 15. d5 cxd5 16. cxd5 Nc5 ({a neat point is} 16... Bxd5 17. fxe4 $16) 17. fxe4 Nxe6 18. Rxf5 $5 ({or the simpler} 18. dxe6 Qxe6 19. Qh5+ g6 20. Qh3 $16) 18... Qd4+ 19. Kh1 Nf8 20. Qe1 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5,Ga1d1]} Rc8 21. Rd1 Rc2 22. e5 Bc5 23. e6 Ng6 24. Qf1 $16) 9. bxc4 e5 10. e3 exd4 (10... O-O 11. O-O {transposes to 8...0-0.}) 11. exd4 Qe7+ 12. Ne2 ({Keeping