8 22. Bf1 $14 {[%cal Gf1c4]}) 17. a4 $1 (17. Nd3 Bf5) 17... a5 (17... Bf5 18. a5 a6 19. c5 Bc7 20. Ne5 Re8 21. Qc3 $14) 18. c5 {White should better continue in the same concrete and energetic manner.} (18. Nd3 {is the other way to control the b4-square, to which} Bf5 {is again fully justified.}) 18... Bxf4 {Parting out with the bishop in return for the d5-square.} ({Moreover, after} 18... Bc7 19. Ne5 $14 {White's knights will be very annoying.}) 19. Qxf4 Be6 ({Another idea is to block the b-file by} 19... Nd5 20. Qd2 Nb4 {at first. In his turn, White has} 21. Ra3 $14 {, thus preparing a rook lift to the kingside or the e-file in particular.}) 20. h4 Re8 ({Black is by no means obliged to protect the g5-square by} 20... h6 $6 {, to which very promising is the exchange sacrifice} 21. Rxe6 $1 fxe6 22. Qe3 {[%csl Re6,Rg6,Rh7]} Re8 (22... Qe8 23. Bh3) 23. Ne5 Rb8 24. Re1 $36 {and the weakened b1-h7 diagonal may tell pretty soon.}) (20... Nd5 21. Qd2 $14 {will most probably transpose at some point to 19...Nd5}) (20... Bd5 {is another option, with the idea to trade the bishops before planting the knight in the centre -} 21. Rab1 Rb8 22. Ne5 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 $14 {, although Black should be aware of the appearance of its counterpart at the c4-square.}) 21. Rab1 (21. Ng5 Bd5 22. Rxe8+ Qxe8 23. Bxd5 Nxd5 24. Qf3 {and it makes sense to play the prophylactic} Nf6 $14 ({and deny Ng5 of its new route to the d6-square, as in} 24... Qe7 25. Ne4 $14)) 21... Qd7 22. Ne5 Qc7 23. Rb2 $14 *

