3, White can finally castle.} h4 (14... Nf8 $6 15. Ne4 $16) (14... Qe7 $6 15. Nb3 $16) 15. gxh4 $1 (15. g4 Qe7 16. Qe1 h3 $1 17. Bxh3 Nxc5 18. Nxb4 e4 $44) 15... Nf8 (15... Nh5 $6 16. Ne4 f5 17. Ng3 $16) 16. Kh1 (16. Ne4 $5 Nxe4 17. fxe4 Bg4 $1 (17... Qxh4 $143 18. Nxb4) 18. Qe1 (18. Nxb4 $6 {, which allows} Bxe2 19. Rf2 d3 $13 {does not at all correspond to all the previous efforts}) 18... Ra6 19. Kh1 (19. Qf2 Rf6) 19... Rh6 20. Bf3 Bxf3+ 21. exf3 Ne6 $14) 16... Ng6 17. Ne4 (17. Nxb4 Nf4 18. Qe1 Bf5 $44) 17... Nxe4 18. fxe4 Bg4 (18... Nxh4 19. Bf3 $1 {[%cal Gf1g1]}) 19. Bf3 Qxh4 20. Qe1 $1 (20. Nxb4 Nf4 21. Qe1 Bxf3+ 22. exf3 Qe7 $1 23. a4 $140 Qxc5 24. b3 Ra6 $1 25. Nxa6 (25. Nd5 Rh6 $44) 25... bxa6 $44 {[%cal Ga6a5,Ge8b8]}) 20... Qxe1 21. Rfxe1 Bxf3+ 22. exf3 $14) (7... Nbd7 8. O-O c6 (8... Be7 {- 7...Be7}) 9. Bxb4 (9. Rd1 b6) 9... axb4 10. Nbd2 b6 11. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 (11... Bb7 $5 12. Rd1 Qe7 13. cxd5 {is based on the vulnerability of the c6-pawn:} cxd5 (13... exd5 14. Nxc6 Qd6 15. Ne5 Nxe5 (15... Rfc8 16. Qb1 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Qxe5 18. e3 $14) 16. dxe5 Qxe5 17. Nb3 Qxe2 18. Re1 Qa6 19. Nd4 $36 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc1f4,Gd4f5,Gc1g5]}) 14. Qc7 Rab8 15. Nxd7 (15. Nc6 Bxc6 16. Qxc6 Rfc8 17. Qa4 b5 18. Qb3 Nb6 $11) 15... Nxd7 16. Nf3 (16. Rdc1 Rfc8 17. Qf4 $14) 16... Rfc8 17. Qf4 Ba6 18. Qd2 Nf6 19. Rdc1 Ne4 20. Qe1 $14) 12. dxe5 Nd7 {took place in two games of Gelfand's and they illustrated that Black has problems to solve -} 13. cxd5 (13. f4 $5) 13... cxd5 14. Nf3 Ba6 (14... Bb7 $6 15. Qe3 Qe7 16. Nd4 Rfc8 17. f4 $14 {[%cal Gf4f5] Gelfand - Adams, London, 2021}) 15. Re1 $142 $5 (15. Qe3 Qb8 $1 {[%csl Re5]} ({a clear refinement over} 15... Rc8 $2 16. Nd4 Rc4 {Gelfand - Sargsyan, Almaty, 2022, when} 17. a3 $1 b3 18. f4 $16 {could fix White's advantage}) 16. Rfc1 ({White would like to siege the b4-pawn rather than} 16. a3 bxa3 17. Rxa3 Bb7) 16... Rc8 17. Rxc8+ Bxc8 18. Qb3 Ba6 19. Bf1 Nxe5 20. Nxe5 Qxe5 21. Qxb4 Qc7 $11) 15... Qe7 (15... Rc8 16. Qe3) ({White has just prepared to meet} 15... Qb8 {with} 16. Qf4 $1 Rc8 $140 17. b3 h6 {[%cal Gg7g5]} 18. h4 $14 {[%cal Gg2f1]}) 16. Qe3 Rfc8 17. Nd4 Rc4 18. Rec1 Rac8 19. Rxc4 Rxc4 (19... dxc4 $2 20. Nc6) 20. Rd1 Qc5 21. Bf1 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5]}) ({A common set-up is} 7... c6 8. O-O b6 {and Bc8 is ready to enter the game.} 9. Ne5 $5 $146 {is very logical:} (9. Bxb4 axb4 10. Nbd2 Ba6 (10... Qe7 $5 11. Ne5 c5 12. Nb3 Bb7 13. Qe3 Na6 $11) (10... Bb7) 11. a3 $1 bxa3 ({better than} 11... Qe7 $6 {in Sadhwani - Vidit, Chess.com INT, 2022, in the view of} 12. axb4 $1 Qxb4 13. Ne5 Bb7 14. Rxa8 Bxa8 15. Nd3 Qe7 16. b4 $16 {[%csl Ra8]}) 12. Rxa3 Nbd7 13. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 (13... Bb7 14. b4 $14) 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. Qc3 $14) 9... Be7 $5 {[%cal Gc8a6] is on the verge of various transpositions to the move orders in the next 3 Chapters. Here is just one sample line -} (9... Bb7 10. Rd1 h6 (10... Nbd7 11. Bxb4 axb4 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nd3 {[%csl Rb4]} Ba6 (13... Qe7 $6 14. Qd2 b3 15. a3 Ne4 16. Qe3 Rfc8 17. Nd2 $16 {[%csl Rb3]}) 14. Nxb4 Bxe2 15. Re1 Ba6 16. Nc6 Qe8 17. Nc3 Bb7 18. Nb4 Qb8 19. Qe3 Qd6 20. a3 $14) 11. b3 $5 (11. Bf4 Nh5) (11. Nc3 Nbd7) 11... Nbd7 12. Bxb4 axb4 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Nd3 Ba6 15. Nxb4 Bxe2 16. Re1 Ba6 17. Nxa6 Rxa6 18. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Gc3b5,Ga2a4]}) ({in case of} 9... Ba6 10. Bxb4 axb4 11. a3 Bb7 {the retreat} 12. Nd3 {makes the difference to the similar line with 10...Ba6 from above. After the forced} bxa3 {White has a promising plan with or without the trade of rooks -} 13. Rxa3 (13. Nxa3 Qe7 14. b4 Nbd7 15. Qb2 $14) 13... Rxa3 14. Nxa3 Qe7 15. b4 Nbd7 16. Qb2 Ra8 17. Rc1 $14) 10. Rd1 Ba6 (10... Nfd7 11. Nxd7 Nxd7 12. e4 Bb7 13. Bf4 $14) 11. Bf4 Nh5 12. Be3 Nf6 13. Nd2 Nfd7 14. Nd3 Nf6 15. b3 Nbd7 16. Nf3 $14) (7... Bxd2+ 8. Nbxd2 b6 {is possible, regarding that White is lacking the b2-b4 push.} 9. O-O Bb7 10. cxd5 (10. Rd1 $5) 10... exd5 11. Nb1 $5 {[%cal Gb1c3]} Nbd7 12. Nc3 Re8 13. Rd1 c6 14. Qc2 $14) (7... b6 8. O-O Ba6 (8... Bb7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bf4 c6 11. a3 Be7 12. Nc3 Nbd7 13. Qc2 $14) 9. Ne5 $5 ({a solid approach is} 9. a3 $5 Bxd2 10. Nbxd2 Qd6 11. Qc2 Nbd7 12. Rfe1 $14 {with 13.e4 next}) 9... Nfd7 $5 {seems reliable:} (9... c5 10. Bxb4 $146 (10. a3 Bxd2 11. Qxd2 Nbd7 12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Nc3 {has taken place in Anton Guijarro - Steinberg, Mayrhofen, 2022, now Black has the forcing} Ne4 $5 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Rfd1 Rad8 17. Bxe4 cxd4 $11) 10... axb4 11. a3 Bb7 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. cxd5 Bxd5 14. Qxc5 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Nbd7 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. Qxb4 Rfb8 18. Qd2 Qb7+ 19. Kg1 Ne4 20. Qc2 Qxb2 21. Qxb2 Rxb2 22. f3 Nd2 (22... Nf6 23. Kf2) 23. Nxd2 Rxd2 24. Kf2 Rd4 25. Rfd1 Rda4 26. Rd3 g5 $14) 10. cxd5 $5 (10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. Bxb4 axb4 12. Nd2 Nc6 13. e3 Ra7 $1 ({a logical idea to exploit the a-file rather than} 13... Na5 14. b3 Bb7 15. Rd1 $14) 14. Rd1 (14. a3 Bb7) 14... Rfa8 15. Qc2 Bb7 16. Qb3 Ra5 17. Rac1 Qd6 18. Nb1 Ba6 19. Bf1 $11) 10... Nxe5 11. dxe6 {is giving rise to immense complications:} Nec6 ({there are a lot of tactical intricacies after} 11... Nbc6 12. Bxb4 axb4 13. dxe5 Nd4 14. exf7+ Rxf7 15. Qe3 $1 Bxe2 (15... Nc2 $2 16. Qe4) 16. Re1 Rf3 $5 (16... Bf3 $2 17. e6 Rf6 18. e7 Qd5 19. Rd1 $18) 17. Qd2 Bb5 18. a4 $1 c5 19. Na3 $1 Ba6 (19... bxa3 $2 20. axb5 $18) (19... Bxa4 20. Nc4) 20. Nb5 Bxb5 21. axb5 Rxg3 $1 22. hxg3 Rxa1 23. Rxa1 Nf3+ 24. Bxf3 Qxd2 25. e6 Kf8 26. Rd1 Qxb2 27. Rd7 Qe5 28. Bd5 (28. e7+ Kf7 29. Bc6 Kf6 30. Kf1 c4 31. e8=Q Qxe8 32. Rd6+ Qe6 33. Rxe6+ Kxe6 $11 {[%csl Gb4,Gc4][%cal Gh7h5,Gg7g5]}) 28... Ke8 29. Bc6 Qxe6 30. Rd6+ Ke7 31. Rxe6+ Kxe6 {Compared to the last subline, Black's c-pawn is still on the 5th rank, but he has little to worry about, e.g.} 32. Kf1 g5 33. Ke2 h5 $11) (11... Qxd4 12. Bxb4 axb4 13. Rd1 Nd3 ({Black does not have time for} 13... Qg4 {because of} 14. e7 $1) 14. exf7+ Rxf7 15. Qe3 Qxe3 16. fxe3 Ra7 17. exd3 $14) 12. Bxc6 Nxc6 13. Qxc6 Qxd4 14. exf7+ {can appear on the board after the abovementioned 11...Nbc6 as well, Black is eliminating Bg2 and can rely on his pair of bishops in the long run, to compensate a missing pawn at least:} Kh8 (14... Kxf7 15. Be3 Qxb2 16. Qd7+ Be7 17. Qd5+ Kg6 18. Qe4+ Kf7 19. Nd2 (19. Qd5+ $11) 19... Bf6 20. Qxh7 Rh8 21. Qf5 Qb5 22. Qxb5 (22. Qf4 Qe5) 22... Bxb5 23. Rac1 Rac8 24. Rfe1 Rhe8 $44) 15. Bc3 Qc5 16. Qxc5 Bxc5 17. Re1 Rxf7 18. e3 Raf8 19. f4 Re7 20. Be5 Rd7 21. Nc3 Rd3 22. Bd4 (22. Kf2 Rd2+) 22... Bxd4 23. exd4 Rd2 $44) 8. O-O c6 ({The main line can be reached via} 8... Nbd7 9. Rd1 ({or} 9. Bf4) 9... c6 10. Bf4 {as well.}) 9. Bf4 ({So is with} 9. Rd1 Nbd7 10. Bf4) ({, while} 9. Nc3 $6 {allows} dxc4 $1 {with questionable compensation for the lost pawn.}) 9... Nbd7 ({In reply to} 9... Nh5 {White will be glad to trade all the long-range pieces, which operate on dark squares, e.g.} 10. Bg5 Bxg5 11. Qxg5 Qxg5 12. Nxg5 Nf6 13. Rc1 $14) 10. Rd1 (10. Nbd2 Nh5 11. Be3 Nhf6 $11) ({The verdict of} 10. Nc3 {is once again depending on} dxc4 $1) 10... a4 $5 ({As said, the possible exchanges after} 10... Nh5 11. Bg5 {are to White's liking:} Nhf6 {is a sensible reaction, to which White can opt for the uncompromising} (11... Bxg5 12. Nxg5 (12. Qxg5 Qxg5 13. Nxg5 Nhf6 14. Nd2 b6 15. Rac1 Ba6 16. Ngf3 $14) 12... Qe7 13. Nf3 Nhf6 14. b3 $14) 12. Nc3 $1 dxc4 (12... h6 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. b3 Rb8 15. e3 $14) 13. Nd2 (13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 $13) 13... Nb6 14. e4 {with ample compensation for the pawn:} a4 $5 {seems to be the critical continuation, when} (14... Qxd4 $2 15. Nf3 Qc5 16. Be3 $18) (14... h6 15. Bf4 (15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. e5 Be7 17. Ne2 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4]}) 15... a4 16. a3 $44 {[%cal Gd2f3]}) 15. e5 Nfd5 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 (16... Qxe7 $6 17. a3 $1 {[%cal Gc3e4]}) 17. Ne2 a3 $1 18. bxa3 (18. b4 cxb3 19. axb3 Nf5 20. Nc4 Nxc4 21. bxc4 f6 $13) 18... Ned5 {may result in an original perpetual at the end of the sharp line} 19. Rb1 f6 20. Ne4 $5 (20. Nxc4 Nxc4 21. Qxc4 Rxa3 $11) 20... fxe5 21. dxe5 Qc7 22. Nd6 Nd7 23. f4 b5 24. Nd4 Nc5 25. f5 Nd3 26. Rxd3 cxd3 27. Qxc6 Qa7 $1 28. N6xb5 Rb8 $1 29. Nxa7 Rxb1+ 30. Kf2 Rb2+ 31. Kg1 Rb1+ $11) (10... b6 11. Ne5 Bb7 {is solid, but also somewhat passive:} 12. Nc3 $5 $146 (12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nc6 Bxc6 (13... Qe8 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 15. Qc7 Ba6 16. Bd6 Qd8 17. Qxd8 Rfxd8 $14) 14. Qxc6 Rc8 15. Qb5 {So far Gelfand - Cheparinov, Warsaw, 2021. Similar situations with a pawn still on the a7-square and small advantage due to the bishops will be analyzed in the next Chapter 4. In this particular case the early advance of the rook's pawn has exposed the light squares to some extent,} Ne8 $14) 12... Nh5 (12... Rc8 $6 13. e4 $16) 13. Nxd7 (13. Be3 Nhf6) 13... Qxd7 14. Bg5 a4 $5 {may once again be Black's best bet -} (14... Ba6 15. cxd5 (15. Na4 $5 Rfb8 16. b3 $14) 15... cxd5 16. e4 dxe4 17. d5 $36) 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Qc2 (16. e4 dxc4 17. e5 f5 18. Bf3 g6 19. Ne2 $44) 16... Qb4 17. b3 $5 (17. cxd5 cxd5 18. a3 Qa5 $11) 17... axb3 18. Qxb3 Qxc4 19. Qxc4 dxc4 20. a4 Nf6 21. Rab1 Ra6 22. e4 $14 {[%cal Gg2f1]}) (10... Ne4 11. Nbd2 ({it is the same story with} 11. Nc3) 11... f5 12. Nxe4 $1 fxe4 13. Ne5 {the new exchanges} Nxe5 (13... Bd6 14. a3 $1 (14. Qe3 Qc7 $13) 14... Qe7 (14... Qc7 $6 15. Qc3) 15. Qe3 $14) 14. Bxe5 Bf6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 {, followed by undermining the central chain by} 16. f3 {can be described as an opening success for White.}) 11. Qc2 $5 {A multifunctional move, the queen joins the battle for the e4-square and keeps an eye on the brave a-pawn.} (11. a3 Ne4 $5) 11... h6 (11... Ne4 12. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Gc3a4]}) (11... b5 12. c5 Ne4 13. Nbd2 g5 (13... f5 14. Nxe4 fxe4 15. Ne5 $14) 14. Nxe4 $1 (14. Be3 f5 $13) 14... dxe4 (14... gxf4 15. Nd6 $16) 15. Ne5 $1 {The subtle point of White's unusual operation - there will be 3 pawns for the piece with every chance for success after} gxf4 16. Nxc6 Qe8 17. Nxe7+ (17. Qxe4 $5 Bg5 18. gxf4 Bh6 19. e3 $13) 17... Qxe7 18. Qxe4 Ra7 19. Qxf4 $14) (11... Nh5 12. Bd2 Nhf6 (12... f5 $6 13. a3 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3]}) 13. a3 $1 h6 (13... Nb6 $6 14. c5 Nc4 15. Bb4 $1 {[%csl Ra4,Gb4][%cal Gb1c3]} b6 16. Nc3 bxc5 17. dxc5 $16) 14. e3 $14 (14. Bb4 $5)) 12. a3 $1 (12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 14. cxd5 (14. Nc3 $2 dxc4 $19 {Predke - Motylev, Sochi, 2021}) 14... exd5 15. e4 Nb6 $132) (12. h4 Nh5 $13) 12... Ne4 $1 {is, besides the Stonewall motifs, aimed at protecting the a4-pawn.} ({An alternative is} 12... b5 {, which is often used for attacking similar c-pawns. The game can continue with} 13. c5 $1 ({White can hardly profit from the c-file, so he should better refrain from} 13. cxb5 cxb5 $132) 13... g5 14. Be3 Ng4 (14... Ne4 $2 15. Ne5) 15. Bd2 f5 (15... e5 16. h3 Nxf2 17. Kxf2 e4 18. Ng1) 16. Nc3 Ngf6 {and the time has come for} 17. b3 axb3 18. Qxb3 {, followed by a timely a3-a4.}) (12... Nh5 13. Bd2 Nhf6 {- 11...Nh5.}) 13. Nc3 (13. Ne5 g5 $5 (13... Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Nf6 $11) 14. Bxe4 gxf4 $13) (13. Ne1 {can also be countered with} g5 14. Bd2 f5 $13) 13... Nxc3 14. Qxc3 (14. bxc3 b5 $5 (14... dxc4 15. Nd2) 15. c5 g5 $132) 14... Nb6 15. Ne5 $5 {The most active option.} ({Here} 15. c5 Nc4 16. e4 {fails to impress in the view of} b6 $1 17. Ne5 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Ba6 $132) (15. Nd2 {is the more cautious way to defend the c-pawn, Black, in order to control the e4-square, can expand by} g5 16. Be3 f5 {with mutual chances -} 17. c5 Nd7 18. Nf3 Bf6 $13 19. Ne5 Bxe5 20. dxe5 Qa5 21. f4 Qxc3 22. bxc3 Ra5 $11) 15... f6 $1 {A remarkable measure against the increasing tension in the centre - Black will get a pawn and positional compensation for the sacrificed exchange.} ({The players can change their roles in case of} 15... Bf6 $6 16. c5 Bxe5 17. dxe5 $1 (17. Bxe5 Nc4 18. Bf4 b6 $11) 17... Nc4 (17... Nd7 18. Rac1 Ra5 19. Be3 Rb5 20. Qd4 $36 {[%csl Gc5,Ge5][%cal Gf2f4]}) 18. Rd4 $1 Qa5 {and now} 19. Rxc4 $5 dxc4 20. Qxc4 $44 {[%cal Gf4h6]} b6 $140 21. Bxh6 $1 Qxc5 (21... gxh6 $2 22. Qg4+ Kh8 23. Qf4 $40 {[%cal Gg2e4]}) 22. Qxc5 bxc5 23. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2c3]} Ba6 24. Bxc6 Rab8 (24... Bxe2 25. Bxa8 Rxa8 26. f4 $14) 25. Bc3 Bxe2 26. Bxa4 $14) 16. Ng6 Nxc4 17. Nxf8 Qxf8 18. e4 b5 $44 19. exd5 (19. Qc2 Bd7 {[%csl Gc4]}) 19... exd5 ({Black is pretty solid after} 19... cxd5 20. Rab1 Bd7 21. Qf3 Rc8 $44 {as well.}) 20. Qc2 Bd7 $11 *

