{[%evp 0,70,20,20,20,2,2,2,2,-26,6,6,6,11,31,26,21,32,29,11,9,9,-5,-29,-29,-32,-36,-36,-47,-8,-4,0,0,-15,18,9,7,-36,-29,-6,-14,-17,-11,-1,15,39,42,14,3,28,23,23,23,36,45,0,13,0,0,0,0,0,1,1,13,16,16,14,14,14,36,26,57]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 c6 (6... dxc4 $6 7. Qa4+ {Black may land in the main Catalan being a tempo (Bc1-d2) down:} Nbd7 (7... c6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. O-O Nbd7 (10... O-O 11. Nc3 Nbd7 {does not differ}) 11. Nc3 (11. a4 $5) 11... O-O 12. Rfd1 Qb6 13. Ne5 $14) (7... Bd7 8. Qxc4 Bc6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 $14) 8. Qxc4 O-O 9. O-O c5 10. dxc5 ({it makes sense to clear the central files, although} 10. Rd1 $14 {is playable as well}) 10... Nxc5 11. Ne5 (11. Be3 $14) 11... Nd5 12. Rc1 $14) (6... Ne4 $6 7. Bf4 Nd7 8. Qc2 c6 9. Nbd2 ({equally good is} 9. Nc3 f5 10. O-O) 9... f5 10. Ne5 $5 Nxe5 (10... O-O 11. Nxe4 fxe4 12. O-O {will transpose}) 11. Bxe5 O-O 12. Nxe4 fxe4 13. O-O Bd6 14. Bxd6 (14. f4 $14) 14... Qxd6 15. Qc3 Bd7 16. c5 Qe7 17. f3 exf3 18. exf3 $14) ({The ensuing lines after} 6... Nbd7 {are about to transpose to the next Chapters, e.g.} 7. Qc2 c6 ({or} 7... O-O 8. O-O) 8. Bf4 O-O (8... b6 $2 9. cxd5 $16 {[%cal Gf4c7]}) 9. O-O {etc.}) 7. Qc2 b6 $5 8. Bf4 Bb7 (8... O-O 9. O-O {is once again of no independent significance}) (8... Ba6 $2 {is a tactical blunder -} 9. cxd5 $16 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gc2a4,Gf4b8]}) 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rd1 (10. Nbd2 c5 $1 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Ne5 O-O $11) 10... O-O ({Besides the natural textmove, Black can fulfil his plan of mobilizing the queenside before castling by means of} 10... Rc8 $5 {, which might bring originality:} 11. Ne5 $5 (11. Nc3 dxc4 $1 (11... O-O 12. Ne5 {goes to the main line with 10...0-0}) 12. Ne5 {(d2)} (12. Qa4 b5 13. Qxa7 Qb6 14. Qxb6 Nxb6 15. Rdc1 (15. a4 b4 16. Nb1 Ba6 $13) 15... b4 16. Nd1 c5 (16... Ba6 $5) 17. Nd2 Bxg2 18. dxc5 Rxc5 19. Kxg2 Rc6 20. Be3 Nfd7 21. a4 bxa3 22. bxa3 Bf6 23. Ra2 Ke7 $11 {Brunsteins - Salcedo Mederos, ICCF email, 2019}) 12... Nd5 13. Nxc4 Nxf4 14. gxf4 O-O (14... Qc7 15. e3 {is practically arriving at the same tabiya}) 15. e3 Qc7 $11 {[%cal Gf8d8] The readers will find in Chapter 8 exemplary variations for the same position with h7-h6 instead of Ra8-c8 on the board}) 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 (12... Ng4 $2 13. h3 g5 14. hxg4 gxf4 15. gxf4 Bc5 16. e3 Qh4 17. Qe2 Rg8 18. Bf3 $16) 13. Nc3 g5 (13... b5 $5 14. cxb5 cxb5 15. a3 {[%cal Ge2e4]}) 14. Be3 O-O ({the idea behind Black's previous move is to prevent the central push rather than grabbing material by} 14... Nxe5 $6 {After} 15. Bd4 {White has the initiative, as the following lines confirm -} Bf6 (15... Qc7 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. e4 dxe4 18. Bxe4 Bxe4 19. Qxe4 f6 20. Rac1 Qb8 21. h4 gxh4 22. f4 Rg8 23. Ne2 Rxc1 24. Rxc1 Nd7 25. Qxe6 Rg6 26. Qh3 $16 {[%cal Gh3h4]}) 16. Ne4 c5 ({a very entertaining branch is} 16... Bg7 17. f4 gxf4 18. gxf4 f5 19. Ng5 Qe7 20. Qc3 Ng6 21. Bxg7 Nxf4 22. Kh1 Rg8 23. Bf6 d4 24. Qxd4 c5 25. Qe5 Bxg2+ 26. Kg1 Nh3+ 27. Kxg2 Nxg5 28. Bxe7 Nf7+ 29. Qg3 Kxe7 30. Rg1 Kf6 31. Rad1 $16) 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Bc3 d4 19. Bxb7 Rb8 20. Bxd4 cxd4 21. Qe4 Rd8 22. Rac1 $16) 15. Bd4 f6 (15... c5 $2 16. Be3 $18 {[%cal Gg2b7]}) 16. exf6 (16. Bh3 f5 $13) 16... Bxf6 17. Qd2 $1 e5 ({in case of} 17... Bxd4 18. Qxd4 Qf6 19. Qxf6 Nxf6 {White can finally unleash} 20. e4 $14) 18. Be3 d4 19. Ne4 h6 20. Qd3 $1 ({instead, after} 20. Nd6 Qc7 21. Qd3 {the game will finish in perpetual -} Qxd6 22. Qg6+ $11) 20... Qe7 21. Bd2 $14) 11. Ne5 Nh5 $1 {The right moment for this jump in order to harass the annoying Bf4.} (11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. cxd5 {is venomous for Black:} cxd5 (13... exd5 14. e4 ({the most consistent move; as a rule, an exciting line like} 14. Nc3 g5 15. Qf5 gxf4 16. Be4 dxe4 17. Qxd7 {is leading to liquidation to an equal ending, e.g.} Qxd7 18. Rxd7 Bb4 19. Rxb7 Bxc3 20. bxc3 fxg3 21. hxg3 Rfb8 22. Rd7 Rd8 23. Rad1 Rxd7 24. Rxd7 Re8 $11) (14. h4 Nc5 15. Nc3 Qd7 $11) 14... d4 15. Rxd4 Bc5 16. Rd2 Qe7 17. e6 $5 $146 {is a fresh and dangerous idea, for example} (17. Nc3 Nxe5 18. Rad1 g5 $5 (18... Bc8 19. h3 $14) 19. Bxe5 Qxe5 20. Bh3 (20. h3 Rfe8 $13) 20... Be7 21. Bf5 {Papaioannou - Gelfand, Batumi, 2018, looks tempting, but Black can confidently play} Rfd8 $1 22. Kg2 h6 $11) 17... Qxe6 (17... fxe6 18. Na3 $1 {[%cal Ga3c4]} Nf6 19. Nc4 Rad8 20. Ne5 Rxd2 21. Qxd2 Rd8 22. Qe2 $14) 18. Nc3 Ne5 19. Rad1 f6 {(Black is deprived of the g7-g5 resource!)} 20. Na4 $1 Be7 ({Black has hardly anything better than this retreat after} 20... Bb4 21. Rd4) 21. Bxe5 fxe5 22. Rd7 Bc8 23. Rc7 $36) 14. e4 {Here too, opening the centre is the most testing continuation:} dxe4 (14... Rc8 $6 15. Nc3 dxe4 (15... d4 16. Rxd4 Qc7 17. Qe2 $1 Nxe5 (17... a6 18. Nd5 $1 exd5 19. exd5 $16 {[%cal Gd5d6]}) 18. Nb5 Qb8 19. Nxa7 $16) 16. Bxe4 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Qe8 18. Nb5 Nc5 19. Qe2 $16) (14... g5 {is a courageous, albeit not sufficient try to solve the opening problems:} 15. Be3 (15. exd5 $5 gxf4 16. dxe6 fxe6 (16... Bxg2 17. Rxd7 $16) 17. Bxb7 fxg3 18. fxg3 Bc5+ 19. Kh1 Rb8 20. Bg2 Qe7 21. Nc3 Nxe5 22. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gc3e4]}) 15... Qc8 ({a reasonable idea to trade the queens; more than risky is} 15... Nxe5 $6 16. exd5 exd5 17. Nc3 $16) 16. Qxc8 Rfxc8 17. exd5 Nxe5 18. Nc3 $14) 15. Bxe4 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Nc5 (16... Qc7 17. Nc3 $14) 17. Qf3 $1 (17. Qe2 Qc7) 17... Qe8 (17... Qc7 18. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Gc3b5]}) 18. Nc3 Rc8 (18... Na4 $6 {Giri - Kramnik, Dortmund, 2011, is dubious in the view of} 19. Ne4 $1 Nxb2 20. Rd4 $40) 19. Rd4 $14) (11... b5 12. Nxd7 (12. c5 {is likely to transpose after both 12...g5 and 12...Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Nd7}) 12... Nxd7 13. c5 g5 (13... e5 {is interesting, but Black's compensation after} 14. Bxe5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Qc7 16. f4 $16 {is arguable}) (13... f5 14. a4 b4 15. a5 $16) 14. Bd2 f5 15. a4 a6 16. e3 $14) ({the insertion of} 11... Rc8 12. Nc3 {before} Nh5 {is enabling White for concrete actions, for example} (12... Nxe5 $6 13. dxe5 Nd7 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. e4 $16 {is back to 11...Nxe5?!}) 13. Bc1 Nhf6 (13... f5 {is best challenged with the surprising sally} 14. Qa4 $5 $36 {[%csl Ra7,Rd7][%cal Ga4a7,Ga4d7]}) (13... Qc7 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. e4 $16) 14. e4 dxc4 15. Nxc4 b5 16. Ne3 Qb6 17. b3 (17. a4 $5) 17... Rfe8 18. a4 $1 (18. Bb2 Bf8) 18... a6 19. Bb2 Bf8 20. a5 $1 Qc7 21. e5 Nd5 22. Ncxd5 cxd5 23. Qd2 $16) ({in reply to} 11... h6 12. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4]} g5 {White has the important intermezzo} 13. cxd5 $1 cxd5 (13... Nxd5 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. Bd2 $14) 14. Be3 Rc8 15. Rac1 $14) 12. Bd2 ({The delayed development of Nb1 is providing White with an extra possibility to support the other knight in comparison to} 12. Bc1 Nhf6 {, see the next note.}) 12... Nhf6 {Equivalent to a draw offer, but the alternatives are failing to impress:} (12... Bd6 $6 13. Bc3 Nhf6 (13... Qc7 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. e4 $16) (13... f5 14. Nd2 $14) 14. Nd2 Rc8 (14... Qc7 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 16. e4 $16) 15. Nxd7 (15. e4 $5) 15... Qxd7 16. e4 dxe4 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 h6 19. c5 Be7 20. Qe2 Qc7 21. b4 $16 {Cheparinov - Sethuraman, Berlin, 2015}) (12... Rc8 13. Nc3 (13. e4 c5 $1) 13... Nhf6 (13... c5 $2 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Qa4 $16) 14. Bf4 {- 11...Rc8}) ({Black's center is under crossfire after} 12... c5 $6 13. cxd5 (13. Qa4 $5 Nhf6 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Qxd7 Nxd7 17. Nc3 cxd4 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Bxd5 Rac8 20. Rac1 Nc5 21. Kf1 $16) 13... exd5 14. Be3 $1 Nhf6 (14... Rc8 15. Nc3 $16) 15. Nc3 cxd4 (15... Rc8 16. Rac1 $16) 16. Bxd4 Nc5 17. Nc4 $1 dxc4 18. Bxb7 Nxb7 19. Bxf6 Qe8 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. Qa4 Na5 (21... Qe6 22. Rd4) 22. Rd7 Qe6 23. Rad1 $18 {Cheparinov- J. Zhao, Doha, 2014.}) 13. cxd5 cxd5 ({Black will find himself in a cramped position after} 13... Nxe5 $2 {by force -} 14. dxe5 Nxd5 15. e4 Nc7 16. Bb4 $1 {(a neat point!)} Qe8 (16... Bxb4 17. Rxd8 Rfxd8 18. Nc3 $16) 17. Bd6 Na6 (17... Rc8 18. Nc3 $16) 18. a3 c5 19. Nc3 $16) 14. Nc6 Bxc6 {Black can also part with the other bishop:} (14... Rc8 15. Nxe7+ ({the alternative} 15. Nxd8 Rxc2 16. Nxb7 Rb8 {looks great for Black}) 15... Qxe7 16. Qb3 {[%cal Gd2b4]} a5 {it is better to exert pressure by the patient} (16... Rfd8 17. Bb4 Qe8 18. Qa3 {[%cal Gb4e7,Ga3a7]} Ra8 19. Nc3 $14) 17. Na3 $5 ({there is certain compensation after} 17. Bxa5 bxa5 18. Qxb7 Rb8 19. Qa6 Rxb2 ({or} 19... Qb4 $5 20. b3 Rfc8 21. Qd3 a4) 20. Qxa5 Nb6 $44) 17... Ba6 18. Nb5 Rc4 19. e3 Rfc8 {and now} 20. Qa3 (20. Bf1 Ne4 $1) 20... Qxa3 21. Nxa3 R4c7 22. f3 $14) (14... Qe8 {is the other, but probably inferior alternative:} 15. Bf4 $5 $146 {is both activating the own bishop and preventing Be7-d6, White is prepared to obtain the advantage of pair of bishops under the most favourable circumstances:} (15. Rc1 {allows} Bd6) (15. Nxe7+ {looks premature -} Qxe7 16. Nc3 (16. Qc7 $143 Ba6) 16... Rfc8) 15... Nh5 {is chasing the bishop, but White gets enough time to rearrange his forces -} (15... Rc8 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Qa4 {with the usual lasting edge in the long run -} a5 (17... a6 18. Qa3) 18. Qa3 Qxa3 19. Nxa3 Ba6 20. Bf1 $14) (15... Ne4 16. Nc3 Nxc3 ({of course,} 16... Bxc6 $6 17. Nxe4 {cannot be recommended}) 17. Nxe7+ Qxe7 18. Qxc3 Rfc8 19. Qb3 Nf6 20. Rac1 $14) 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Be3 Rfc8 18. Nc3 Nhf6 19. Rdc1 h6 (19... Ne4 20. Qb3) 20. f3 $14 {[%cal Gc2d2]}) 15. Qxc6 Rc8 {The situation has been determined - the game is entering a complex strategical phase, Black has to take measures against Bg2, which has just left without a counterpart:} (15... Qb8 16. Rc1 $5 (16. Qb5 a6 17. Qd3 b5 {[%cal Gd7b6]}) 16... Rc8 17. Qxc8+ Qxc8 18. Rxc8+ Rxc8 19. Nc3 Ne8 20. e3 Nd6 21. Rc1 Kf8 (21... Nc4 22. Ne2) 22. Bf1 Nb8 23. Bd3 $14) (15... a6 {is a clever attempt at covering the weakened complex of light squares on the queenside -} 16. e3 ({or the mass exchanges after} 16. Rc1 Rc8 17. Qxc8 Qxc8 18. Rxc8 Rxc8 19. Nc3 b5 20. Rc1 {with small pull for White -} Nb6 {[%cal Gb6c4]} 21. Nd1 Rxc1 22. Bxc1 $14) 16... b5 (16... Rc8 17. Qa4 {[%csl Ra6]} Nb8 18. Qb3 $14) 17. Rc1 Qb8 (17... b4 18. Be1 {[%cal Gb1d2]}) 18. Bf1 (18. Ba5 {seems to lead to nowhere -} Rc8 19. Qxc8+ Qxc8 20. Rxc8+ Rxc8 21. Nc3 (21. Nd2 {is countered by} Rc2) 21... Bd8 $11 {Cuenca Jimenez - Kuzubov, Ovar, 2022}) 18... Nb6 (18... Rc8 $6 19. Qxc8+ Qxc8 20. Rxc8+ Rxc8 21. a4 $14 {reveals the huge difference between 18.Ba5 and 18.Bf1!}) 19. Qc7 Bd6 20. Qxb8 Rfxb8 21. Rc6 Be7 22. Be1 $14) (15... Qc8 {may well be Black's best:} 16. Qxc8 (16. Qb5 {is exposing the queen to the useful expansion} a6 17. Qd3 b5 18. Rc1 (18. e3 $5 Nb6 19. b3) 18... Qb7 19. Be1 {[%cal Gb1d2]} Rfc8 20. Nd2 Nb6 $11) 16... Rfxc8 17. Nc3 a6 {and White can put his hopes on the pair of bishops by playing} 18. e4 dxe4 19. Nxe4 Nd5 20. Nc3 (20. Rdc1 N7f6) 20... N7f6 21. Rdc1 Kf8 22. Kf1 $14 {[%cal Gf1e2]}) 16. Qb5 (16. Qa4 $143 Rc4 17. Qxa7 Rxd4 18. Nc3 Rc4 $11) 16... Ne8 {[%cal Ge8d6] A logical manoeuvre, the alternatives are not that impressive:} (16... Nb8 17. e3 ({White can begin with} 17. Be1 {, which is anyway a part of the intended set-up}) 17... Ne8 (17... Nc6 18. Be1) 18. Be1 Nd6 19. Qe2 Nc6 20. Nc3 Qd7 21. Rac1 $14) ({Here} 16... Rc4 {seems just to help White's plan after the simple} 17. e3 {[%cal Gg2f1]}) (16... Ne4 $6 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Nc3 Nf6 19. Qa4 $16) 17. Qd3 Nd6 (17... Ndf6 $5 18. Be1 Nd6 19. e3 Qd7 20. Nd2 $14) 18. b3 ({It makes sense to take the c4-square under control, also possible is} 18. Nc3 Nc4 19. Bc1 Bb4 (19... Nf6 20. b3 Nd6 21. Bd2 {would transpose to the main line}) 20. e4 Bxc3 21. bxc3 dxe4 22. Bxe4 Nf6 23. Bb7 Rc7 24. Ba6 Qd5 25. Rb1 $14 {[%cal Gc1f4] Cheparinov - So, Kocaeli, 2015}) 18... Nf6 (18... f5 19. f3 Nb8 20. Nc3 Nc6 21. e3 Bf6 22. Ne2 Qd7 23. Rac1 Rc7 {took place in Caruana - Adams, Baden-Baden 2013, when} 24. Rc2 Rfc8 25. Rdc1 $14 {was the logical follow-up.}) (18... Nb8 19. Nc3 Nc6 20. e3 $14 {[%cal Gd2e1]}) 19. Nc3 Qd7 20. f3 $5 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Nf5 ({The correspondence tournament practice has seen} 20... Rfd8 21. e4 dxe4 22. fxe4 Nb7 {[%cal Gd7d4,Gb7c5]} (22... Nde8 23. Bf4 $14) 23. Bf4 {and now:} Bb4 (23... Na5 24. e5 Bb4 {The first try, a later game has proved that Black would have better started with this move.} 25. Ne2 Nd5 26. Bg5 Be7 {So far A. Perez Lopez - G. Menendez Rodriguez, ICCF email, 2017, here worth of attention is} 27. Bxd5 Bxg5 (27... exd5 28. Bxe7 Qxe7 29. Nf4 $14) 28. Be4 g6 29. h4 Bh6 30. Kg2 $14) 24. Ne2 (24. Nb5 a6 25. Na7 Ra8 26. Qxa6 Bc3 27. Qxb6 Bxa1 28. Rxa1 Qxd4+ 29. Qxd4 Rxd4 30. Nc6 Rd7 $13) 24... Nc5 25. Qe3 e5 $1 26. Bxe5 Ng4 27. Qf4 h5 $1 28. d5 Nxe5 29. Qxe5 Qg4 30. Nf4 h4 31. Qh5 Qxh5 32. Nxh5 Re8 33. Rac1 Rcd8 34. Rc4 a5 35. gxh4 b5 36. Rc2 (36. Rcd4 Bc3) 36... Nxe4 $11 {Gavrijski - Peiro Aparisi, ICCF email, 2021.}) 21. e3 Rfd8 ({Or} 21... h5 22. Ne2 {and Black may consider doubling of the rooks.}) 22. Ne2 h5 (22... a5 23. a4) (22... Qc7 $6 23. Rac1 Qd7 24. Rxc8 Qxc8 25. Rc1 Qd7 26. a4 Ba3 27. Rc2 a5 28. Qa6 Rb8 29. Nf4 $14 {is an example of a success of White's strategy, Caruana - Yu Yangyi Tromsoe, 2013.}) 23. Rf1 $5 {[%cal Ga1d1]} Ba3 24. b4 Qa4 25. Nc3 Qd7 {A repetition of moves is already in the air, White has preferred to continue on with} 26. Rfb1 Nd6 27. Nd1 Nc4 28. Be1 a6 29. Kh1 Qa4 30. Bf1 {So far Velilla Velasco - Hoeven, ICCF email, 2016, when Black has also} a5 $5 31. bxa5 $140 (31. Qb3 Qc6 {will most probably transpose}) 31... bxa5 32. Qb3 Qc6 33. Bxa5 Nxa5 34. Qxa3 Nc4 35. Qd3 Qa4 $44 *

