{[%evp 0,25,20,20,19,2,2,2,15,-7,6,6,6,30,-7,0,37,25,25,26,16,16,15,38,26,40,38,26]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O c5 ({The main debate after} 7... dxc4 {is whether White will make use of the extra Bc1-d2 move:} 8. Qa4 $1 (8. Qc2 {is the inferior way to recapture the pawn in the view of} b5 9. Ne5 ({in case of} 9. a4 b4 {neither of the knights has access to the d2-square}) 9... Nd5 $13) 8... c5 (8... a6 $6 9. Qxc4 b5 10. Qc2 Bb7 {and the tempo up is telling -} 11. Rc1 $16) (8... Bd7 $142 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Nc3 $14) 9. dxc5 Nbd7 10. Qxc4 Nxc5 {[%emt 0:00:04] tranposes to Chapter}) (7... Ne4 8. Qc2 Nd7 {[%emt 0:00:07] will be examined in Chapter 7.}) (7... Nc6 $6 {seems dubious, as} 8. Qc2 {poses certain problems: too artificial is} Ne4 (8... dxc4 9. Qxc4 Qd5 10. Rc1 $5 (10. Qd3 Qf5 11. Qxf5 exf5 {strongly resembles the famous Romanishin's concept in the Nimzo-Indian, but here Black will have still to improve Nc6 after} 12. Rc1 Rd8 13. e3 Be6 14. Nc3 $14) 10... Rd8 11. e3 Qxc4 12. Rxc4 Bd6 13. Rc1 $14) 9. Rd1 Nd6 (9... Nxd2 $6 10. Nbxd2 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4,Ga1c1]}) (9... a5 10. Be1 Nb4 11. Qc1 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3]}) 10. b3 a5 11. Be1 $14 {and it is White, who has successfully regrouped.}) (7... b6 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. Bf4 {[%emt 0:00:01] has been covered in the 1st Part of our Catalan.}) ({Black's set-ups with} 7... a5 8. Qc2 c6 {will be the subjects of the next Chapters.}) 8. dxc5 $1 {White has a good reason to deviate from the position of Tarrasch type after} (8. cxd5 exd5 ({the trade of all c- and d-pawns} 8... cxd4 $6 9. Nxd4 Nxd5 10. Nc3 $16 {can only enhance the difficulties in front of Black}) 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. dxc5 Bxc5 $14) 8... Bxc5 (8... dxc4 $6 9. Na3 Bxc5 10. Nxc4 $16 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gf3e5] with yet another dream Catalan for White.}) 9. Qc2 $1 {A subtle move, pointing at the shaky location of Bc5.} Nc6 (9... Be7 10. cxd5 exd5 (10... Nxd5 11. Rd1 Nc6 12. Nc3 $16) 11. Nc3 Nc6 12. Rad1 h6 13. Bf4 $16) ({in reply to the other retreat} 9... Bb6 10. Nc3 {is preparing an unpleasant pin of Nf6, while} d4 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 $16 {leads to a fine reversed Benoni for White with mobile queenside majority against a strangely placed Bb6}) ({as before,} 9... dxc4 {is not the solution -} 10. Qxc4 Qe7 11. Nc3 Nbd7 12. Rac1 $16) ({similarly to 9...Be7,} 9... Nbd7 {is met by} 10. cxd5 exd5 (10... Nxd5 $6 11. Ng5 N5f6 12. Nc3 $16) 11. Nc3 {with a promising Tarrasch version, for instance} Nb6 12. Rad1 $16) 10. cxd5 Qxd5 11. Nc3 ({A natural developing move,} 11. Bf4 $5 {is also worth a try.}) 11... Qf5 12. Qxf5 exf5 13. Rac1 $14 {The queens are gone, but Black has still a lot of work to do for defending and mobilizing his queenside.} *

