{[%evp 0,55,19,19,19,2,13,15,7,-7,6,14,13,0,0,0,24,24,18,7,9,-8,14,12,23,23,23,-2,23,25,23,29,30,6,10,16,66,45,24,20,13,21,54,52,47,47,23,25,50,50,49,-6,11,16,10,12,8,8]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Qc2 b6 (8... a5 9. Rd1 Nbd7 10. Bf4 {transposes to Chapter 9.}) ({Details about} 8... Ne4 9. Be3 (9. Ne5 $5) 9... Nd7 {can be found in the next Chapter 7.}) 9. Bf4 Ba6 (9... Bb7 10. Ne5 (10. Nbd2 Nh5) 10... Nbd7 11. Rd1 {leads us back to Chapter 4.}) 10. cxd5 $5 {An ambitious idea to exploit the c-file.} ({The calmer} 10. Nbd2 Nbd7 {is given in Chapter 11.}) 10... cxd5 ({Otherwise, in case of} 10... Nxd5 11. Nc3 Nxf4 12. gxf4 {the c6-pawn remains a long-term source of concern, which seems to be not fully compensated by the pair of bishops:} Nd7 (12... Bb7 13. Ne5 f6 14. Nd3 Na6 (14... Qxd4 $6 15. Qb3 Qd7 16. Rfd1 $16) 15. e3 Qd7 16. Qb3 Kh8 17. Rfd1 $14) 13. Rac1 Bb7 14. Rfd1 $14 {[%cal Gf3e5]}) 11. Rc1 Nbd7 {The most popular continuation.} (11... Bd6 12. Ne5 (12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Bf1 $14) 12... Nh5 (12... Bb7 13. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5]}) 13. Bd2 $5 {is a probable improvement:} (13. Be3 Nd7 14. Qa4 {is leading to a complex position after} Nxe5 15. dxe5 (15. Qxa6 Ng4 $132) 15... Bxe5 16. Qxa6 Bxb2 17. Na3 Qe7 18. Nb5 Bxa1 19. Rxa1 Rfc8 $13) 13... Bxe2 (13... Nd7 14. Qa4 $1 Nxe5 15. Qxa6 $1 Ng4 ({the point behind White's move 13 is revealed - now there is no target after this jump, while} 15... Nc4 {will lose a pawn to} 16. Rxc4 $1 dxc4 17. Bxa8 Qxa8 18. Qxc4 $16) 16. Nc3 f5 17. e3 $16) 14. Nc3 Ba6 15. a4 {and the queenside pressure seems to compensate the sacrificed pawn -} Nf6 16. Nb5 Bxb5 17. axb5 $36) (11... Nh5 12. Bc7 Qe8 13. a4 Nf6 14. Na3 Nbd7 15. Nb5 Qc8 16. Qd1 $14 {[%cal Gc7d6,Gb5d6]}) 12. Nc3 Nh5 {Questioning the annoying bishop at once, Black has also tried:} (12... Bb4 13. Bf1 Rc8 (13... Qe7 $6 14. Qa4 Bb7 15. a3 $16) 14. Qb3 Qe7 (14... Bxc3 15. Rxc3 Rxc3 16. Qxc3 Qa8 17. Qa3 $14) 15. Qa4 $1 Bc4 {and now} 16. Nb5 {is unpleasant to meet:} Bxb5 (16... Ne4 $2 {in Dubov - Aronian, chess24.com INT, 2020, could have been refuted by} 17. Nxa7 $1 {with big material and positional advantage after} Ra8 18. b3 Bc3 (18... Nc3 19. Nc6 $1 Nxa4 20. Nxe7+ Bxe7 21. bxc4 $16) 19. bxc4 Bxa1 20. Rxa1 $16) 17. Qxb5 Bd6 18. Qa6 $1 {(securing the control over the c-file)} Rxc1 19. Rxc1 Bxf4 20. gxf4 Nb8 21. Qa4 {with a stable edge -} Ne4 22. e3 $14) (12... Bb7 $6 13. Nb5 Ne4 14. Qc7 Ba6 15. a4 $16) (12... Qc8 $6 {has been put under a cloud by the inspired tactical idea} 13. Qd1 $1 Qb7 14. e4 $1 Nxe4 (14... dxe4 15. Ng5 $16) 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Nd2 (16. Rc7 Qd5) 16... Bd3 17. Rc3 $1 Qa6 {and, although Black survived in Vitiugov - Yu Yangyi, Wijk aan Zee, 2020, he would have found himself in serious trouble after the consistent} 18. Rc7 $1 Rfd8 19. Rac1 Rac8 $140 20. Nxe4 Bxe4 21. Bxe4 Rxc7 22. Rxc7 Qxa2 23. Qc2 $16) ({Another top Chinese player was less lucky with} 12... b5 {and the vigorous} 13. a4 $1 Qb6 (13... b4 $6 14. Nb5 Qb6 15. Bf1 $16) 14. axb5 Bxb5 15. Nxb5 Qxb5 16. Bf1 a5 17. e3 Qb7 18. Qc6 Qxc6 19. Rxc6 $16 {Gelfand - Wang Hao, London, 2012.}) 13. Qa4 ({Both} 13. Bd2 Nhf6) ({and} 13. Be5 Nhf6 {may result in draws by repetition}) (13. e3 $5 Rc8 (13... Nxf4 14. exf4 $14) 14. Qa4 Bb7 15. h4 ({a necessary precaution against the imminent g7-g5; instead, the greedy} 15. Qxa7 $2 {is going to drop material after} Bc6 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gc8a8]}) 15... a6 16. Qd1 h6 17. Bh3 $14) 13... Nxf4 ({The seemingly obvious} 13... Bb7 $2 {is nicely refuted by} 14. Bc7 $1 Qxc7 (14... Qe8 15. Nb5 $16) 15. Nxd5 Qd8 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Rc7 $16 {, regaining the piece with interest.}) 14. Qxa6 Nxg2 15. Kxg2 Qc8 16. Qxc8 Rfxc8 17. Nb5 Rc4 ({In case of} 17... g5 {White is securing the nice b5-square for the knight or winning the fight for the c-file with the help of the little move} 18. a3 $1 {and favourable endgame after} Rxc1 19. Rxc1 a6 20. Rc7 axb5 21. Rxd7 Bf6 22. Rd6 g4 23. Ne5 Bxe5 24. dxe5 Ra6 $14) 18. Rxc4 dxc4 19. Rc1 a6 20. Nc7 Rc8 21. Nxa6 b5 22. a3 Rc6 23. Nb4 Bxb4 24. axb4 Ra6 {The forced sequence has ended, White can counter the intended penetration by bringing the rook to the a-file himself.} 25. Rc3 Nf6 (25... Kf8 {will be met by the same} 26. Ra3 {and, even though the protected passed pawn is helping Black to stay in the game, Nf3 can be smoothly directed to the excellent blockading c3-square. The textmove is aimed against this manoeuvre.}) 26. Ra3 Rxa3 27. bxa3 Ne4 28. Ne1 $14 *

