{[%evp 0,37,25,19,19,7,7,7,7,-19,13,12,12,0,0,-1,19,24,29,19,55,20,50,31,18,-3,30,28,33,29,61,57,61,78,87,113,81,73,106,68]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Qc2 Ne4 9. Be3 $5 (9. Bf4 c6 {will be the subject of the next Chapter.}) 9... c6 (9... f5 10. Nbd2 c6 {is just a reversed order of the text moves.}) 10. Nbd2 {White can also choose one of the other natural developing moves like} (10. Rd1) ({or} 10. Nc3) 10... f5 {The logical consequence of Black's move 8.} (10... Nd6 11. Bf4 $14) 11. Ne1 $5 {[%cal Gd2f3,Ge1d3] The standard regrouping of the knights against the Stonewall.} (11. Rad1 $14) 11... Ndf6 {The drawback of this move is evident - the e5-square is left without any control.} (11... Bf6 12. Ndf3 $14) 12. Ndf3 dxc4 {This is the concrete idea, which can justify Black's previous move.} (12... b6 $6 13. Ne5 Bb7 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. N1d3 $16 {[%cal Gd3f4]}) (12... Ng4 13. Bf4 g5 14. Bc1 $16 {[%cal Ge1d3]}) 13. Ne5 $5 {An adequate reaction against the intended jump on the d5-square.} ({White is fine after the simple} 13. Qxc4 {as well -} Nd5 14. Rd1 $14) 13... b5 14. Nxc6 Qd7 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. a4 Qe8 17. axb5 Qxb5 18. Bxe4 $5 ({A plausible alternative is} 18. Bf4 Nd5 19. Bxe4 fxe4 20. Bd6 Rf7 21. Ng2 $14) 18... Nxe4 (18... fxe4 19. Ng2 {may transpose to the previous note.}) 19. Ng2 $14 {[%cal Gf2f3]} *

