{[%evp 0,41,23,19,33,7,7,15,15,-7,12,12,12,0,-9,-4,24,14,14,9,48,38,33,25,47,50,40,13,81,25,79,45,80,68,74,8,2,-2,7,-33,17,-27,-22,-69]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Qc2 c6 9. Bf4 Ne4 ({A decision like} 9... dxc4 10. Qxc4 {must be quickly justified by Black, since, contrary to the relevant variation in the Slav with 4.Qc2, Bc8 has not entered the game yet: The moves} Nd5 ({Black can play} 10... Qb6 11. Qc2 {before} Nd5 12. Bd2 c5 13. dxc5 (13. e4 Nb4) 13... Qxc5 (13... Nxc5 14. Nc3 Nxc3 (14... Nb4 15. Qb1 $16 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gf1d1]}) 15. Bxc3 Bd7 16. Ne5 Be8 17. Rac1 $36) 14. Nc3 N7b6 15. Rfc1 Nxc3 16. Bxc3 Nd5 17. Bd4 Qxc2 18. Rxc2 {with typical Catalan pressure due to the powerful Bg2 -} Rd8 (18... Bd7 $2 19. e4 $1 Nb6 20. Rc7 Bd8 21. Bxb6 Be8 22. Ba5 b6 23. Bxb6 axb6 24. Rcc1 $16) 19. Ne5 $1 f6 (19... Nb4 20. Rc7 Bd6 21. Rc4 $14) 20. Nd3 Kf7 21. Bc5 (21. Rac1 Bd7 22. Bxd5 exd5 23. Bc5 Re8 $14) 21... Bxc5 22. Rxc5 b6 23. Rc6 Rd7 24. Rac1 Bb7 25. Bxd5 exd5 26. Rc7 Rad8 27. Kf1 $14) 11. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gb1c3]} (11. Nc3 Nxf4 12. gxf4 Nb6 13. Qb3 Nd5 14. e3 f6 $13) 11... c5 {can be also executed at once.} (11... b6 $2 12. Qxc6 Ba6 13. Re1 $16 {does not promise enough compensation, Lazavik - Kravtsiv, Chess.com INT, 2022}) 12. Nc3 $1 {White must not exchange pawns himself, while such developing move is both natural and useful in the fight for the central squares:} (12. e4 b5 $1 13. Qe2 (13. Qxb5 Rb8 $44) 13... N5f6 14. dxc5 Nxc5 {and Black seems in good shape -} 15. Rd1 Qb6 16. e5 Nd5 17. Nc3 Nxc3 18. Bxc3 Bb7 $11) 12... N7b6 (12... N5b6 13. Qd3 cxd4 14. Qxd4 Nf6 15. Rfd1 Qxd4 16. Nxd4 Rd8 (16... Nc4 17. Bc1 Rd8 18. b3 Nb6 19. Bb2 $14) 17. Ndb5 Bd7 18. Be1 $14) 13. Qb3 cxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxc3 (14... Bf6 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Nf3 $14) ({even} 14... a5 15. Rfd1 a4 16. Qc2 Bd7 {does not solve all the problems in the view of the cool} 17. a3 Rc8 18. Qd3 $14) 15. Bxc3 Nd5 (15... e5 16. Nf3 Be6 17. Qc2 f6 18. Nh4 $1 Qc8 19. Rac1 Rf7 20. Qb1 $14 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gg2e4]}) 16. Nf5 $1 Nxc3 17. Nxe7+ Qxe7 18. Qxc3 e5 19. Rac1 $14) (9... h6 10. Rd1 b6 (10... a5 {transposes to next Chapter}) 11. Nc3 (11. Ne5 $5) 11... dxc4 (11... Ba6 $6 {is precarious, for} 12. Ne5 Rc8 13. Qa4 {forces Black to the awkward} Nb8 {Even more,} 14. cxd5 {will practically make him take with the knight, because} cxd5 $6 {is going to be penalized by} 15. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 16. Bxb8 Bxe2 17. Nxe2 Rxb8 18. Qxa7 $16) (11... Bb7 12. Ne5 (12. b3 $5) 12... g5 (12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. e4 $1 {is destroying the centre. No wonder that the tectics are working in White's favour -} d4 16. Rxd4 Bc5 17. Rd2 (17. Rd3 Ba6 18. Rd2 g5 19. Qa4 Bc8 {will transpose to the line with 17....g5, see below}) 17... g5 (17... Qe7 18. Rad1 Rfd8 19. a3 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4]} g5 (19... a5 20. Na4 $16) 20. b4 gxf4 21. gxf4 $1 $16) 18. Qa4 $1 Bc8 (18... gxf4 $6 19. Rxd7 Qc8 20. Qd1 $16 {[%cal Gd1g4]}) 19. b4 b5 (19... gxf4 20. bxc5 Qg5 21. Rxd7 Bxd7 22. Qxd7 Rfd8 23. Qa4 Qxe5 24. Rc1 bxc5 25. Qc2 $16 {[%cal Gc2e2]}) 20. Nxb5 Bb6 21. Be3 Bxe3 22. fxe3 Qb6 23. Nd4 Nxe5 24. Rc2 Bd7 25. Qa3 Rac8 26. Rac1 Rxc2 27. Rxc2 Rc8 28. Rxc8+ Bxc8 29. Qc3 Ba6 30. a4 $14) 13. cxd5 $1 {This characteristic intermezzo after g7-g5, as a rule, is the right way to preserve some advantage.} cxd5 14. Be3 Rc8 15. Rac1 b5 16. Qd2 b4 17. Na4 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Nd7 19. b3 Nxe5 20. Bxa7 Qa5 21. Bd4 Nd7 22. Qe3 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Rc8 24. Rxc8+ Bxc8 25. h4 $14 {J. Stephan - A. Nickel, ICCF email, 2019}) 12. Nd2 Nd5 13. Nxc4 Nxf4 14. gxf4 {reaches a typical situation, in which Black has conceded some space in return for the pair of bishops. Indeed, he is going to wait for the most appropriate moment to release the tension by playing c6-c5, right now his most natural continuation is} Qc7 (14... Bb7 15. f5 $1 exf5 16. Qxf5 Nf6 17. a4 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gf5f3]}) 15. e3 (15. Qe4 Bb7 16. f5 b5 (16... Nf6 $6 17. Qe5) 17. fxe6 bxc4 18. exd7 Qxd7 19. d5 Rac8 20. dxc6 Qxc6 21. Qxc6 Bxc6 22. Rac1 Bf6 $11) (15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. fxe5 Bb7 17. Rac1 Rfd8 18. Qd3 (18. Nb5 Qb8 19. Bxc6 Rc8 20. Qe4 Rxc6 21. Rxc6 Qe8 22. Rdc1 Bc5 23. Rxe6 Qd7 24. Qd3 Qxe6 25. dxc5 Qxe5 26. Qe3 Qf6 $44) (18. e3 c5 $132) 18... Rac8 19. Qg3 Qb8 $11) 15... Bb7 {[%emt 0:00:04] This position, though with Ra8-c8 instead of h7-h6, has already been mentioned in Chapter} 16. Rac1 Rad8 (16... Rfd8 17. f5 e5 18. d5 cxd5 19. Bxd5 $14) (16... Rac8 17. Ne5 Nxe5 18. fxe5 Rfd8 19. f4 $14) 17. Qe4 $5 Nf6 18. Qf3 Nd5 19. Nxd5 (19. Ne5 c5) 19... exd5 (19... cxd5 $6 20. Ne5 Qd6 21. Bf1 $16) (19... Rxd5 $6 20. Ne5) 20. Ne5 Bd6 21. Bf1 $14) 10. h4 $5 {This thrust, which, amongst all, is directed against the imminent g7-g5, is not extravagant at all and we are going to see more of it, including in the next Chapter.} ({The most popular is} 10. Nc3 g5 {, when both retreats have been tested in high-level games:} 11. Be3 (11. Bc1 f5 12. b3 b6 13. Bb2 (13. Nd2 Nef6) 13... Bb7 14. Rad1 Qe8 $13 {with mutual chances, So - Nakamura, Saint Louis, 2017}) 11... Nd6 {[%cal Gd6c4,Gd6f5]} 12. b3 Nf5 13. Bd2 g4 14. Ne1 Nxd4 15. Qd1 dxc4 $5 {ignores White's second threat} (15... Bf6 16. e3 Nf3+ (16... Nf5 17. Qxg4+ Bg7 18. Rd1 $14) 17. Nxf3 gxf3 18. Qxf3 Bg7 {Grischuk - Nakamura, Paris, 2019, is more pleasant for White after winning the pawn back and the natural} 19. Rfd1 Qe7 20. Rac1 $14) 16. Bh6 Nf6 (16... Ne5 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 18. bxc4 Nf5 19. Qc1 Nxc4 20. Nd3 $14) 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 {, hoping to claim compensation for the exchange due to the pair of bishops and the queenside majority:} 18. e3 (18. bxc4 e5 19. e3 Ne6 20. Qc2 Nc5 21. Na4 (21. Rd1 Qc7) 21... Nxa4 22. Qxa4 Bf5 23. Rd1 Qc7 $44) 18... Nb5 $1 19. Qxd8+ Bxd8 20. Nxb5 cxb5 21. bxc4 bxc4 22. Rc1 Bd7 23. Bxb7 Rb8 24. Ba6 Ne4 25. Rxc4 Nd2 26. Rd4 Nxf1 27. Rxd7 Ba5 28. Kxf1 Rb1 29. Rxa7 h5 30. Bd3 Rxe1+ 31. Kg2 Bc3 $14) (10. b3 $5 g5 (10... f5 11. Nc3) 11. Be3 f5 12. Nc3 $14) 10... h6 {Resumes the idea for g7-g5.} ({The jump to the centre is normally a precondition for} 10... f5 11. Nc3 Qe8 (11... Bf6 12. Rad1 {[%cal Gf3e5]}) ({details about} 11... h6 {can be found in the notes to 11...f5, see below}) 12. Rac1 h6 13. e3 {and even for the aggressive} Qh5 14. Ne2 g5 {, to which White can try to take over the initiative at the cost of a pawn -} 15. Bc7 $1 Rf7 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 gxh4 $140 18. Nf4 Qg5 19. gxh4 Qxh4 20. f3 Nf6 21. Ng6 Qg5 22. Nxe7+ Rxe7 23. Kh2 $5 $14 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg2h3]}) 11. Nc3 g5 ({The return to the Stonewall by} 11... f5 {is best met by} 12. Nxe4 $1 {and now:} dxe4 (12... fxe4 13. Ne5 Nxe5 (13... g5 $6 14. hxg5 hxg5 15. Be3 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qc7 17. Bd4 c5 18. cxd5 exd5 19. b4 b6 20. f3 $16) (13... Bf6 14. Rad1 Qe8 15. f3 $16) 14. Bxe5 Bf6 15. f3 $5 ({The elimination of the e4-pawn is a logical consequence of the trade of the knights on move 12, the idea can be realized by} 15. Bxf6 Rxf6 $140 16. f3 $16 {as well}) 15... Bxe5 16. dxe5 Qb6+ 17. Kh2 Bd7 18. Rad1 Qc5 19. Qb3 $16) 13. Ne5 g5 14. hxg5 hxg5 15. Nxd7 Bxd7 16. Be5 Bf6 (16... c5 17. dxc5 Bxc5 {is an attempt to prevent the intended central break; White has a curious deflecting pawn sacrifice at his disposal, namely} 18. a3 a5 19. b4 $1 axb4 20. axb4 Bxb4 21. Rxa8 Qxa8 22. c5 Ba5 23. g4 $36) 17. Rad1 Be8 18. f3 $14) 12. Be3 ({It will be exciting to see games with} 12. Bc1 f5 13. g4 $5) 12... Nd6 ({In reply to} 12... f5 {White has the stunning} 13. Qc1 $1 {, directed against the f5-f4 advance and questioning Black's kingside phalanx. Similar to a previous note for 10...f5, the opening of the g-file} gxh4 14. gxh4 {seems to serve more White, for instance} Rf6 15. Kh1 $14 {[%cal Gf1g1,Gg2h3]}) 13. b3 f5 (13... dxc4 $5 14. Rad1 cxb3 15. axb3 $16 {[%cal Gf3e5]}) 14. Ne5 $5 $146 (14. hxg5 hxg5 15. Ne5 Kg7 {may eventually transpose to the main text.}) 14... Kg7 (14... gxh4 $6 15. Bxh6 Nxe5 (15... hxg3 16. Bf4 $1 gxf2+ 17. Rxf2 {[%csl Rg8]} Bh4 18. Bf3 $1 {[%cal Gf2g2]} Bxf2+ 19. Kxf2 {[%cal Ga1g1]} Qh4+ 20. Bg3 Qxd4+ 21. e3 Qc5 22. Rg1 $18) 16. dxe5 Nf7 17. Bf4 hxg3 18. Rad1 $1 gxf2+ 19. Rxf2 Bh4 20. Bf3 $1 {[%cal Gf2g2]} Bxf2+ 21. Kxf2 Qh4+ 22. Bg3 Qh7 23. Rh1 Nh6 24. cxd5 Ng4+ (24... cxd5 25. Nxd5 $18) 25. Ke1 Qg7 26. Bf4 $1 Bd7 (26... Nxe5 27. Bxe5 Qxe5 28. Rg1+ Kh8 29. dxc6 bxc6 30. Qd2 Qf6 31. Bxc6 Bb7 (31... Rb8 32. Qf4 $18) 32. Bxb7 Rad8 33. Qe3 $18) 27. Bxg4 Qxg4 (27... fxg4 28. Ne4 $5 (28. Bh6 $18) 28... Rxf4 29. Nf6+ Rxf6 30. exf6 Qf7 31. d6 $18 {[%cal Gc2e4]}) 28. Be3 $1 Qg3+ 29. Bf2 Qf4 30. Qd3 $1 Rf7 31. Rh4 Qc1+ 32. Nd1 Rg7 33. Qh3 Kf7 34. Rh6 Rag8 35. Rf6+ Ke8 36. dxe6 Bc8 37. Qh5+ Kd8 38. Rf7 Bxe6 39. Bh4+ Rg5 40. e3 Ke8 41. Rf8+ $1 Kxf8 42. Bxg5 $18) (14... Qe8 15. hxg5 hxg5 16. f4 $14) 15. Rad1 Nf7 16. hxg5 {Together with the next move - a reasonable plan to reinforce Ne5.} ({An opportunity for the extraordinary break} 16. g4 $5 {is existing here again: Black can also get rid of the annoying Ne5 at once -} Nfxe5 (16... Nf6 17. f3 $1 {A cool-blooded move, the shelter in front of Kg8 is seriously questioned:} Qc7 (17... Bd6 18. gxf5 exf5 19. cxd5 Nxd5 (19... cxd5 20. f4 $16) 20. Nxd5 cxd5 21. f4 $16) 18. gxf5 Nxe5 19. dxe5 Qxe5 20. Bd4 {will ruin the Stonewall, e.g.} Qxf5 21. Qxf5 exf5 22. cxd5 gxh4 23. e4 $36) 17. dxe5 Nxe5 (17... f4 $6 18. Bc1) 18. Bd4 Bf6 19. gxf5 {with better prospects for White, regarding that Ra8 and Bc8 are still on their initial squares. We can therefore expect from any central confrontation to favour the first player -} Ng4 20. Qd2 $1 Qd6 (20... e5 21. Bc5 Be7 22. Bxe7 Qxe7 23. cxd5 Bxf5 24. d6 $36) 21. f4 e5 (21... gxf4 22. Rxf4 exf5 23. cxd5 c5 24. Nb5 $1 Qb6 25. Bxf6+ Rxf6 26. d6 c4+ 27. Kh1 Qxb5 28. d7 Bxd7 29. Qxd7+ Qxd7 30. Rxd7+ Kh8 31. bxc4 $14) 22. hxg5 exd4 23. gxf6+ Qxf6 24. Qxd4 Qxd4+ 25. Rxd4 Ne3 26. Rf2 Nxf5 27. Rd3 d4 28. Ne4 $14) 16... hxg5 17. f4 Ndxe5 (17... g4 18. Kf2 $14) (17... Nh6 18. fxg5 Bxg5 19. Qd2 Bxe3+ 20. Qxe3 $14) 18. dxe5 Bd7 19. fxg5 $1 Rc8 $1 (19... Nxe5 $6 20. Qb2 {is spelling danger along the big diagonal, for example} Ng4 21. Nxd5+ Kg8 22. Nf4 $16 Nxe3 23. Nh5 $1 Rf7 24. g6) (19... Bxg5 20. Bd4 $16) 20. Qd2 Bxg5 21. Bf4 $14 *

