 ({but definitely not} 18. exf3 $6 e5 $11)) 12. e3 $1 f5 (12... Nxf4 13. exf4 $16 {[%csl Rc8]}) (12... g5 13. Bd6 Bxd6 14. cxd6 $16 {[%csl Rc6]}) 13. Nbd2 Nhf6 (13... Bb7 14. Nb3 $16 {[%cal Gf4d6,Gb3c1,Gc1d3]}) 14. Ng5 Nb8 {Black has not equalized in C. Bauer - A. Fernandes, San Sebastian, 2009, for instance} 15. h4 h6 16. Nh3 Nbd7 17. Nf3 $16 {[%csl Re5,Rg5][%cal Gg2f1]}) ({After} 10... Nh5 11. Bc1 {Black must somehow resume the control over the e4-square:} f5 ({in reply to} 11... b5 {White inserted} 12. Ne5 Bb7 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 {before} 14. c5 {, intending 15.e4, while} f5 {has urged him to get rid of the other defender of the e5-square by means of} 15. Nd2 Qc7 16. Nf3 Bf6 17. Bg5 Rae8 18. Qd2 $14 {Gelfand - Kamsky, Sochi, 2008}) (11... Nhf6 12. Nbd2 {[%cal Ge2e4]} b6 (12... b5 13. c5 $16) 13. e4 $36) 12. Nc3 (12. b3 $14) 12... Bd6 13. b3 $14 {[%cal Gc3a4,Ga4b2,Gb2d3]}) ({Advances like} 10... a4 $5 {are very trendy today, here it is quite provocative:} 11. Ne5 $1 (11. Nc3 dxc4 12. Nxa4 $140 (12. Nd2 Nb6 $13) 12... Nd5 $13) 11... Qa5 ({the initiative belongs to White after} 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. cxd5 {and now:} exd5 ({after} 13... cxd5 $6 14. e4 d4 {might be only a temporary pawn sacrifice, but White can safely increase his pressure along the open files, e. g.} 15. Rxd4 Qa5 (15... Qb6 $6 16. Rd1) 16. Nd2 (16. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c4]} Nxe5 17. Rc1 Nc6 18. Rd2 $14) 16... Nxe5 17. b4 axb3 18. Nxb3 Qb5 19. a4 Qc6 20. Qd1 f6 21. Bf1 $14 {[%cal Gf1b5]}) 14. e4 $1 Nb6 $5 $146 {may well be Black's best bet, although there is no clear path to full equality after the natural} (14... d4 {has been tried here as well -} 15. Rxd4 Qb6 16. Rd1 (16. Rd2 $5 $146 {with the idea for} Qa5 17. e6 fxe6 18. Na3 {is a probable improvement, e.g.} e5 19. Be3 Nb6 20. Nc4 Nxc4 21. Qxc4+ Kh8 22. a3 $14) 16... Qa5 17. Nc3 a3 (17... Nxe5 18. Nd5 cxd5 19. Bxe5 $14) 18. bxa3 {S. Brunello - N. Short, Caleta, 2012} Nxe5 19. Nd5 cxd5 20. Rxd5 (20. Bxe5 dxe4 21. Qxe4 Bxa3 $11) 20... b5 21. Bxe5 Be6 $44) (14... dxe4 15. Bxe4 h6 16. Na3 $14 ({or once again} 16. e6 $5 fxe6 $140 17. Na3 $36)) 15. exd5 {, as follows:} Nxd5 (15... cxd5 $6 16. Qe2 $1 (16. Nc3 Bg4 17. Rd4 Bc5 $13) 16... Be6 17. Nc3 $16) 16. Nc3 Be6 17. Nxa4 Qa5 18. Bxd5 (18. Nc3 Nxf4 19. gxf4 g6 $44) 18... cxd5 (18... Bxd5 19. Nc3 Be6 20. Ne4 h6 21. Nd6 $14) 19. Nc3 Rfd8 20. Be3 {[%cal Ge3d4]} d4 $1 21. Bxd4 (21. Rxd4 Qxe5) 21... Rd7 $1 {[%cal Ga8d8]} 22. Ne2 Rad8 23. Bc3 Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 25. Qxd1 Qxa2 26. Nf4 $14) (11... Nh5 12. Bd2 Nhf6 13. Nd3 Bd6 14. Na3 $1 Qe7 15. Rac1 Rd8 16. Bf4 Bxf4 17. Nxf4 $14) (11... Qb6 12. Nxd7 $146 ({White has a good reason to postpone} 12. c5 Qa7) 12... Nxd7 (12... Bxd7 $6 13. c5 Qa7 14. Nc3 Rfc8 15. e4 $16) 13. Nc3 $5 ({the textmove is giving rise to an exciting skirmish in the centre, given the transfer of Qd8 to the queenside; a pure positional approach is} 13. c5 Qa7 14. e4 b6 15. Bd6 Re8 16. Bxe7 Rxe7 17. cxb6 Qxb6 18. Nc3 Qa7 19. Rac1 Re8 $11) 13... Qa6 (13... a3 14. b3 $14) 14. cxd5 exd5 15. e4 dxe4 16. Qxe4 $5 (16. Nxe4 Nf6) (16. d5 f5 $11) 16... Bb4 (16... Bd8 17. d5 Nf6 18. Qb4 $14) 17. d5 Bxc3 18. dxc6 $1 (18. bxc3 Nf6) 18... Bxb2 (18... Nf6 $6 19. Qe7 $1) 19. Rab1 Nc5 (19... Qxc6 20. Qxc6 bxc6 21. Rxb2 $14) 20. Qe7 {[%cal Gd1d8]} Bf6 21. Qxc5 bxc6 22. Bxc6 Bg4 23. Bxa8 Bxd1 24. Be4 Rd8 25. Rb6 Qe2 26. Be3 Qe1+ 27. Kg2 Be2 28. Rb1 Qc3 29. Rc1 Qxc5 30. Rxc5 $14 {Black seems to have survived the worst, even though the danger for his a-pawn is not entirely over}) 12. Nxd7 (12. Nd3 Qa7 $132) (12. Nd2 {is slightly imprecise because of} Nxe5 $1 13. dxe5 Nd7 (13... Ng4 $5 {contains an unexpected tactical idea for} 14. Bh3 Nxf2 $5 15. Kxf2 $140 Qc5+ 16. e3 g5 $13) 14. Nf3 h6 15. h4 Qa6 $132 16. cxd5 $140 (16. Rac1 Qxc4 17. Qxc4 dxc4 18. Rxc4 Nb6 $11) 16... exd5 ({less logical is} 16... cxd5 17. Bf1) 17. Nd4 (17. Rac1 Nc5 $132) ({Black can consider the same jump in answer to} 17. e6 {or play} fxe6 {without any fear of} 18. Bxh6 {, to which the new e-pawn can advance 