{[%evp 0,61,19,13,27,7,5,15,15,-19,11,11,11,-4,-4,4,25,13,12,2,15,9,2,20,19,11,18,8,3,-36,-27,18,18,23,28,21,15,20,20,20,21,21,20,8,10,-23,20,9,25,8,13,-43,47,59,44,37,36,39,59,39,46,39,51,50]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Qc2 c6 9. Bf4 Nh5 10. Bc1 Nhf6 ({As soon as Nf6 has moved away, in case of} 10... b6 {Black must reckon with} 11. e4 dxe4 (11... Nhf6 12. e5 Ne4 13. Rd1 Bb7 (13... Ba6 14. Ne1 $1 {[%cal Gf2f3]}) 14. Ne1 $5 (14. Bf4 $14) 14... f6 15. f3 Ng5 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. Bxg5 Bxg5 18. f4 Bf6 19. Nf3 c5 20. Nc3 $14) 12. Ne5 $5 (12. Qxe4 Bb7 13. Ne5 Nhf6 14. Qe2 Qc8 15. Rd1 $14) 12... Nxe5 (12... Bb7 13. Bxe4 $16) 13. dxe5 f5 14. exf6 Nxf6 15. Nc3 e5 16. Nxe4 Bf5 17. Nxf6+ Rxf6 18. Qb3 Kh8 19. Be3 $14) (10... f5 11. b3 $14) 11. Nbd2 {[%cal Ge2e4]} b6 (11... c5 {is a serious alternative, especially when Black can recapture with the knight. Indeed, there is always a risk that the central pawn exchanges will enlarge the scope of Bg2.} 12. Rd1 (12. dxc5 $5 {is good enough in the fight for an opening advantage:} Bxc5 (12... Nxc5 13. b4 Ncd7 (13... Nce4 14. a3 $14) 14. a3 b6 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Bb2 Bb7 17. Rac1 Rc8 18. Qa4 $14) 13. Nb3 Bb6 14. Bf4 $14) 12... b6 (12... cxd4 13. Nxd4 Qb6 14. N2f3 $14) 13. cxd5 {looks fine as well:} Nxd5 ({after} 13... exd5 14. e4 Bb7 15. e5 {the sequence} Ne4 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Ne1 cxd4 18. Bxe4 Bxe4 19. Qxe4 {is more or less forced and the d4-pawn looks doomed. Nevertheless, White does not need to stick to such small material gain at any cost:} Nc5 (19... Qc7 20. Bf4 (20. e6 f5) 20... Nc5 21. Qxd4 Rad8 22. Qe3 $14) (19... f6 20. Rxd4 Nc5 (20... fxe5 21. Rd3 Bc5 22. Be3 Bxe3 23. Rxe3 Qf6 24. Nf3 $14) 21. Rxd8 Nxe4 22. Rxa8 Rxa8 23. exf6 Bxf6 24. Rb1 Bd4 (24... Rd8 25. Be3) 25. Be3 Bxe3 26. fxe3 Rd8 27. Rc1 $14) 20. Qxd4 Qxd4 21. Rxd4 f6 22. Bf4 $5 (22. exf6 Bxf6 $44) 22... g5 23. Be3 fxe5 24. Rc4 $14 {and, similar to the subline with 20...fxe5 from above, White can rely on his better pawn structure in the long run.}) 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Nb3 $1 Nxb3 (15... Bb7 16. Nxc5 bxc5 17. a3 $14 {[%cal Ge2e4]}) (15... Ba6 16. Nxc5 bxc5 17. a3 $14) 16. Qxb3 Qe8 (16... a5 17. a4 $14 {[%csl Rb5]}) 17. Ne5 Bb7 18. a4 Bd6 (18... Rc8 19. a5 $14) 19. Nd3 $14 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ga4a5,Ge2e4]}) 12. e4 dxc4 (12... Bb7 $6 13. e5 Ne8 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Re1 Qc7 (15... Rc8 16. Qd1) 16. Qd1 a5 (16... Rc8 17. Nb1 $1 {[%cal Gb1c3]}) 17. Nf1 Rc8 18. Ne3 Ba6 19. h4 $16 {Cheparinov - Piorun, Skopje, 2019}) (12... c5 {is accordingly met by} 13. e5 Ne8 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Rd1 $1 Nc7 16. Nf1 $14 {[%cal Gf1e3] and Black is going to have trouble in protecting the central d5-pawn}) ({its exchange by} 12... dxe4 {does not yield equality yet -} 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 (13... Bb7 14. Nxf6+ Nxf6 15. Rd1 $16 {[%cal Gc4c5]}) 14. Qxe4 Bb7 15. Rd1 Qc8 (15... Nf6 $6 16. Qe2 Qc8 17. Bf4 $16) 16. Bf4 (16. Qc2 $5 c5 17. d5) 16... c5 17. d5 Re8 18. Qd3 exd5 19. cxd5 Bf6 20. Re1 $14) 13. Nxc4 Bb7 14. Ne3 $5 ({An essential theoretical line is going on with} 14. Bf4 c5 15. Rfe1 cxd4 16. Nd6 $1 {(see the next Chapter as well)} Bxd6 17. Bxd6 d3 $1 18. Qxd3 Bxe4 19. Qd4 e5 20. Qa4 Re8 21. Rad1 Bxf3 22. Bxf3 e4 23. Bxe4 (23. Bg2 h6) 23... Nxe4 24. Rxe4 Rxe4 25. Qxe4 Nc5 26. Qf3 Ne6 $14) (14. Bg5 $5 {is a major alternative:} b5 ({it is worth remembering that} 14... h6 {can be energetically met by} 15. e5 $1 Nd5 (15... Ne8 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Nh4 $16) (15... hxg5 16. Nxg5 b5 17. exf6 Nxf6 18. Ne5 Qxd4 19. Rae1 $16) 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 17. Nd6 Rb8 18. Rad1 $16) ({after} 14... c5 15. e5 $1 {is critical again -} Nd5 16. Nd6 $1 Nb4 17. Nxb7 Nxc2 18. Nxd8 Bxd8 19. Rad1 Rc8 20. Bxd8 Rcxd8 {and here the clever} 21. d5 $1 exd5 22. a3 $1 {[%csl Rc2] forces the opponent to} d4 23. Rd2 d3 24. Rxd3 Nd4 25. Nxd4 cxd4 26. f4 Nc5 27. Rd2 Nb3 28. Rdd1 $14 {, when another d4-pawn of his has turned into a tempting target}) 15. Ne3 c5 {is more to the point after Nc4 has been chased. In his turn, White is going to shift his attention to the other central push} (15... Rc8 16. e5 (16. Rfe1 $14) 16... Nd5 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Nxd5 cxd5 19. Qd3 $14) ({here too, Black is experiencing difficulties in case of} 15... h6 16. e5 $1 {, for example} hxg5 17. Nxg5 g6 18. Rad1 Kg7 19. exf6+ Nxf6 20. Rfe1 Rc8 21. h4 $14) 16. d5 exd5 17. exd5 {and now: in reply to} Re8 {worth of attention is} (17... h6 $6 {is inviting} 18. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 19. Nf5 Nh7 20. Rfe1 Bf6 21. d6 Qb6 22. Rad1 Rad8 23. Qd2 $16 {with huge initiative}) ({White is exerting strong pressure along the central files after} 17... Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Rad1 {, here are several sample lines in confirmation to this -} Nb6 20. Bf4 $1 Qd7 (20... Qc8 $6 21. Rfe1 Bf6 22. Be5 Qe6 23. Qxc5 $16) 21. Rxd5 $1 ({less adventurous way to a lasting pull is} 21. Ng5 Bxg5 22. Bxg5 f6 23. Be3 $14) 21... Nxd5 22. Rd1 Rae8 23. Qd2 (23. Ne5 Nb4 24. Qxh7+ Kxh7 25. Nxd7 c4 26. Nxf8+ Bxf8 $14) 23... Qe6 24. Qxd5 Rd8 25. Qxe6 Rxd1+ 26. Qe1 Rfd8 27. Kf1 Rxe1+ 28. Kxe1 $14) 18. a4 a6 19. Nd2 $5 $146 {and now:} Qb6 (19... h6 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 (20... Nxf6 $2 21. d6 $18) 21. Ne4 $36) 20. Ne4 h6 21. a5 Qa7 22. Nxf6+ Nxf6 23. Bf4 c4 24. Rad1 {and, due to the mighty and well-supported central passed pawn, White's chances are preferable. The following sample line is far from obligatory, but it is demonstrating some hidden tactical possibilities -} Bf8 (24... Bc5 $6 25. Nf5) 25. Bc7 {[%cal Gc7b6]} Bc5 26. Nf5 Nxd5 27. Bxd5 Bxd5 28. Bb6 (28. Qc3 f6 29. Bb6 Qd7 30. Nxg7 Kxg7 31. Bxc5 Rad8 $11) 28... Bxb6 29. axb6 Qd7 30. Ne3 Rxe3 31. fxe3 Qe6 $44) 14... c5 15. d5 $1 exd5 16. exd5 Nxd5 ({Otherwise this pawn may become unbearable -} 16... Re8 $6 17. Rd1 b5 18. b3 $16 {[%cal Gc1b2]}) 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Rd1 Be6 (18... Bxf3 $2 19. Bxf3 Ne5 (19... Rc8 20. Qf5 Rc7 21. Bf4 $18) 20. Rxd8 Nxf3+ 21. Kh1 Raxd8 22. Qe2 $18 {[%csl Re7,Rf3]}) (18... Bb7 $2 19. Ng5 Bxg5 20. Bxb7 $18) 19. Ne5 {The point of the operation, which has started with moves 14 and 15,} (19. Bf4 Bf6 {and the same jump is likely to transpose to 21. ..h6, see below.}) 19... Nxe5 20. Rxd8 Raxd8 21. Be4 $1 f5 (21... h6 22. Bf4 Bf6 23. Re1 Nc4 24. b3 $14) (21... Bg4 22. Be3 h6 (22... f5 $6 23. Bg2) 23. Kg2 $14) 22. Bb7 $5 {Anticipating the penetration of the knight to the d3-square with Ba6-c4 in mind.} ({Less ambitious is} 22. Bg2 Nd3 $44) 22... Rd7 23. Bf4 Nd3 24. Rd1 $5 {A reasonable decision to fight for the d-file.} ({The enemy rooks cannot be chased away from it, as shown by a variation like} 24. Bc6 Rdd8 25. Bc7 Rd4 26. Qe2 Kf7 27. Be5 (27. Qh5+ Kg8) 27... Nxe5 28. Qxe5 Rc8 29. Bb5 Re4 30. Qc3 Rd8 $44 {Regarding also Black's equivalent for the queen, the idea to level the material with a transition into an ending with a pair of bishops is admirable.}) 24... Rfd8 25. Bc6 Nb4 26. Bxd7 Nxc2 27. Bxe6+ Kf8 28. Rxd8+ Bxd8 29. Bxf5 Nd4 30. Bd3 ({Of course not} 30. Bxh7 $6 Ne2+ $11) 30... h6 31. Kg2 $14 *

