{[%evp 0,39,10,13,27,7,15,15,15,-24,11,12,12,2,2,9,25,13,13,12,10,2,19,-19,-22,-19,-11,-28,-24,-25,-26,-27,-21,-27,-33,-38,-31,-50,-37,-17,-39,-32]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Qc2 c6 9. Bf4 b6 10. Nbd2 Nh5 ({We have already seen a number of occasions, in which} 10... c5 $5 {has been played only with an available recapture with Nd7. Here the critical continuation is} 11. e4 (11. cxd5 Nxd5 $11) (11. dxc5 Nxc5 12. Rfd1 Bb7 13. Rac1 Rc8 $11) (11. Ne5 Bb7 $11) 11... dxc4 (11... dxe4 {seems to be the most natural reaction and now:} 12. Ne5 $5 (12. Nxe4 Bb7 {is more or less balanced:} 13. Nxf6+ (13. Nd6 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 cxd4 15. Rae1 (15. Nb7 Qc8 16. Nd6 $11) 15... Nc5 (15... a6 $5 16. Bxa8 (16. Nb7 Qc8 17. Nd6 $11) 16... Qxa8 $44) (15... e5 $5 16. Nf5 Bb4 $132) 16. Nb7 Nxb7 17. Bxb7 Rb8 18. Bxb8 Qxb8 19. Bf3 Rd8 $44) 13... Nxf6 14. Rad1 cxd4 (14... Qc8 $5) 15. Rxd4 Qc8 16. Rfd1 (16. Qe2 {is almost reaching the position from my game with Gajewski, see below, but with Black's turn, so here} Bc5 {seems to be the equalizer -} 17. Rd2 Ne4 18. Rdd1 Qc6 $11) 16... Bc5 17. R4d3 Be4 18. Ne5 Bxd3 19. Rxd3 a5 20. Bxa8 Qxa8 21. Nd7 (21. Be3 Qe4) 21... Nxd7 22. Rxd7 Rd8 23. Qd3 Rxd7 24. Qxd7 h6 $11) 12... Bb7 13. Rad1 {requires high precision from Black:} Nh5 $1 ({the mass exchanges, starting with} 13... cxd4 {are enabling White to retain some lasting pressure, e.g.} 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bxe4 Nxe4 (15... Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Bc5 18. Bxd4 Qe7 19. Rd3 Rad8 20. Rfd1 Bxd4 21. Rxd4 g6 22. b3 $14) 16. Rxd4 Nef6 (16... Nec5 17. Nxd7 {and White will regain the piece with interest}) 17. Rfd1 (17. Nxd7 $6 Bc5 $1 {is an instructive trick}) 17... Bc5 18. Rxd7 Nxd7 19. Nxd7 Qe7 20. Nxc5 bxc5 (20... Qxc5 21. Bd6 Qc6 22. Bxf8 Rxf8 23. b3 $14) 21. Bd6 Qf6 22. Bxf8 Rxf8 23. h4 $14) (13... Qc8 14. Nxd7 Nxd7 15. Nxe4 cxd4 {is leading to small material deficit after the vigorous} 16. Bd6 $1 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Bxd6 18. Qxa8 Qxa8 19. Bxa8 Bc5 20. Bg2 $14) 14. dxc5 (14. Nxe4 Nxf4 15. dxc5 {- 14.dxc5}) 14... Nxf4 15. Nxe4 Nxe5 16. Rxd8 Nh3+ $1 17. Bxh3 (17. Kh1 $2 Raxd8 $17) 17... Nf3+ 18. Kh1 Raxd8 19. Bg2 Bxe4 20. Qxe4 Nd2 21. Qb7 Bxc5 22. Rd1 Ne4 $1 23. Rxd8 Nxf2+ 24. Kg1 Ng4+ $11) (11... Ba6 12. exd5 exd5 13. Rad1 Rc8 14. Qa4 Bb7 15. Rfe1 $14 {looks very nice for White}) ({in reply to} 11... Bb7 {, which attacks the e4-pawn, a very promising idea is} 12. cxd5 exd5 13. e5 Nh5 (13... Ne4 14. Rad1) 14. Be3 $14 {, when Nh5 is badly placed}) 12. Nxc4 {and Black is facing the same choice:} Ba6 $5 {is much more interesting, especially after the principled} (12... Bb7 13. Rfe1 cxd4 14. Nd6 {will put him firmly on the defensive side, e.g.} Bxd6 15. Bxd6 d3 (15... Rc8 16. Qa4 Re8 17. Qxd4 Nc5 18. e5 Nfe4 19. b4 Nxd6 20. exd6 Nd7 21. Rad1 Bd5 22. Ne5 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 Nxe5 24. Rxe5 Qd7 25. Re3 $14) 16. Qxd3 Bxe4 17. Qd4 e5 18. Qa4 Re8 19. Rad1 $44 Bxf3 $140 20. Bxf3 e4 21. Bxe4 (21. Bg2 h5 $13) 21... Nxe4 22. Rxe4 Rxe4 23. Qxe4 Nc5 24. Qf3 Ne6 $14 {This important theoretical variation has already been mentioned in the previous Chapter}) 13. d5 $5 (13. Qa4 Qc8 14. Nd6 Bxd6 15. Bxd6 Bxf1 16. Bxf1 Nxe4 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 18. Bg2 f5 $11) (13. Rfd1 cxd4 14. Rxd4 Bc5 15. Rdd1 Rc8 $11) 13... exd5 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Nfe5 Nb4 (15... Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Nb4 17. Qc3 {is practically the same}) 16. Qc3 Nxe5 (16... Bf6 $143 17. Rad1 Qe7 18. Rxd7 Qxd7 19. Nxd7 Bxc3 20. bxc3 Nd3 21. Bxa8 Rxa8 22. Ndxb6 axb6 23. Nxb6 Re8 24. Be3 $14) 17. Bxe5 Qd3 (17... Nd5 18. Qb3 b5 {is running into} 19. Rad1 $1 {as well -} bxc4 20. Qa4 Qb6 21. Bxd5 Bb5 22. Qc2 Rad8 23. Bxc4 $14) 18. Bxa8 Bxc4 (18... Rxa8 19. b3 b5 20. Na5 $14) 19. Rfc1 Be6 ({the only known game saw} 19... Qxc3 $5 20. Rxc3 Bxa2 21. Bg2 a5 $44 {J. Jareno Bautista - J. Rojas, ICCF email, 2020, which finished peacefully 9 moves later}) (19... Bg5 $6 20. f4) 20. Bf3 Qxc3 21. Rxc3 c4 22. Be4 $1 {and, even though the impression is that the compensation for the exchange is insufficient, in the following sample lines White has to increase his edge in endings with opposite-colored bishops -} f5 (22... f6 23. Bf4 f5 24. a3 Bf6 25. Bxf5 Bxf5 26. axb4 Bxc3 27. bxc3 a5 28. bxa5 bxa5 29. Rxa5 $14) 23. a3 fxe4 24. axb4 Bxb4 25. Rxa7 Rf5 26. Bd4 Bxc3 27. Rxg7+ Kf8 28. bxc3 $14) (10... Ba6 11. Rfe1 $5 ({after} 11. Rac1 Nh5 12. Be3 Nhf6 13. Bf4 Nh5 {White deviated from the repetition with} 14. Be5 Rc8 15. e4 f6 16. Bf4 Nxf4 17. gxf4 {, which brought success to him, Gelfand - Keymer, Biel, 2021, but in my view, the position is doubled-edged after} f5 $132) ({Black seems ready to meet} 11. e4 {, as shown by} dxc4 (11... Nxe4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Qd3 15. Rfc1 Qxc2 16. Rxc2 c5 17. Bxe4 Rab8 $11) 12. Nxc4 Nxe4 13. Rfd1 Nef6 14. Nce5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Nd5 16. Nxc6 Qd7 17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Rac1 Rfc8 19. Qf5 Qe8 $11) (11. Rfd1 {is the main theoretical favorite, but I would like to suggest another square}) 11... Nh5 {is once again a major alternative:} (11... c5 12. e4 dxc4 {Here an original sacrifice of a second pawn by} (12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Rxe4 Nf6 15. Ree1 cxd4 16. Rad1 $14) 13. d5 $1 exd5 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Rad1 $36 {reveals one of the points behind 11.Rfe1!? Black is facing certain problems:} Nb4 {seems to be the best practical chance, leading to complicated positions with unbalanced material, though White is objectively playing on two results:} (15... Bf6 16. Qa4 $1 Nxf4 (16... c3 17. Ne4 Bb7 18. bxc3 $16) 17. gxf4 Bc8 (17... Qc8 18. Ne4 b5 19. Qa5 $16) 18. Qc6 Rb8 19. Nxc4 Rb7 20. Qb5 Rc7 21. Nfe5 $36) 16. Qe4 (16. Qf5 $5 Bf6 17. Nxc4 Bxc4 18. Rxd7 Qc8 19. Nd2 Be6 20. Rxe6 Qxd7 21. Rxf6 Rad8 22. Ne4 Qxf5 (22... Rfe8) 23. Rxf5 Nxa2 24. Bf1 $14) 16... Nf6 17. Qxe7 Qxe7 18. Rxe7 Nfd5 19. Rd7 c3 20. bxc3 Nxc3 21. Re1 Bb5 22. Rd6 Ne2+ 23. Kh1 Nxf4 24. gxf4 Rad8 25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. h4 $14) (11... Rc8 {allows} 12. e4 {, but Black can immediately initiate actions against it by means of the usual} Nh5 13. Be3 Nhf6 {A curious line goes on with} 14. Rad1 dxc4 15. Nxc4 Nxe4 16. Nfe5 f5 17. a3 $1 (17. Nd2 {at once is met by} Nxe5 18. dxe5 Bd3 19. Qa4 Qd5 20. Qxa7 Bb4 $13) 17... Ndf6 18. Nd2 Bd6 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. Bf4 $14) 12. Be5 (12. e3 g5 $1 {An essential point - here this thrust is coming at the right moment.} 13. cxd5 (13. Be5 $6 f6 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Qxc6 fxe5 $15) 13... gxf4 14. dxe6 fxg3 ({it is also possible to take the bull by the horns and rely on the extra piece -} 14... fxe6 15. exf4 Ng7 16. Rad1 $44) 15. exd7 gxf2+ 16. Kxf2 Qxd7 17. Kg1 (17. Rg1 $6 Kh8) (17. Ne5 Bh4+ 18. Kg1 Qe7 $132) 17... Qe6 $13) (12. Be3 Rc8 $11) 12... Rc8 (12... f6 $2 13. cxd5) 13. e4 (13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Qa4 Bb7 15. Qxa7 Bc6 {[%cal Gg7g5]} 16. Rec1 g5 $5 {[%cal Gf7f6]} 17. Bh3 Qe8 18. Rc2 Ra8 19. Qc7 Rc8 $11) ({the direct} 13. Bh3 $5 {is an interesting, albeit a bit artificial try to limit some of the just mentioned possibilities to trap Be5, which are fully valid after the text move as well}) 13... g5 $5 (13... f6 14. Bf4 Nxf4 15. gxf4 $14 {[%cal Gf4f5]}) 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Qa4 Bb7 16. Qxa7 Bc6 17. exd5 exd5 (17... Bxd5 18. Rec1) 18. Bh3 $1 f5 (18... f6 {is the last chance to pretend a material gain, the assessment is depending on a complicated line like} 19. Nxg5 $1 Ra8 20. Qc7 Nxe5 21. Ne6 $1 Qxc7 22. Nxc7 Ra7 23. Ne6 Nc4 24. Nxc4 dxc4 25. Nxf8 Kxf8 26. Be6 $14) 19. g4 Nxe5 ({Black has more trouble in proving compensation for the missing pawn without the queens, namely} 19... Ra8 20. Qc7 Nxe5 21. Qxd8 Bxd8 22. Nxe5 Nf4 23. Bg2 $14) 20. Nxe5 Nf4 21. Nxc6 Nxh3+ 22. Kg2 Rxc6 (22... Nf4+ 23. Kh1 {is likely to transpose}) 23. Rxe7 Rh6 $1 24. gxf5 Nf4+ 25. Kg1 Qd6 26. Rg7+ Kh8 27. Rf7 Rxf7 28. Qxf7 Rf6 29. Qe8+ Rf8 30. Qe3 Rxf5 31. Re1 Kg8 $44) (10... Bb7 {is a bit more passive than 10...Ba6, after} 11. e4 {Black must tread carefully:} Nh5 $5 (11... dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 (12... c5 $5 {is back to 10. ..c5}) 13. Qxe4 Nf6 14. Qe2 c5 {This pawn has not come here in one go, which is already a concession. Even though there is no direct refutation, White has all the freedom to improve -} 15. Rfd1 cxd4 16. Rxd4 Qc8 17. Ne5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qb7+ 19. Qf3 Qxf3+ 20. Kxf3 Rfc8 21. Rad1 $14 {with typical endgame edge, Cheparinov - Gajewski, Islandic League, Reykjavik 2023. White has control over the d-file, while the opponent must constantly watch for the vulnerable c6-square.}) (11... Rc8 $6 12. e5 Ne8 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Qd1 $16 (14. Qa4)) (11... c5 $6 {is also transposing to 10...c5}) 12. Be3 (12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Bc7 Qe8 $11) 12... Nhf6 {is taking advantage of the fact that 13.e5 is running into 13...Ng4, so White has to reconcile himself with the repetition or go for the courageous} 13. h4 $5 (13. Rad1 Rc8 $13) 13... dxe4 $146 (13... dxc4 14. e5 Nd5 15. Ng5 g6 (15... Bxg5 $143 16. Bxg5 Qc7 17. Nxc4 c5 18. dxc5 bxc5 19. Rfd1 $14) 16. Bxd5 $1 cxd5 (16... exd5 17. e6 Bxg5 18. Bxg5 Nf6 19. exf7+ Rxf7 20. Nf3 Qd6 21. Ne5 Rff8 22. Bf4 $36) 17. Ndf3 $40 {Langeveld - Pessoa, ICCF email, 2020}) 14. Nxe4 (14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Ng4 $132) 14... c5 15. Nxf6+ (15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 Qc7 $11) 15... Nxf6 16. Rad1 Qc7 17. Qe2 $14 {is more pleasant to handle, though Black has achieved a better version of the abovementioned game of mine with Gajewski, for the rooks are already connected.}) 11. e3 $5 (11. Be3 Bb7 $11) (11. Be5 Bb7 $11) 11... Nxf4 ({After} 11... Bb7 12. cxd5 {Black's best is} Nxf4 (12... cxd5 $6 13. Bc7 $1 Qe8 14. Rfc1 Nhf6 15. Bf1 {was awkward for Black in Ding Liren - Anand, Kolkata, 2019, e.g.} Rc8 16. Qa4 $16) ({in case of} 12... exd5 13. h4 Rc8 {the subtle maneuver} 14. Nb1 Nxf4 15. exf4 c5 16. Nc3 {posed problems -} Nf6 17. Rad1 $14 {[%cal Gf1e1] Giri - Topalov, Stavanger, 2022}) 13. exf4 {with ultimate transposition to the leading text with} ({White does not benefit from} 13. dxc6 {because of} Ne2+ 14. Kh1 Rc8 15. Qd3 Nxg3+ 16. hxg3 Rxc6 $11) 13... cxd5 (13... exd5 $143 14. Rfe1 $14)) (11... g5 $6 12. Be5 f6 (12... g4 13. cxd5 $1 gxf3 14. Bxf3 $16) (12... Bb7 13. cxd5 $16) 13. cxd5 {and the elimination of the bishop will cost many pawns, while after} Nxe5 14. dxe5 cxd5 15. e4 $16 {the material is equal, but Black's minor pieces are badly coordinated}) (11... Ba6 12. Rfc1 Rc8 {took place in one of the key games for the European title, White did not hesitate over the familiar} 13. h4 $5 (13. cxd5 Nxf4 14. exf4 cxd5 15. Qa4 Nb8) 13... dxc4 14. Nxc4 c5 15. Qa4 Nxf4 16. exf4 Bb7 $5 {is a probable improvement, for instance} (16... Nb8 17. Nce5 f6 $5 (17... Qe8 18. Qb3 Bb7 19. dxc5 Bxc5 20. Rc3 $16) 18. Ng4 $1 Qd7 19. Qxd7 Nxd7 20. Re1 Kf7 21. Ne3 Rfd8 22. d5 Nf8 {and Black survived in Esipenko - Sarana, Vrnjacka Banja, 2023, but} 23. Rad1 $16 {would have put him under severe pressure}) 17. Qxa7 Rc7 18. Qa4 cxd4 19. Nce5 Nc5 20. Qxd4 f6 21. Qxd8 Rxd8 22. Ng4 $14) 12. exf4 Bb7 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Rfc1 Rc8 ({White's prospects are higher after} 14... Bd6 15. Ne5 Nf6 16. h4 $14 {[%cal Gg2f1,Gf1d3]}) ({similar is} 14... Nf6 15. Ne5 $14) 15. Qa4 $1 {[%csl Ra7]} a6 (15... a5 {looks obliging and White can immediately make use by playing} 16. Bf1 (16. h4 $14) 16... Nf6 17. Ne5 Ne4 18. Ndf3 Bd6 19. Bd3 $14) 16. Qb3 b5 (16... Rxc1+ 17. Rxc1 Qb8 18. Re1 $14) (16... Rc7 17. Qe3 Bd6 18. Ne5 $14) 17. Qe3 $146 (17. Rxc8 Qxc8 18. a4 bxa4 19. Qxa4 Nb6 20. Qd1 Nc4 $11 {Giri - Topalov, Stavanger, 2022}) (17. a4 Qb6) 17... Nb6 18. Ne5 Rc7 (18... Nc4 19. Ndxc4 bxc4 20. b3 Ba3 21. Rc2 cxb3 22. Qxb3 Rxc2 23. Qxc2 $14) 19. Ndf3 Nc4 20. Qe2 $14 *

