{[%evp 0,15,13,13,15,15,15,15,10,-18,8,15,19,13,13,11,10,15]} {In this mini-chapter, I would like to point out one specific move order.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O Nbd7 7. Qc2 {It's important to start with this move which is preventing the setups based on the immediate ...b7-b6.} ({Worse is} 7. b3 {when after} b6 8. Bb2 Bb7 9. Nc3 c5 $11 {the position is completely equal.}) ({The pawn sacrifice} 7. Nc3 dxc4 8. a4 (8. e4 Rb8) 8... a5 9. e4 Nb6 $13 {leads to an unclear position.}) ({Another option is} 7. Qd3 a6 8. b3 b6 9. Bb2 Bb7 10. Nc3 (10. Nbd2 c5) 10... Re8 $13 {Again the position is unclear.}) 7... c6 {Black has nothing better than this move.} ({Starting with} 7... b6 $2 {is a mistake because of} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 ({The point is that} 8... exd5 {will be met by} 9. Qc6 $1 Rb8 10. Bf4 $16 {with a huge advantage for White.}) 9. a3 Bb7 10. e4 N5f6 11. Nc3 c5 12. Rd1 cxd4 13. Nxd4 $16 {White enjoys a considerable advantage in this symmetrical position. Black should always reckon with the advance e4-e5.}) (7... c5 $6 {does not correlate well with 6...Nbd7 -} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 (8... exd5 9. Nc3 $16) 9. Rd1 $36) 8. Nbd2 {is a transposition to Chapter 10.} *

