{[%evp 0,41,13,13,15,15,10,15,8,-18,12,4,13,13,27,10,18,-9,19,19,3,11,17,2,11,12,10,-26,-23,-29,-29,-37,-37,-30,-35,-31,-23,-23,3,-3,-10,-5,-29,-37]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c6 7. Qc2 ({A different theoretical line is} 7. b3 b6 8. Bb2 Bb7 9. Nc3 Nbd7 {, though White may cleverly make other useful developing moves before deciding about Bc1.}) 7... b6 (7... Nbd7 {is back to Chapter 10.}) (7... dxc4 8. Qxc4 b5 {will be examined in Chapter 17.}) (7... a5 {is normally connected with b7-b6 and activating Bc8.} 8. Rd1 $5 {is the main move, let me mention the minor alternatives at first:} (8. Nbd2 b6 9. e4 Bb7 10. Rd1 (10. e5 Nfd7 {[%cal Gc6c5]}) 10... c5 $13 {[%cal Gb8c6]}) 8... b6 {is, as said, the most consistent, but then} (8... b5 $6 9. c5 Nbd7 10. Nbd2 $5 {[%cal Ge2e4]} (10. Bf4 Ne4 11. Nbd2 f5 12. Nxe4 fxe4 13. Ne5 $14) 10... Qc7 11. Nf1 {[%cal Gc1f4]} (11. e4 e5 12. exd5 cxd5 13. Nf1 exd4 14. c6 d3 15. Qxd3 Nc5 16. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gf1e3]}) 11... Ne4 ({here} 11... e5 $2 {is beautifully refuted by} 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Bf4 Nfd7 14. e4 $1 g5 $140 15. Bxe5 Nxe5 16. exd5 $18) 12. Bf4 Qa7 13. N1d2 {is absolutely fine for White, as the Stonewall will be immediately destroyed, e.g.} f5 14. Nxe4 fxe4 15. Ne5 $16 {[%cal Gf2f3]}) (8... Na6 $6 9. a3 $16 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gf3e5,Gb1c3]}) (8... Nbd7 {looks natural, but then White has a good reason to revert to} 9. Nbd2 {[%cal Ge2e4]} c5 (9... b6 10. e4 Ba6 ({as soon as the d7-square is already occupied, here} 10... Bb7 11. e5 {forces Black to the awkward} Ne8 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nf1 $16 {[%cal Gf1e3]}) 11. b3 (11. e5 Ne8 12. h4 $16) 11... c5 12. exd5 exd5 13. Bb2 Rc8 14. Nf1 $16 {[%cal Gf1e3]}) 10. cxd5 exd5 (10... Nxd5 11. a3 $14) 11. Nb1 {[%cal Gb1c3]} b6 12. Nc3 Bb7 13. dxc5 Bxc5 (13... bxc5 $6 14. Nh4 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gh4f5]} Nb6 15. Nf5 $16) 14. Nd4 $14) 9. Ne5 $1 {poses certain problems:} Bb7 (9... Nfd7 10. Nd3 $1 {must be even more unpleasant to the side with less space -} (10. cxd5 cxd5 ({but not} 10... Nxe5 $6 {because of the tactical motif} 11. d6 $1 Qxd6 12. Bf4 $16 {[%emt 0:00:08] , which is also due to the delayed development of Nb1}) 11. e4 Nxe5 12. exd5 Ng6 13. d6 Ra7 14. dxe7 Nxe7 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bxe7 Rxe7 17. Nc3 Bb7 18. Bxb7 Rxb7 19. d5 exd5 20. Rxd5 Nd7 21. Qd2 $14) 10... Bb7 (10... Ba6 11. b3) 11. b3 Na6 12. a3 $1 (12. Bb2 Nb4) 12... Qc8 (12... c5 13. dxc5 Naxc5 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Bxd5 exd5 16. Nf4 $16 {[%csl Rd5]}) 13. Bb2 Rd8 14. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Ge2e4]}) (9... Ba6 10. b3 {may just transpose to the abovementioned line}) 10. Bf4 (10. Nc3 Nfd7) 10... Nh5 (10... Nfd7 11. Nxd7 Nxd7 12. e4 $14) ({analogously to 8....Nbd7 from above, after} 10... Nbd7 {White can concentrate on the central advance by} 11. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Nh5 12. Bc1 Nhf6 13. e4 $14) (10... Na6 11. a3 Rc8 12. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Ra6]}) 11. Be3 Nf6 12. Nc3 Nfd7 13. Rac1 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. Bd4 Qb8 (15... c5 $2 16. Be3 $18) 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. e4 dxe4 18. Bxe4 Bxe4 19. Qxe4 $14) 8. Rd1 (8. Nbd2 {is once again the less flexible continuation, even more, Black has} c5 $1 9. dxc5 (9. e4 Nc6) 9... bxc5 10. e4 Nc6 11. exd5 exd5 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. a3 Rb8 $11) (8. b3 Bb7 {is supposedly of no independent significance.}) 8... Bb7 ({After} 8... Ba6 {Black must once again reckon with} 9. Ne5 {and now:} Nfd7 (9... Qc8 10. b3 $5 ({one more clever twist in White's opening strategy rather than the common} 10. Bf4 Nbd7 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Nc3 Bb4 13. Rac1 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Nh5 15. Be3 Nhf6 16. c4 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Ng4 18. cxd5 Nxe3 19. fxe3 Qxc2 20. Rxc2 Rac8 21. Rxc8 Rxc8 $14) 10... Nbd7 11. Ba3 $146 {(the point!)} Bxa3 12. Nxa3 Qc7 (12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 Ng4 14. Qc3 f6 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. Nc2 $14) 13. Nd3 Rac8 14. Rac1 Qb8 15. Qb2 $14) 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. e4 {with indisputable White's initiative:} Nxe5 (11... Nf6 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Nc3 Bb7 14. Be4 $1 h6 15. a3 Nd7 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. Bh7+ Kh8 18. Nxd7 (18. Bf5 Nxe5 19. dxe5 d4 $13) 18... Qxd7 19. Bf5 Qd8 20. Qe2 Bd6 21. Be3 $14) 12. exd5 Nd3 {is dubious in the view of} 13. d6 $1 ({a very entertaining line is} 13. dxe6 Nc6 14. Qxc6 Rc8 15. Qa4 fxe6 16. Qxa6 Nxf2 17. Re1 Rxc1 $1 18. Rxc1 Qxd4 19. Qe2 Bc5 $5 20. Re1 Nd3+ 21. Kh1 Nf2+ $11) 13... Qxd6 (13... Nb4 14. dxe7 Qxe7 15. Qa4 Nd5 16. Nc3 Bb7 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Bxd5 exd5 19. Bf4 $14) 14. Bxa8 Nb4 (14... Qxd4 $2 15. Nc3 $18) 15. Qa4 Be2 (15... b5 $6 16. Qb3 N8c6 17. Bf4 Qd7 18. Bxc6 Qxc6 19. Rc1 Qa8 20. a4 $16) 16. Rd2 b5 17. Qb3 Bc4 18. Qd1 Bg5 (18... N8c6 $6 19. Bxc6 Qxc6 20. Nc3 Nd5 21. Nxd5 Bxd5 22. Rc2 Qd7 23. Bf4 $16) 19. f4 Bf6 {was drawn in Naniwadekar - Santoso, ICCF email, 2020, but White has every reason to play on for the full point, for instance} 20. Bg2 Qb6 (20... N8c6 21. Nc3 Bxd4+ 22. Kh1 $14) 21. Kh1 N8c6 22. b3 Bd5 (22... Bxd4 $6 23. Bb2) 23. Nc3 Bxg2+ 24. Rxg2 Rd8 25. Bb2 h6 26. Rb1 Rxd4 27. Qf1 $14) ({It is no longer surprising that} 8... Nbd7 {urges White to} 9. Nbd2 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Bb7 (9... Ba6 10. e4 Nxe4 ({if} 10... Rc8 {, as we already know,} 11. e5 Ne8 12. h4 $14 {would be unpleasant to meet}) 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 (12... f5 $6 13. Nxc6 Qe8 14. b4 Bd6 15. a4 Bb7 16. b5 $16) 13. dxe5 Qc7 14. Bxe4 h6 {and White can exert maximum pressure on the opponent by means of the sound pawn sacrifice} 15. Be3 {[%cal Gc4c5]} Qxe5 (15... Rfd8 16. c5 Qxe5 17. cxb6 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 axb6 19. Bxb6 $14) 16. Rd7 (16. Bf4 $140 Qf6) 16... Bc5 17. Re1 Bxe3 18. Rxe3 Qc5 19. b3 {with plenty of compensation due to the active pieces -} b5 20. Bh7+ Kh8 21. cxb5 {and now:} Qxb5 ({the trade} 21... Qxc2 22. Bxc2 {does not bring any relief -} cxb5 (22... Bxb5 23. a4 Ba6 24. Rc3 $16) 23. Be4 Bc8 24. Rc7 Rb8 25. Rd3 {[%cal Gc7f7]} g5 26. Rxa7 $16) 22. Bd3 Qb6 23. Bxa6 $140 Qxa6 24. Rc3 Rad8 25. Rxc6 Qa5 {is relatively the best option -} 26. Rcc7 Rxd7 27. Rxd7 $14) 10. e4 dxc4 (10... dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Qc8 (12... Nf6 $6 13. Qe2 $16 {[%cal Gc4c5]}) 13. Bf4 c5 14. d5 $36) 11. Nxc4 c5 12. e5 $5 (12. Nfe5 cxd4 13. Rxd4 Qc7 14. Bf4 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Qc6 $11) 12... Nd5 13. Qe4 $5 (13. dxc5 Rc8 $132) 13... b5 (13... cxd4 14. Qg4 Kh8 15. Nxd4 $14) 14. Nd6 Bxd6 15. Ng5 g6 (15... f5 $6 16. Qe2 Be7 17. Nxe6 Qb6 18. Nxf8 Rxf8 19. dxc5 Qxc5 20. a4 $16) 16. exd6 ({the insertion of} 16. Qh4 h5 {is definitely risky -} 17. exd6 c4 $13) 16... N7f6 ({here} 16... c4 $2 {is apparently a serious tactical error in the view of} 17. Nxe6 $1) 17. Qh4 $5 $146 {is a tempting pawn sacrifice, after} (17. Qe5 c4 18. a4 (18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Qd7 20. Bxd5 Bxd5 21. Qf6 Qd8 22. Bg5 {is a very ambitious try, to which an adequate reaction is} h6 $5 23. Qxd8 Rfxd8 24. Bxd8 Rxd8 $44 {with ample compensation for the exchange}) 18... b4 (18... a6 19. Bd2) 19. Nf3 Nd7 (19... Ng4 20. Qe2 Qxd6 21. h3 Ngf6 22. Qxc4 $14) 20. Qe2 c3 21. Ne5 cxb2 22. Bxb2 a5 23. Qb5 $1 N7b6 24. d7 Ba6 25. Qc6 Ra7 26. Qc5 Ra8 $11) 17... Qxd6 (17... c4 $2 18. Bxd5 $1 Bxd5 19. Qh6 $1 Qxd6 20. Bf4 Qe7 21. Be5 Rfc8 22. Re1 c3 23. bxc3 Rxc3 24. g4 $18 {[%cal Gg5h7]}) 18. dxc5 Qxc5 19. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3e5] White is enjoying a promising long-term initiative, giving the supremacy on the dark squares, for example} Rfc8 (19... Qc4 20. Rd4 Qc2 21. Bh6 Qxb2 22. Re1 $36) 20. Ne5 (20. b3 Qb4 21. Nd4 a6 22. Bb2 $44) 20... Qc7 21. Re1 (21. Qd4 Ne8) (21. Bxd5 Nxd5 22. Rxd5 Bxd5 23. Bf4 Qd8 24. Bg5 f6 25. Bxf6 Qc7 26. Rf1 Qc2 27. Ng4 h5 28. Nh6+ Kh7 29. Ng4 Kg8 $11) 21... Ne8 22. Bh6 $44) 9. Nc3 (9. b3 Nbd7 {is once again likely to transpose.}) 9... Nbd7 (9... dxc4 $6 {is an obvious concession, after} 10. Ne5 {White regains the pawn with interest.}) ({in reply to} 9... Na6 {a very solid option is} 10. b3 c5 $140 11. dxc5 bxc5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Bb2 $14 {with excellent play against the hanging pawns.}) 10. b3 {White can hardly do without this move.} (10. e4 $6 dxc4 $15) 10... Ba6 {is further questioning the c4-pawn. Here are the alternatives in brief:} (10... c5 $6 11. cxd5 Nxd5 (11... exd5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Bb2 $16) 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 (12... exd5 13. Bb2 $14) 13. e4 Bb7 14. Bf4 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Rc8 16. Qe2 $36) (10... Qc8 11. a4 $5 (11. Bb2 Ba6 {- 10...Ba6 11.Bb2 Qc8}) (11. e4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 c5 14. d5 Re8 15. Qc2 Bf6 16. Rb1 exd5 17. cxd5 h6 $13) 11... a5 ({just like on the previous move} 11... c5 {fails to impress -} 12. cxd5 Nxd5 (12... exd5 13. Bb2 $16) 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. e4 Bb7 15. d5 $36) 12. Bb2 Re8 13. e3 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1]}) (10... Rc8 11. e4 {is more justified here due to the shaky Bb7:} Nxe4 (11... dxe4 12. Ng5 $1 h6 (12... c5 13. dxc5) 13. Ngxe4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 c5 15. Nxc5 $1 Bxg2 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. Kxg2 b5 18. c5 e5 19. dxe5 Qc6+ 20. f3 Bxc5 21. Bb2 $16) 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 {forces Black to spend time on} Ba8 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 14. Qe2 c5 15. dxc5 Bf6 16. Rb1 bxc5 17. Bf4 $16) 11. Bf4 (11. Nd2 {does not pretend for much -} Rc8 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 12. a4 c5 $11) ({Compared to the text, the bishop has a limited scope after} 11. Bb2 {, Black can still choose 11...Qc8 or fight for the initiative by} dxc4 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Ne4 b5 $13) ({In case of} 11. Qd3 {the central break can be prepared by} Qc8 (11... c5 {at once is perhaps a bit premature -} 12. Bb2 Rc8 13. Nb5 $14) 12. a4 c5 13. Ba3 Rd8 $13) 11... Nh5 {The typical reaction.} (11... dxc4 $6 12. bxc4 Bxc4 13. Nd2 Ba6 14. Bxc6 Rc8 15. Qa4 Nh5 16. Be5 $1 (16. Bxd7 Rxc3) 16... Nxe5 17. dxe5 Qc7 18. Qxa6 Qxe5 19. Nc4 Qxc3 20. Rac1 Qf6 21. Bf3 g6 22. Qxa7 $16) (11... Rc8 12. e4 dxc4 {and here again} 13. Nd2 {appears to be a temporary pawn sacrifice, for example} b5 (13... c5 $6 14. d5 $16) (13... Nh5 14. Be3) 14. bxc4 bxc4 15. Bf1 Qa5 (15... Bb4 16. a3 Ba5 17. Bd6 Re8 18. Bb4 $14) 16. Nxc4 Bxc4 17. Bxc4 Nb6 18. Bf1 $14) 12. Bd2 Nhf6 (12... b5 $6 13. Ne5 Rc8 14. e4 $16) (12... f5 $6 13. a4 $16) 13. e4 {Now this push contains a real pawn sac.} dxc4 14. e5 Nd5 15. Ne4 cxb3 (15... c3 $6 16. Nxc3 Nb4 17. Qb2 Nd3 (17... c5 18. Bf4 $36) 18. Qb1 Nb4 19. a3 Nd5 {took place in Cheparinov - Faydi, Europe Echecs INT, 2021. The unsuccessful knight cruise has given to White a free hand on the opposite wing -} 20. h4 $16) (15... b5 16. Neg5 g6 17. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]} c5 18. h5 Kg7 19. Ne4 Rc8 20. Nd6 Bxd6 21. exd6 $40 {[%csl Rg7]}) 16. axb3 Be2 (16... Bb5 $6 {is by no means preventing the knigside assault in the already familiar manner -} 17. Neg5 g6 18. h4 Kg7 19. h5 $40) 17. Neg5 g6 18. Re1 Bxf3 19. Nxf3 c5 20. dxc5 Bxc5 (20... bxc5 21. h4 $44 {[%csl Rg7,Rg8][%cal Gh4h5,Ga1a4]}) ({White's ongoing initiative is spread all over the board after} 20... Nxc5 21. b4 $1 Nb7 (21... Nd7 $6 22. Nd4 $1 Nxb4 23. Qb1 Nd5 24. Nc6 Qe8 25. Bh6 $16) 22. Nd4 (22. Qc6 Rb8) 22... Rc8 23. Qa4 a5 24. Nc6 Qd7 25. Nxe7+ Qxe7 26. bxa5 bxa5 27. h4 $14 {[%csl Gd2,Gg2,Rg8]}) 21. h4 $44 *

