{[%evp 0,43,13,15,15,10,9,12,9,-18,4,8,12,10,17,-13,14,18,21,32,34,29,32,0,30,-1,8,5,8,-15,6,6,2,3,15,2,19,0,0,43,52,42,39,45,49,53]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 c5 (7... Nc6 8. Qxc4 Qd5 {We have already had such a position in Chapter 5 with an extra  (Bc1-d2) move for White, which allowed him to defend the queen by a rook. Here} 9. Qa4 {[%cal Gb1c3] is more or less necessary, but White gets anyway a better version of the line 5...Nc6 6.Qa4 Qd5!? 7.0-0 Nc3, for instance} Bd7 10. Nc3 Qh5 11. Qc4 (11. Qd1 Rad8 12. Bf4 Bd6 13. Bg5 $14) 11... Rfd8 12. Rd1 Rac8 13. h3 $14) (7... Bd7 {is of completely different essence to the featured ideas for an early c7-c5 advance - by this maneuver Black is trying to neutralize firstly the danger along the h1-a8 diagonal:} 8. Qxc4 (8. Ne5 Nc6 (8... Bc6 9. Nxc6 Nxc6 10. e3 Na5 11. Bd2 c5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Qa4 Nc6 14. Qxc4 Be7 15. Rd1 Qb6 16. Bc3 Rfd8 17. Na3 $14) 9. Qxc4 $5 ({in case of} 9. Nxc6 Bxc6 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Qxc4 Qd5 $11 {Black's better mobilization seems to counterbalance the structural defects in his queenside formation}) 9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 b5 11. Qc2 Nd5 12. Nc3 c6 13. h4 $5 Qb8 14. Bf4 Rd8 15. Ne4 $14) 8... Bc6 9. Nc3 Nbd7 {has been covered in Part 1.}) (7... Nbd7 8. Qxc4 c5 $6 {is inferior in comparison to the leading text -} 9. Rd1 Nb6 10. Qc2 Nbd5 11. dxc5 Qc7 12. Bg5 Qxc5 13. Qxc5 Bxc5 14. Ne5 Be7 15. Na3 h6 16. Bd2 $16 {with typical Catalan endgame, in which Black is firmly on the defensive side.}) 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Relatively the best continuation, here are some alternatives:} (8... Qc7 9. Na3 ({good enough is} 9. Qxc4 Qxc5 10. Qxc5 Bxc5 11. Nc3 Nc6 12. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Gf1d1]}) 9... Qxc5 10. Nxc4 Nc6 11. Be3 Qf5 12. Qb3 e5 13. Rfd1 $16 {[%cal Gc4d6]}) (8... Nbd7 9. Na3 Nxc5 10. Nxc4 Bd7 11. Nfe5 $14 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gc1f4]}) (8... Na6 9. Na3 $14 {[%cal Ga3c4] will just transpose to the latter line}) ({in reply to} 8... Bxc5 {White can play} 9. Qxc4 {with tempo, thus preserving the playing initiative after} Qe7 10. Nc3 ({opening the diagonal in front of the Catalan Bg2 with} 10. Ne5 $5 Bd6 $140 11. Nd3 {deserves serious attention -} e5 12. Nc3 Be6 13. Qb5 Nc6 14. Bg5 $14) 10... b6 (10... Bd7 11. Ne5 Rc8 12. Qh4 {does also justify White's move 9 -} Bc6 13. Nxc6 Nxc6 14. Rd1 h6 15. Bd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2e1,Ga1c1]}) 11. Bg5 ({the insertion of} 11. a3 a5 {[%emt 0:00:18] is far from necessary, White may even lack the opportunity to play b2-b4 at a proper moment, see move}) 11... Nbd7 12. Nh4 $5 Rb8 13. Bf4 Bd6 (13... e5 14. Bg5 {[%cal Gc3d5]} Bb7 15. Bxb7 Rxb7 16. Rac1 $14) 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Rfd1 Qc5 16. Qxc5 Nxc5 (16... bxc5 17. Rd2 $14) 17. Nf3 Bd7 ({the exchange of the light-squared bishops after} 17... Bb7 $6 18. Ne5 {will just help the opponent to increase the queenside pressure, for example} a5 {19.b4 b5, fixing the c6-forepost, has been the imminent threat, but the text move exposes the b5-square as well -} 19. Rac1 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 $16 {[%cal Ge5c6,Gc3b5]}) 18. b4 (18. e4 $5 Bc6 19. Ne5) 18... Na4 19. Rxd7 Nxc3 20. Rxa7 Nfd5 21. Ne5 Ra8 22. Rb7 {and, even though Black is able to eliminate all queenside pawns after} Nxb4 23. Rxb6 Rxa2 {, the problems with his stranded knights may lead to 4 vs. 3 endgame -} 24. Rxa2 Nbxa2 25. e3 $14) 9. Na3 $5 ({Black's life seems easier after the straightforward} 9. Qxc4 e5 10. Nc3 Qa5 {[%cal Gc8e6]}) 9... Bxc5 10. Nxc4 Nb4 ({After} 10... Bd7 11. Nce5 {White's pair of bishops will be an asset in the long run -} Qb6 ({or} 11... Nxe5 12. Qxc5 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 $14) 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. Bd2 Rac8 14. Rac1 $14) (10... Qe7 11. Nce5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Rd8 13. Bd2 $14) 11. Qd2 Qc7 {This retreat does not avoid the exchange of the queens.} ({Perhaps we are going to see in the future more practical examples with} 11... Qe7 {e.g.} 12. a3 Rd8 13. Qc3 Nbd5 14. Qc2 Bd7 15. b4 Bb6 16. Bb2 Bb5 17. Rac1 Rac8 18. Qb3 $14) 12. Qf4 Qxf4 13. Bxf4 Nbd5 14. a3 Nxf4 ({Yet another typical Catalan endgame with White's lasting pressure along the open files and on the queenside arises after} 14... Bd7 15. b4 Bb5 16. Rfc1 Be7 17. Bd6 Bxc4 18. Bxe7 Nxe7 19. Rxc4 Rfc8 20. Nd2 Ned5 21. Rac1 Rxc4 22. Rxc4 Rd8 23. Kf1 $14) 15. gxf4 Nd5 16. e3 Rd8 (16... Bd7 17. Nfe5 Ba4 18. Rfc1 $14) 17. Rac1 Be7 18. Nfe5 f6 19. Nf3 Rb8 20. Rfd1 Bd7 21. Nd4 g6 22. Na5 $14 *

