{[%evp 0,41,15,15,17,9,7,15,9,-18,8,8,12,10,19,4,4,-20,13,25,25,18,27,-30,19,22,4,-16,-16,10,-8,-7,-13,-6,20,27,34,-32,1,-52,-10,22,10,12]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6 $5 8. Bg5 $5 (8. Qxc4 {does not at all confuse Black's smooth development after} Bb7 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gb8d7]}) ({On the contrary, a principled line is} 8. Ne5 {, when Black has a rich compensation for the exchange after} Qxd4 9. Bxa8 Qxe5 10. Bf3 Nd5 11. Qxc4 Ba6 12. Qa4 c5 $44) 8... Nd5 ({Black should be aware that an automatical move like} 8... Bb7 $4 {is typically refuted by} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Ng5 $1 $18 {Cheparinov - Bekker Jensen, Sibenik, 2016}) ({To} 8... Ba6 {critical is} 9. Nbd2 ({here} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Ng5 {is far from convincing in the view of} Bxg5 11. Bxa8 Qxd4 $44) (9. Ne5 Nd5 {does not bring dividends to White as well}) 9... Nd5 (9... c3 $6 10. bxc3 Bxe2 11. Rfe1 $44 Ba6 (11... Bxf3 12. Nxf3 c6 13. Ne5 $36) 12. Ne5 c6 13. c4 Bb7 (13... Qxd4 $2 14. Ne4 $18) (13... h6 14. Bf4) 14. Rad1 h6 15. Bf4 $36) ({in reply to} 9... Nbd7 {it makes sense to accept the offered exchange -} 10. Ne5 $1 (10. Nxc4 Bb7 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc7c5]}) 10... Nxe5 11. Bxa8 Qxd4 12. Bg2 {with various possibilities for both sides:} c3 $5 ({the easiest reaction to} 12... Qc5 $6 {J. Fernandez - P. Mary, ICCF email, 2014, is} 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Bxe4 f5 16. Bg2 $16) (12... b5 13. b3 $1 Ba3 14. bxc4 Nxc4 15. Rad1 Qc5 (15... Qb2 16. Qd3) 16. Nxc4 Qxc4 (16... bxc4 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. Qc3 $16) 17. Rd2 $1 h6 (17... Qxc2 $2 18. Rxc2 c5 19. Bc1 Bxc1 20. Rfxc1 c4 21. Rd2 $18 {[%cal Gd2d6]}) 18. Be3 Bb4 19. Rc1 $1 ({much more resolute than} 19. Qxc4 bxc4 20. Rc2 Rd8 $14) 19... Bxd2 20. Qxd2 Qa4 21. Rxc7 Nd5 22. Rxa7 $16) 13. bxc3 Qg4 14. Bf4 Qh5 (14... Ng6 15. Bf3) 15. Bxe5 Qxe5 16. Rfe1 $14) (9... b5 10. Ne5 ({a safe approach is} 10. a4 Nc6 11. axb5 Bxb5 12. Nxc4 $14) 10... Nd5 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. b3 c3 (12... cxb3 13. Nxb3 $44 {[%cal Gb3c5]}) 13. Bxd5 exd5 14. Qxc3 b4 15. Qf3 Qd6 16. Rfc1 ({a firework like} 16. Ndc4 {does not achieve much after} Qe6) 16... Nd7 17. Nxd7 ({there is no need for entering} 17. Nc6 Rfe8 {either}) 17... Qxd7 18. e3 Bb5 19. a4 bxa3 20. Rxa3 $14) 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Nxc4 {is a key tabiya:} c5 (11... Nd7 12. Qa4 ({worth exploring is the immediate} 12. Nfe5 $5) 12... Bb7 13. Rac1 ({the practice has seen} 13. Nfe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 c5 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Qa5 f6 17. Nc4 Nb6 18. Nxb6 axb6 19. Qxb6 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 Rab8 21. Qa6 Rxb2 22. Rfb1 Rfb8 23. Rxb2 Rxb2 24. a4 Qd7 25. Qa8+ Kf7 26. Qf3 Qd5 27. a5 Rb7 28. a6 Ra7 29. Ra5 g5 $11 {and an extra pawn will not mean much in the eventual rook ending, so the game E. Stefanov - F. Baumbach, ICCF email, 2018, has petered out quickly to a draw}) 13... c5 14. Nfe5 $5 (14. Qa3 N5f6 {has occurred in Aronian - Fressinet, Paris, 2016, White can claim a lasting edge by} 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Rfd1 Rfd8 17. Nd4 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qb7+ 19. Kg1 $14) (14. Rfd1 N5f6 15. Nfe5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 $14) 14... Nxe5 15. dxe5 Qc7 16. Nd6 Bc6 17. Qc4 $14) 12. Rac1 {is arriving at another important crossroads:} Rc8 {is another alternative, albeit a bit artificial one:} (12... Nd7 13. Qa4 Bb7 {is back to 11...Nd7}) (12... Nc6 $5 13. dxc5 $1 ({much simpler than} 13. Qa4 Ncb4 14. a3 b5 15. Qa5 bxc4 16. axb4 Nxb4 17. dxc5 Rab8 $11) 13... Qxc5 (13... bxc5 $6 14. Qa4 Qb7 15. Qa3 Ncb4 16. Nfe5 $16) {and here} 14. Qa4 $1 {is a reminder to the opponent that his opening problems are far away from being solved:} Ndb4 (14... Bb5 15. Qb3 Qb4 16. Nd6 $1 Qxd6 (16... Qxb3 $6 17. axb3 Bxe2 18. Rxc6 Bxf1 19. Kxf1 $16) 17. Qxb5 Rac8 18. Rfd1 Qb4 19. Qxb4 Ncxb4 (19... Ndxb4 20. Ne1 $1 {[%cal Ga2a3]}) 20. a3 Nc6 21. Ng5 $1 Nce7 (21... h6 22. Bxd5 exd5 23. Nf3 Ne7 24. Nd4 $14) 22. Rxc8 Rxc8 23. e4 Nf6 24. Bh3 $1 {[%cal Gg5e6] An incredible resource - in spite of the reduced material, the combination of the threats e4-e5 and Nxe6 is impossible to meet without dropping material -} Kf8 25. e5 Nfd5 26. Nxh7+ Ke8 27. Ng5 Rc2 28. Rb1 Nc6 29. Bg2 Nxe5 30. Bxd5 exd5 31. Re1 f6 32. Nf3 Kf7 (32... Kd7 33. Nxe5+ fxe5 34. Rxe5 Kd6 35. Rg5 $16) 33. Nxe5+ fxe5 34. Rxe5 d4 35. Rd5 Rd2 $14) (14... Qb5 $6 15. Qa3 $16 {[%cal Gc4d6]}) ({if Black prefers to retreat the bishop, then it is the right moment for} 14... Bb7 15. Nce5 Qb4 16. Qxb4 Ndxb4 17. a3 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Nd5 19. f4 Rac8 20. Rfd1 $14) 15. Ne3 $1 (15. Nce5 Qb5 16. Qxb5 Bxb5 17. a3 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Nd5 19. Rfe1 Rac8 $11) 15... Qb5 16. Qxb5 Bxb5 17. a3 Na6 (17... Bxe2 18. axb4 Bxf1 19. Rxc6 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 Rac8 21. b5 $14) 18. Nd1 $1 {[%cal Gd1c3]} ({An excellent concrete idea rather than the tame} 18. Rfe1 Rac8) 18... Nc5 19. Nc3 Ba6 20. b4 Nb3 21. b5 Nxc1 22. Rxc1 Bb7 23. bxc6 Bxc6 24. Rb1 $1 {(a start of a subtle consolidating regrouping)} Rac8 25. Rb3 Rfd8 {and now the common maneuver} 26. Ne5 Be8 27. f4 f6 28. Nd3 {is fixing White's advantage -} Bf7 29. a4 e5 30. Ra3 exf4 31. gxf4 $14) 13. Qd2 $1 $146 {seems to be an essential improvement:} (13. Nce5 {is instructively neutralized by} Nd7 $1 (13... f6 $6 14. Nd3 Nd7 15. Qa4 Bxd3 16. exd3 $16 {Dubov - Bacrot, Chess.com INT, 2022}) 14. Qa4 Bxe2 15. Qxd7 Qxd7 16. Nxd7 Bxf1 17. Rxf1 c4 {with sufficient counterplay due to the possession of the c-file after} 18. Nde5 c3 19. bxc3 Rxc3 {, for instance} 20. Ng5 Rc7 $11) 13... Nc6 (13... Bxc4 14. Rxc4 Nd7 15. e4 N5f6 {and now:} 16. e5 $5 (16. dxc5 Rxc5 17. Rxc5 bxc5 (17... Nxc5 18. e5 Nd5 19. Nd4 $14) 18. Qe2 Rb8 19. Rc1 h6 20. b3 $14) 16... Nd5 17. Rcc1 h6 18. Qe2 Rab8 19. Rfd1 $14) (13... Nd7 14. b3 $1 Bb7 15. Rfd1 $14) 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. b3 Rd8 16. Nfe5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Rac8 18. Qb2 $14) 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nbd2 (10. Ne5 {is time-consuming and Black should easily equalize -} Bb7 11. Qxc4 (11. Nxc4 c5) 11... c5 12. Nc3 (12. dxc5 Rc8 $11) 12... Nd7 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. dxc5 Nxc3 15. Qxc3 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Rac8 $11 {and it is time to agree to a draw, Nisipeanu - Bacrot, Zagreb, 2019}) ({the same belongs to} 10. Qxc4 Ba6 11. Qc2 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Gc7c5]}) (10. e4 Nb4 11. Qc3 c5 $5 {is double-edged -} 12. a3 N4c6 13. d5 Na5 14. Nbd2 Ba6 $13) (10. Rc1 $5) 10... b5 (10... Bb7 {does not mind restoring the material balance, but Black has still to prove equality after} 11. Nxc4 Nd7 (11... c5 $6 {is obviously untimely because of} 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Ng5 $1 g6 14. Ne4 Qe7 15. Rfd1 Nc6 16. Ncd6 Ncb4 17. Qc1 f5 18. Qg5 fxe4 19. Qxe7 Nxe7 20. Nxb7 e3 21. f4 $16) 12. a3 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4] , which sets a small positional trap:} c5 (12... N5f6 13. b4 $1 {is a definite strategical achievement for White -} Be4 (13... c5 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. b5 a6 16. a4 $14) 14. Qb2 c5 (14... a5 15. b5 c6 16. bxc6 Bxc6 17. Rfc1 $14) 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. b5 a6 17. a4 Rfb8 18. Nfd2 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 $14) 13. e4 (13. dxc5 Rfc8) 13... N5f6 14. e5 Nd5 15. Rfe1 $14 {and, though the hole on d6 is not that critical, White has all the time to choose the best moment for accessing it.}) (10... Ba6 {- 8...Ba6.}) 11. h4 $5 $146 {[%cal Gf3g5] A fresh and quite reasonable idea.} (11. a4 c6 12. e4 Nb6 13. a5 N6d7 14. b3 cxb3 15. Nxb3 Bb7 16. a6 $5 (16. e5 Na6 $13) 16... Nxa6 17. Na5 Nb6 18. Nxc6 Qe8 $11 {Gelfand - Laznicka, Novy Bor, 2018}) (11. e4 Nb6 $13) (11. b3 {is the most popular continuation and now:} c3 {is a sensible choice for limiting White's active options:} (11... cxb3 12. Nxb3 a5 13. Ne5 (13. Rfc1 c6 14. Ne5 a4 15. Nc5 $44 {may just transpose}) 13... a4 14. Nc5 c6 15. a3 Ra7 16. Rac1 Rc7 {Grischuk - Nakamura, Paris, 2019} 17. Rfd1 $44) 12. Ne4 (12. e4 cxd2 13. exd5 exd5 14. Qxd2 Qd6 {is practically the leading line without the insertion of 11.h4!? h6 -} 15. Rac1 c6 16. Rfe1 (16. Ne5 Be6) 16... a5 $11) 12... b4 13. a3 {has appeared twice in my own practice:} Nc6 $1 {at once is fully playable -} (13... f5 14. Nc5 Nc6 15. axb4 Ncxb4 16. Qc1 Bd7 17. Ne5 (17. Nxd7 Qxd7 $13 {Yu Yangyi - Cheparinov, China, 2018}) 17... Bb5 18. Re1 $44) 14. axb4 (14. Neg5 {appears to be dangerous only at first sight, as shown by} f5 15. e4 fxe4 16. Qxe4 g6 17. axb4 Rb8 $132) 14... Ncxb4 15. Qc1 Ba6 16. Re1 c2 17. Nc5 (17. Qd2 Bb5 18. Rec1 Rfd8) 17... Bb5 18. Qd2 a5 19. Rec1 (19. Ne5 c6 (19... Rfd8 $5) 20. Be4 Rfd8 21. Bxc2 f6 22. Nf3 e5 $11 {Van Wely - Cheparinov, Hockenheim, 2018}) 19... c6 {looks roughly balanced either:} 20. e3 (20. Ne1 e5 21. e3 (21. e4 exd4 22. Qxd4 Nc7 23. Nxc2 Rfd8 $11 {Bosiocic - Bacrot, Batumi, 2018}) 21... exd4 22. exd4 Rfe8 23. Nxc2 Nxc2 24. Rxc2 Nb4 $11) 20... Rfd8 21. Ne1 {does not differ much after the same break} e5 22. Nxc2 Nxc2 23. Qxc2 exd4 24. exd4 Qf6 25. Rd1 h6 26. h4 Nb4 27. Qc3 Ra7 $11) 11... h6 {The threatened knight jump should not be underestimated:} (11... Bb7 12. b3 $1 ({the immediate} 12. Ng5 f5 13. e4 Nb4 {is providing Black with an additional option for} 14. Qc3 h6 {, when the pawn can be regained by} 15. Nxe6 Qxe6 16. Qxb4 {with mutual chances after} Qb6 17. a4 a6 18. d5 Nd7 $13) 12... c3 (12... c5 {looks like the lesser evil -} 13. bxc4 bxc4 14. dxc5 $14 {, see the next line as well}) 13. Ng5 f5 (13... g6 14. Bxd5 exd5 15. Qxc3 b4 16. Qd3 $14) 14. e4 $1 cxd2 15. exd5 Bxd5 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Qxd2 $44 {Compared to the leading text, here White has frightening possibilities along the e-file in addition.}) (11... Nc6 12. b3 Ncb4 (12... c3 {is naturally running into} 13. Ng5 g6 14. Bxd5 exd5 15. Qxc3 $14) 13. Qc1 c5 $1 (13... cxb3 14. Nxb3 $36 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ga2a3,Ge2e4]}) ({here} 13... c3 {is not better at all -} 14. Ne4 $16) 14. a3 Nc6 15. bxc4 bxc4 16. Qxc4 Nxd4 17. Rfc1 Rd8 18. Kf1 Nb6 19. Qxc5 Qxc5 20. Rxc5 $14) (11... a5 {is interesting, though it must not discourage the standard break:} 12. b3 {can be executed at once -} (12. Ng5 $5 g6 (12... f5 $6 13. b3 cxb3 14. Qxb3 Rd8 15. e4 fxe4 16. Ngxe4 Nc6 17. Nf3 $36) 13. b3 cxb3 14. Nxb3 a4 15. Nc5 Na6 16. Nd3 $44) 12... cxb3 (12... c3 13. e4 cxd2 14. exd5 exd5 15. Ng5 g6 16. Bxd5 Ra6 17. Qxd2 $14) 13. Nxb3 c6 14. Rfc1 a4 15. Nc5 Rd8 16. Rd1 $44) 12. b3 c3 (12... cxb3 13. Nxb3 $44) 13. e4 ({A plausible alternative is} 13. Ne4 b4 14. a3 f5 15. Nc5 Nc6 16. axb4 Ncxb4 17. Qc1 Bd7 $13 {with very attractive play after the natural centralization of the other knight. The same position, but without the advances of the h-pawns, has arisen in my aforementioned game with Yu.}) 13... cxd2 14. exd5 exd5 15. Qxd2 Qd6 (15... c6 16. Ne5 {is going to transpose.}) 16. Rac1 c6 17. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5]} a5 ({White has sufficient compensation after} 17... Be6 18. Rc5 Rc8 19. Rfc1 $14 {as well.}) 18. Rc5 a4 19. Rfc1 axb3 20. axb3 Bd7 21. Qf4 $44 (21. Bf1 $5 {[%cal Gf1d3]}) *

