{[%evp 0,68,15,15,9,9,9,15,7,-18,2,2,10,6,6,-13,22,31,33,35,37,31,15,13,51,52,50,-17,-19,-19,-15,-15,23,-7,-26,13,-13,-21,71,71,97,85,76,23,65,39,9,9,7,7,16,3,10,33,22,32,12,12,15,15,28,28,28,23,29,28,28,23,23,23,47]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 c6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qd3 $5 ({The main theoretical continuation is} 9. Qc2 Bb7) (9. Qb3) 9... Nbd7 ({In reply to} 9... Bb7 {White can use the opportunity for} 10. Ne5 $1 Qc8 {protects Bb7, but Black has also to react adequately to} ({there are tactical drawbacks of the queen's location after} 10... Qb6 {, here is a beautiful sample line in confirmation to this statement -} 11. Be3 Rd8 12. Nc3 c5 13. dxc5 Qc7 14. c6 $1 Nxc6 (14... Bxc6 $2 15. Nxc6 Rxd3 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. exd3 b4 18. Bxa8 bxc3 19. bxc3 $16) 15. Qxb5 $1 {(the next big point!)} Nxe5 16. Qxb7 Qxb7 17. Bxb7 Rab8 18. Ba6 Rxb2 19. Rab1 Rc2 20. Rfc1 Rxc1+ 21. Rxc1 $16 {Even though Black has succeeded to win the pawn back, to his sorrow the endgame on the board is quite one-sided.}) 11. Nc3 {as well:} c5 {must be shot at equality, but in fact, White can stay on top in many ways:} ({to} 11... Rd8 {very interesting is} 12. Qf3 $5 {[%cal Gc3b5]} b4 13. Ne4 Rxd4 $140 14. Ng5 $16) (11... Nbd7 12. Nxd7 (12. Bg5 $5) 12... Qxd7 13. Rd1 $14) 12. Bxb7 (12. Nxb5 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Nc6 14. Qf3 (14. Bg5 h6 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Qe4 Nxe5 17. Nd6 Qc6 18. dxe5 Qxe4+ 19. Nxe4 Bxe5 20. Rab1 c4 21. Rfc1 Rfb8 22. Rxc4 Rxb2 23. Rxb2 Bxb2 $14) 14... Nxe5 (14... Nxd4 $6 15. Nxd4 cxd4 16. Nc6 Bc5 17. Rd1 Qd7 18. Bg5 $16) 15. dxe5 Nd7 16. Rd1 (16. Qe4 Nxe5) 16... Nxe5 17. Qe4 Qc6 18. Qxc6 Nxc6 $14) 12... Qxb7 13. dxc5 ({good enough is} 13. Qxb5 Qxb5 14. Nxb5 a6 15. Na3 cxd4 16. Rd1 Bxa3 17. bxa3 Rc8 18. Rxd4 Nc6 19. Nxc6 Rxc6 $14 {with an extra, albeit doubled, pawn}) 13... b4 14. Na4 Nc6 15. Nxc6 (15. Qf3 Nd5) 15... Qxc6 {and now:} 16. b3 (16. Qc2 $5 Rfc8 17. Bf4 (17. Be3 Nd5 18. Bd4 {is less to the point because of the tricky} Nb6) 17... Bxc5 ({it is not clear how Black is going to profit from a trade like} 17... Nd5 18. Rac1 Nxf4 19. gxf4 $14) 18. Nxc5 Qxc5 19. Qxc5 Rxc5 20. Rfc1 $14) 16... Bxc5 (16... Rfd8 17. Qf3) 17. Bb2 Be7 {and here comes the instructive exchange} 18. Bxf6 $1 (18. Rac1 Qd5) 18... gxf6 (18... Bxf6 19. Rac1 Qb7 20. Nc5 Qe7 21. Nd7 $14) 19. Rfc1 Qd6 20. Qxd6 Bxd6 21. Rc6 Be5 22. Rac1 $14 {with a lasting edge in this endgame, in which the enemy queenside pawns are attractive targets.}) 10. Be3 {[%cal Gf1c1,Gb1d2]} (10. Bg5 $5 {is worth of attention and, as it often happens,} Bb7 {is countered by} 11. Ne5 $1 ({in case of} 11. Nbd2 Qb6 12. a4 a6 {the same} 13. Ne5 {can be answered with} Rad8 14. Nxd7 Rxd7 15. Nb3 bxa4 16. Rxa4 c5 $11) 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd5 ({perhaps} 12... Nd7 $5 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Qe3 Nb6 15. Rc1 Nc4 16. Qc3 Qc7 {is the more critical option, for instance} 17. a4 a6 18. Na3 c5 19. Nxc4 bxc4 20. Bxb7 Qxb7 21. Rc2 $14 {, though it should be noted that the slightly bizarre placements of Bb7 on the a6-square on moves 16 and 17 must be carefully studied}) 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Nd2 (14. Nc3 $143 Nxc3 15. Qxc3 c5 $1 16. Bxb7 Qxb7 17. Qxc5 Rfc8 18. Qe3 Rc2 19. b3 h6 $44) 14... Qc7 (14... Rad8 15. Ne4 {is another evidence of why White should better preserve the knight}) 15. Ne4 $1 {Here is this jump again! The knight is directed towards the vulnerable c5- and d6-squares, for instance, White will be enjoying a great compensation after} Qxe5 16. Nc5 Bc8 17. Qd2 $44) 10... a5 {Black is striving at active counterplay.} ({Alternatively, the backward c-pawn is in trouble after} 10... Nd5 11. Rc1 Bb7 12. Nbd2 $14) ({Also, after} 10... Bb7 11. Nbd2 Nd5 {White can either transpose to the previous line with 12.Rc1 or firstly fix the control over the c5-forepost by} 12. Nb3 $14 {[%cal Gb3c5,Ga1c1]}) 11. Rc1 b4 $5 {[%cal Gc8a6]} ({Instead, after the natural} 11... Bb7 12. Nbd2 Nd5 13. Ne4 h6 14. Ne5 (14. Nc5 $14) 14... Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nxe3 16. Qxe3 $16 {Black is doomed to passivity, Studer - Pichot, Biel, 2021}) (11... Nd5 12. Nbd2 Ba6 13. Ne4 b4 14. Qd2 Rc8 15. a3 $14) 12. Rxc6 (12. Nbd2 Ba6 13. Nc4 Nd5 14. Qd2 c5 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Nd4 Rc8 $11) 12... Nd5 $146 (12... Bb7 13. Rc1 Ba6 $6 (13... Nd5 14. Bd2 {is back to 12...Nd5}) 14. Qd1 Nd5 15. Bd2 Qb6 16. e4 $5 (16. Be1 $16 {, as in Matlakov - Caruana, Chess.com INT, 2022, is good enough}) 16... N5f6 17. Be3 Nxe4 (17... Ng4 18. Nbd2 Nxe3 19. fxe3 $16) 18. Nbd2 Nxd2 19. Nxd2 Rad8 20. d5 $16) 13. Bd2 Bb7 14. Rc1 Ba6 (14... Rc8 15. a3 Qb6 16. Rxc8 Rxc8 17. axb4 Nxb4 ({the other capture} 17... axb4 {may turn this pawn into a constant source of concern after the exemplary} 18. Ne1 Bf6 19. e3 Nc7 20. Nc2) 18. Qb3 $14 Bxf3 $140 19. Bxf3 Nc2 (19... Qxd4 20. Rxa5 Ne5 21. Rb5 $14) 20. Qxb6 Nxb6 21. Rxa5 Nxd4 22. Ra7 Bf8 23. Na3 Nxf3+ 24. exf3 $14) 15. Qc2 N7b6 $1 (15... Bxe2 16. Bxb4 Rc8 (16... Bxf3 17. Bxe7 Nxe7 18. Bxf3 $16) 17. Bc3 (17. Qxc8 Qxc8 18. Rxc8 Rxc8 19. Bd2 Rc2 20. Ne1 Rxb2 21. Bxa5 Bf6 $11) 17... Ba6 18. Nbd2 $14) ({it is not easy for Black to prove compensation after} 15... Rc8 16. Qd1 Qb6 17. Bf1 $14 {either}) ({similar is} 15... Qb6 16. Qd1 Rfc8 17. e3 $14) 16. Bf1 (16. Qd1 Nc4 17. Rc2 Rc8 18. Bc1 Qc7 19. Ne1 Qd7 $44) 16... Rc8 17. Qd1 Nc4 18. e4 Nf6 19. Qb3 $1 a4 20. Qxa4 Qb6 21. Re1 ({A logical idea to stick to the central pawn. Other options are} 21. Bg5 h6 22. Nbd2 Nxd2 $140 23. Bxd2 Bb7 24. Bd3 Nxe4 25. Be3 Rxc1+ 26. Rxc1 Nf6 27. Ne5 Ra8 28. Qb3 Nd5 $44) ({and} 21. Qb3 Na5 22. Qd1 Nxe4 23. Bxa6 Qxa6 $44) 21... Rfd8 22. a3 {The most direct shot at the annoying b4-pawn.} ({The course of the game may become extremely exciting after} 22. Bf4 $5 Bb5 23. Qb3 e5 $1 24. Bxe5 (24. Nxe5 Nxe5 25. Bxe5 Bxf1 26. Rxf1 Ng4 27. Bf4 g5 28. Qf3 Nxh2 29. Kxh2 gxf4 $13) 24... Ng4 $1 25. Bf4 Rxd4 $1 26. Nxd4 Qxd4 27. Qf3 Bc5 28. Bxc4 Bxc4 29. Kg2 Nxf2 {and White is well-advised to give back the exchange, but to simplify to a safe situation by} 30. Nd2 Nd3 31. Nxc4 $1 Nxe1+ 32. Rxe1 Qxc4 33. b3 Qe6 $44) 22... Bb5 23. Qb3 Na5 24. Qd1 Bxf1 25. Rxf1 ({Black seems to have ample compensation after each capture, for example} 25. axb4 Nc6) ({or} 25. Kxf1 Nc6 26. Qe2 (26. e5 Nd5 $44) 26... Nxd4 27. Nxd4 Qxd4 28. Bxb4 Bxb4 29. axb4 Qxb4 30. Nc3 Nd7 31. Red1 Nc5 32. Rxd8+ Rxd8 33. Rd1 Rb8 $44) 25... Nxe4 26. Bxb4 Bxb4 27. axb4 Qxb4 28. Qe1 Qxe1 29. Rxe1 Nb3 30. Ra4 Nd6 31. Nc3 Nc4 32. Nb5 Nbd2 33. Nxd2 Nxd2 34. Kg2 Rc2 $44 *

