{[%evp 0,65,19,31,14,-14,-11,0,0,-14,-5,3,8,11,10,-24,11,11,-8,30,35,34,49,38,133,110,110,128,108,147,85,104,98,54,137,118,122,77,156,105,81,118,108,112,84,99,77,69,56,91,29,23,31,31,31,48,42,27,33,41,47,34,34,35,34,38,27,27]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b5 8. a4 b4 {This is the most common move in the position. Black gains queenside space at the price of accepting inferior pawn structure.} ({A known mistake is} 8... c6 $2 9. axb5 cxb5 10. Ng5 $18 {when White is winning on the spot.}) ({Recently, the move} 8... Bb7 $5 {became quite popular. At this point, White should go for} 9. axb5 a6 10. bxa6 {This is the most principled continuation. Now, Black should try to prove his compensation for the pawn.} ({Harmless is} 10. Nc3 {when the play might continue} axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 12. Nxb5 Bd5 {Black is ready to proceed with either ...c7-c5 or ...Nc6.} 13. Bf4 {The most natural continuation.} ({The somewhat passive} 13. Rd1 {is will met by} Nc6 14. Qa4 Qb8 15. Nc3 (15. Bf4 Bd6) 15... Qb6 {Black's pressure on d4 and along the b-file provides him excellent counterplay. The concrete threat is ...Bxf3 followed by ...Nxd4.} 16. e3 Rb8 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. Ne5 {It seems that this move puts Black under pressure but after} Qa7 $1 {it becomes clear that White does not have any advantage.} 19. Qxc6 ({Nothing changes} 19. Qxa7 Nxa7 20. g4 Rb4 $11 {[%cal Gf6e4] with equality.}) 19... Rb6 20. b3 Bf8 21. Qa4 Ra6 22. Qb5 Rb6 23. Qa4 Ra6 $11 {White was forced to accept a draw in 1/2-1/2 (25) Nepomniachtchi, I (2792)-So, W (2771) Saint Louis 2022}) 13... c5 14. dxc5 Qa5 {This is the most precise reaction.} ({In case of} 14... Bxc5 $6 15. b3 Qb6 16. bxc4 Be4 17. Qb2 $14 {Black still needs to prove his compensation for the pawn.}) 15. Nc3 Qxc5 16. Rc1 (16. Be3 Qc7 $11) (16. e4 Bb7 $132) 16... Rc8 $1 {The idea behind this move is to recapture on d5 with a knight.} ({Less precise is} 16... Nc6 17. Nxd5 exd5 {1/2-1/2 (23) Ding, L (2799)-Nakamura, H (2736) Chess. com INT 2021 Now, after} 18. Be3 $1 Qa5 19. Nd4 $14 {White could have obtained a slight edge.}) 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxb8 ({Nothing gives} 18. Ng5 g6 {with a fine position for Black.}) 18... Rxb8 19. Nd2 Qb4 ({Also possible is} 19... g6 $5 20. Nxc4 Bg5 21. e3 Bf6 {1/2-1/2 (23) Aberbach Peltzman, A (2265)-Cvak, R (2329) LSS email 2020}) 20. Nxc4 Rc8 21. Qd3 Nb6 22. b3 Nxc4 23. bxc4 g6 $11 {The position is completely equal. White's extra pawn is not important at all.}) 10... Nxa6 11. Qxc4 Bd5 12. Qc3 {This is the only challenging move. The queen is sidestepping Black's gain of a tempo based on ...Nb4.} ({For instance, after} 12. Qd3 Nb4 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 {Black has an excellent compensation for the pawn. The following lines illustrate how the play might continue.} 14. Qd1 {The most natural move.} ({Another possible line is} 14. Qa3 Qb7 15. Nc3 Na2 $1 16. Qxe7 Nxc1 17. Rxc1 Qxb2 $11 {with full equality.}) 14... Na2 $5 (14... c5) 15. Nc3 ({Nothing gives} 15. Bd2 Qb7 16. Nc3 Qxb2 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Qb1 Rb8 19. Qd3 Qb3 $11) 15... Nxc3 16. bxc3 h6 ({A bit less precise is} 16... c5 {which was played in the game 1/2-1/2 (69) Dubov, D (2702)-Nakamura, H (2768) Chess.com INT 2022 At this point, White could have played} 17. Be3 cxd4 (17... Rc8 18. Qa1) 18. Bxd4 $14 {with a slight advantage.}) 17. Bf4 ({Logical but a bit passive is} 17. Ne1 {which was played in the game 1/2-1/2 (39) Chigaev, M (2639) -Esipenko, A (2720) Ufa 2021 At this point, Black could have played} Qa2 $5 18. Qd2 (18. Nd3 Rb8 $44) 18... Qb3 19. Qc2 Rb8 20. Bxd5 Nxd5 21. Bd2 Qxc2 22. Nxc2 Rb3 23. Na1 Rb2 24. Rd1 Nb6 $44 {with excellent compensation for the pawn.}) 17... Rb8 $5 (17... c5 {1/2-1/2 (40) Berkes,F (2671)-Grischuk,A (2775) Struga 2021}) 18. Bxc7 (18. Qa1 Qb7 $44) 18... Rc8 19. Bf4 Rxc3 20. Ne1 Qa2 21. Bxd5 Nxd5 22. Bd2 Rc4 23. Nf3 Rc2 $44 {Again, Black's active pieces provide more than sufficient compensation for the pawn. 1/2-1/2 (56) Nguyen, T (2548)-Huschenbeth, N (2628) Germany 2021}) ({Completely harmless is} 12. Qc2 Nb4 $1 13. Rxa8 Nxc2 14. Rxd8 Rxd8 15. Bf4 (15. e3 c5 $11) 15... Rb8 16. Bxc7 Rxb2 $11 {with full equality. Black is ready to recapture the pawn by means of ...Bxf3 followed by ...Nxd4.}) {The following sequence is pretty forced} 12... c5 13. Be3 Ne4 14. Qe1 Nb4 15. Rxa8 ({Similar is} 15. Nc3) 15... Qxa8 16. Nc3 Nxc3 {Black should probably start with this move before playing ...Nc2.} ({The immediate} 16... Nc2 {is well met by} 17. Nxd5 ({Nothing gives} 17. Qc1 Nxe3 18. Qxe3 (18. fxe3 Rc8 $44) 18... cxd4 19. Qxd4 Bf6 20. Qe3 Nxc3 21. bxc3 Rc8 $11 {with equality 1/2-1/2 (59) Lei, T (2505)-Yoo, C (2457) chess24.com INT 2021}) 17... exd5 {This move is more or less forced.} ({After} 17... Qxd5 $6 18. Qc1 $1 {the opposition on the long diagonal might get pretty annoying.} cxd4 ({Another option is} 18... Nxe3 {Nevertheless, the endgame arising after} 19. Qxe3 cxd4 20. Nxd4 Bc5 21. Qxe4 Qxe4 22. Bxe4 Bxd4 23. b4 $14 {is slightly better for White.}) 19. Bf4 d3 (19... Qb3 $2 20. Ne1 $1 Nxe1 21. Bxe4 f5 22. Bb1 $18 {1-0 (39) Royal,S (2375)-Prokofiev,V (2279) Miercurea Ciuc 2022}) 20. exd3 Qxd3 21. Ne5 {Despite the equal material, White's bishop pair as well as the unstable black pieces give White an edge. A possible line would be} Qe2 22. Qd1 Qxd1 23. Rxd1 f5 24. Nc6 Bf6 25. b4 e5 26. Nxe5 Bxe5 (26... Nxb4 27. Nd7) 27. Bxe5 Nxb4 28. Bf1 $14 {[%cal Gf1c4] Black still needs to work for equality.} (28. Rd7 Nf6 $11)) 18. Qc1 Rc8 {This is Black's best bet on obtaining counterplay.} ({After} 18... Nxe3 19. Qxe3 Qb7 20. Rb1 Rb8 21. h4 $14 {White is better in view of his superior structure.}) 19. Qxc2 cxd4 20. Qd3 dxe3 21. Qxe3 Bc5 {Black tries to play as actively as possible in order to compensate for his inferior pawn structure.} ({The pseudo-active} 21... Rc2 {allows} 22. Ne5 $1 Rxb2 23. Rc1 {when threats such as Nc6 and Qf4 are really annoying.} Rb8 {The idea of this prophylactic move is to defend the f7-pawn via f8.} ({In case of} 23... g6 24. Bxe4 dxe4 25. Kg2 Bf8 26. Rc4 $14 {Black will probably be forced to play for a draw in an endgame with a pawn down.}) 24. Qf4 Rf8 25. Bxe4 dxe4 26. Rd1 $5 {[%cal Gd1d7]} h6 27. Rd7 Bf6 (27... Bg5 28. Qf5) 28. Ng4 Bg5 29. Qf5 $14 {Practically speaking, Black's position remains a bit unpleasant.}) 22. Qf4 Bd6 23. Qg4 {[%cal Gf3g5] Black should now reckon with the threat of Ng5.} Qb7 ({The endgame arising after} 23... g6 24. Ng5 h5 25. Qh4 Be7 26. Bxe4 dxe4 27. Qf4 Qa2 28. Nxe4 Qxb2 29. e3 $14 {is quite annoying for Black.}) 24. Ng5 (24. Nd4 g6) 24... Nxg5 25. Qxg5 $14 {Again, Black needs to work hard in order to make a draw.}) 17. bxc3 Nc2 {The most logical and straightforward continuation.} ({Another possibility is} 17... cxd4 {Nevertheless, after} 18. Bxd4 Nc2 (18... Nc6 19. Qd2 $14) 19. Qd2 Nxd4 20. cxd4 Bf6 21. Qf4 $14 {[%cal Gh2h4,Ge2e3,Gf3e1] White is slightly better. After e2-e3 and h2-h4, he can consider exchanging the bishops with Ne1.}) 18. Qd2 Nxe3 (18... cxd4 19. Bxd4 {would transpose to 17...cxd4.}) 19. Qxe3 cxd4 20. cxd4 Bf6 {Black starts pressing the d4-pawn in the most direct way. Nevertheless, sometimes (especially when White plays e2-e3) the bishop turns out to be restricted on f6.} ({Another option is} 20... Rd8 21. Qf4 h6 (21... Bd6 22. Qh4 h6 {will transpose to the main line.}) ({After} 21... Bxf3 22. Bxf3 Qb8 23. Qe4 $14 {White enjoys a risk-free edge.}) 22. e3 Bd6 23. Qh4 Bb4 {This move is a prophylaxis against Ne1. Remember that exchanging the light-squared bishops is White's main strategic idea in this line.} 24. Qg4 {[%cal Gf3h4] preparing Nh4 on the next move.} Bxf3 25. Bxf3 Qa5 26. Rb1 Bd6 27. h4 $14 {This position was reached in the game 1-0 (58) So, W (2776)-Nepomniachtchi, I (2773) Bucharest 2022. White eventually managed to win this slightly better endgame.}) 21. Qf4 Qb8 {Black insists on exchanging queens. After such an exchange, White's winning chances will be considerably reduced.} ({In case of} 21... Rc8 {White has time to play} 22. Rb1 $1 {activating the rook and planning to exchange the bishops by means of Ne1.} h6 23. Ne1 Bxg2 24. Nxg2 Qa2 25. Re1 $14 {Black does not have enough compensation for the pawn.}) ({A typical position arises after} 21... Bxf3 22. Bxf3 Qb8 {Once again, White should refrain from exchanging queens and play} 23. Qe4 g6 ({Nothing changes} 23... Qd6 24. e3 Rc8 25. h4 g6 26. Rb1 h5 27. Kg2 Kg7 {This position was reached in the game 1/2-1/2 (72) Vidit, S (2730)-Nakamura, H (2768) Kolkata 2022. With a precise play, the game should end in a draw but White can keep playing for a long time.}) 24. Rb1 Qd6 25. e3 Rc8 26. Kg2 Kg7 27. Rb7 Rc7 28. Rb5 Rc8 29. Qb1 $14 {1/2-1/2 (67) Andreikin, D (2729)-Nakamura, H (2766) Chess.com INT 2022. Again, we have the familiar type of position. Black still needs to prove the draw.}) 22. Qg4 {This move is slightly more precise from a practical point of view.} ({is playable as well but after} 22. Qxb8 Rxb8 23. e3 Bxf3 24. Bxf3 g6 25. Rc1 $14 {White's winning chances are considerably reduced without queens. This position was reached in the game 1/2-1/2 (34) Dubov, D (2702)-Nakamura, H (2766) Chess.com INT 2022}) 22... g6 23. e3 h5 24. Qf4 Qxf4 25. gxf4 Bxf3 26. Bxf3 Rd8 27. Rb1 Rd7 28. Kg2 Kg7 $14 {This position occurred in the game 1/2-1/2 (129) Andreikin, D (2729)-Nakamura, H (2760) Chess.com INT 2022. Again, the draw is the most probably result but White will definitely keep playing.}) 9. Nfd2 Nd5 {Recently, this move is played almost exclusively at the highest level.} ({Statistically speaking, a bit more popular is} 9... c6 {which is the old main line. You can see many games by Nakamura (with Black) from this position.} 10. Nxc4 Qxd4 11. Rd1 Qc5 {This is the only reasonable square for the queen.} ({After} 11... Qg4 $6 12. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Rg4] the black queen is already in danger.}) 12. Be3 Qh5 {Black is planning to compensate for his poor structure by means of kingside activity. His next move can be ...Ng4.} ({Remember that the exchange of the queens is favorable for White since Black will remain with his weaknesses.} 12... Qf5 $6 13. Qxf5 exf5 14. Nbd2 Be6 {The most consistent choice. Black is ready to play ...Nd5 in response to Na5.} ({One of White's main strategic ideas is the exchange of the dark-squared bishops. For instance, after} 14... Rd8 $6 15. Nb3 Be6 (15... Nd5 16. Bd4 $16) 16. Bc5 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Bxc5 18. Nxc5 Nd5 19. Na5 Kf8 20. Nd3 $16 {Black is almost lost from a strategical point of view.}) ({Pointless is} 14... Ba6 $6 {when after} 15. Bd4 Ne4 (15... Rd8 16. e3 $16) 16. Rac1 $16 {White enjoys a huge advantage.}) 15. Na5 Nd5 (15... Bd5 16. Rac1 $16) 16. Bd4 Rc8 ({The attempt to give the pawn back by playing} 16... c5 $2 {does not help either. For instance, after} 17. Bxc5 $1 Bxc5 18. Ndb3 Be7 19. Bxd5 Bxd5 20. Rxd5 $16 {White got a tremendous advantage in the game 1-0 (60) Nguyen, A (2507)-Nguyen, Q (2182) Ho Chi Minh City 2019}) 17. Rac1 c5 18. Be5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd2c4] Black's main problem is the unstable d5-knight. White is ready to follow up with Ndc4 on the next move.} Nd7 ({Wrong is} 18... f6 $2 {in view of} 19. Ndc4 fxe5 20. Bxd5 Bxd5 21. Rxd5 e4 22. Rxf5 $18 {when White is already winning.}) 19. Ndc4 N5b6 20. Bd6 $1 {Instead of taking the exchange, White is playing for domination.} ({After} 20. Bxa8 Rxa8 $44 {Black has compensation for the exchange.}) 20... Bf6 21. b3 $1 Re8 22. Bc7 $1 Nxc4 (22... Rac8 $2 23. Nd6 $18) 23. Nxc4 h5 24. a5 $16 {Black is almost paralyzed.}) 13. Nbd2 {The most natural move. Depending on Black's reaction, the knight will go either to e4 or b3.} ({The position arising after} 13. Bf3 Ng4 14. h4 e5 $13 {is unclear.}) 13... Ng4 {The most promising attempt. Black is going for the bishop pair.} ({Less precise is} 13... Ba6 $6 {when} 14. Bf3 $1 {is very powerful. Black does not have a favorable way of defending the queen.} Ng4 ({The position arising after} 14... Qg6 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 f5 17. Bd3 $16 {[%cal Gc4a5,Gc4e5,Ga1c1] is a complete disaster for Black. White will increase the pressure with simple moves such as Rac1 and Ne5. In many cases, even Na5 comes into consideration.}) 15. Bxg4 Qxg4 16. f3 Qh5 (16... Qf5 17. Ne4 $14) (16... Qg6 17. Ne4 $16) 17. Ne4 f5 {This position was reached in the game 1-0 (55) Erdos, V (2609)-Atabayew, S (2443)/Batumi GEO 2018/The Week in Chess 1248. The following long line is quite illustrative. Please, don't try to remember everything by heart!} (17... c5 18. g4 $16) 18. Bc5 $1 fxe4 19. Bxe7 Re8 20. Qxe4 Bxc4 21. Qxc4 Rxe7 22. Rd8+ Re8 (22... Kf7 23. Rad1 $18) 23. Rad1 Qf7 24. R1d6 $1 Kf8 25. a5 Qe7 26. Rxe8+ Qxe8 27. Rxe6 Qc8 28. Qxb4+ Kg8 29. Re7 Na6 30. Qd4 Qf8 31. Rxa7 Rxa7 32. Qxa7 Qc8 33. Qb6 c5 34. Kf2 $16 {Black will hardly manage to survive in this endgame.}) ({Natural but dubious is} 13... e5 $6 {which is well met by} 14. Ne4 $1 {[%cal Ge4f6] White is planning to exchange the f6-knight which is Black's only active piece. Another idea is Bc5.} Ng4 (14... Bf5 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Qb3 $16) (14... Nd5 15. Bc5 $16) 15. h4 Bf5 {This position occurred in the game 1-0 (26) Bu, X (2699)-Yang, K (2331) China 2014} ({The tempting} 15... f5 $2 {fails to} 16. Bc5 $1 Bxc5 17. Nxc5 e4 (17... f4 18. Nd6 $18) 18. Nd6 $18 {when White is winning.}) (15... Qg6 16. Qc1 $16) (15... Nxe3 16. Nxe3 $16) {At this point, White could have played} 16. Qc1 $1 Nd7 17. Ned6 Be6 18. Na5 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 $16 {with a tremendous advantage.}) ({In respose to} 13... Nd5 {we should play} 14. Nb3 $1 {planning to exchange the bishops via c5.} Nd7 ({After} 14... Nxe3 15. Nxe3 $16 {[%cal Ga1c1] it's not clear how Black will develop his queenside.}) 15. Rac1 Ba6 16. Bf3 Qg6 17. Nca5 $1 Qxc2 ({Even worse is} 17... Ne5 18. Bc5 $1 Nxf3+ 19. exf3 Qf6 20. f4 $16 {with a huge advantage for White.}) 18. Rxc2 Nxe3 19. fxe3 Ne5 20. Kf2 Bf6 (20... Rac8 21. Rdc1 $16) (20... Rfd8 21. Rdc1 $14) 21. Nc5 Bc8 22. Nd3 b3 23. Rc5 Nxf3 24. Kxf3 $14 {White has very strong compensation for the pawn.}) 14. Nf3 $1 {This is the most ambitious continuation. The knight can often go to d4.} ({A decent alternative is} 14. Nf1 Nxe3 15. Nfxe3 a5 {[%cal Ga8a7,Gc8a6] This position occurred in the game 1/2-1/2 (82) Vachier Lagrave, M (2789) -Nakamura, H (2769) Paris 2018. Now, after} 16. Rac1 Ra7 17. b3 $44 {White would have obtained a pleasant compensation for the pawn. Black will hardly manage to develop his queenside without accepting some material concessions.}) 14... Nxe3 ({Black finds himself overextended after} 14... e5 $6 15. h3 $5 {White is sacrificing another pawn in order to get access to the important f5-square.} ({Obviously, there is nothing wrong with} 15. Bd2) 15... Nxe3 16. Nxe3 Bxh3 $6 17. Bxh3 Qxh3 18. Qf5 $16 {After the exchange of the queens, Black's position is falling apart.}) 15. Nxe3 a5 {This useful move is the best preparation for ...Ba6.} ({The immediate} 15... Ba6 $2 {will be met by} 16. Rac1 $16 {[%csl Rb8,Rc6] when it's not clear how Black will develop the queenside.}) ({Too passive is} 15... Bb7 16. Nd4 {This position was reached in the game 1-0 (28) Carrasco Miranda, A (2285)-Mena, A (1826) Chess.com INT 2022. White has excellent compensation for the pawn.} Qe5 17. Rac1 Rd8 18. Ng4 $1 Qa5 (18... Qg5 19. h3 $16) 19. Qe4 Qd5 20. Qf4 Qg5 21. Qxg5 Bxg5 22. f4 Be7 23. Ne5 $16 {White's advantage is out of the question.}) ({Very passive is} 15... a6 {when White has a variety of good moves. A possible follow-up is} 16. Nc4 Ra7 17. Nfe5 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ga1d1] planning to double the rooks along the d-file. We are even not interested by the c6-pawn.} f6 ({In case of} 17... c5 {White can keep increasing his pressure by making simple moves -} 18. Rd2 Rc7 19. Rad1 f6 20. Bf3 Qe8 21. Be4 Qh5 22. Nd3 Kh8 23. Nb6 $16 {White enjoyed a huge advantage in the game 1-0 (34) Boreika, V (2211)-Sileika, A (2119) ICCF email 2020}) 18. Bf3 Qe8 19. Nd3 a5 20. Qd2 c5 21. Qe3 $16 {Once again, it's not clear how Black will keep everything together. 1-0 (52) Foenander, P (2198)-Campani, P (2126) ICCF email 2020}) 16. Nd4 Ba6 (16... Ra7 17. Rac1 Ba6 {transpose to 16...Ba6.}) 17. Rac1 Ra7 (17... Rc8 $6 18. Bf3 $1 {White starts gaining important tempis by using the inferior position of the black queen.} ({A decent alternative is} 18. f4 Ra7 19. Bf3 Qg6 20. Be4 Qh5 21. Kg2 c5 22. Nb5 Rd7 23. Bf3 Qg6 24. Qb3 $14 {with nice compensation for the pawn.}) 18... Qe5 (18... Qg6 19. Be4 Qh5 20. h4 Ra7 21. Kg2 $36) 19. Ng4 Qc7 20. Qe4 {[%cal Gg4e5]} Ra7 21. Ne5 $1 {White managed to arrange his pieces in a perfect way. Black should now reckon with Nxf7 as well.} Bg5 (21... c5 $2 22. Nxf7 $18) 22. Rc5 $1 {The only attempt to fight for an advantage.} (22. e3 c5 23. Ndc6 Bb7 24. Rxc5 Nxc6 25. Nxc6 Bxc6 26. Rxc6 Qxc6 27. Qxc6 Rxc6 28. Bxc6 Rc7 $11) (22. Bg4 Bxc1 23. Nxf7 Bc4 24. Bxe6 Bxe6 25. Qxe6 Qd7 26. Nh6+ Kh8 27. Nf7+ $11) 22... Qb6 (22... Be7 23. Rc2 Bf6 24. Ndxc6 $16) (22... Qd6 $2 23. Qc2 $18) 23. Nb3 $1 {An important stabilizing move.} ({In case of} 23. Nxf7 Qxc5 24. Nxe6 Qc4 25. Nfxg5 Qxe4 26. Nxe4 Nd7 27. Nd6 Rb8 $13 {the arising position is very unclear.}) 23... f5 (23... h6 24. Rd6 $36) 24. Qc2 Be7 25. Nc4 (25. Rxa5 c5 26. Nc4 Qc7 27. Rb5 {transposes to 25.Nc4.}) 25... Qc7 26. Rxa5 c5 27. Rb5 $1 {A strong positional exchange sacrifice.} Rd8 ({Nothing changes} 27... Nc6 28. e3 $16 {with an obvious advantage for White.}) 28. Rxd8+ Qxd8 29. e4 Bxb5 30. axb5 g6 31. Qe2 $16 {White has fantastic compensation for the exchange.1/2-1/2 (62) Burmeister,F (2206)-Zunkovic,S (2291) ICCF email 2019}) 18. Bf3 $1 Qe5 ({Similar is} 18... Qg5 19. h4 Qe5 20. Ng4) 19. Ng4 Qc7 20. Bxc6 h5 (20... Qc8 21. Bb5 Qxc2 22. Rxc2 Bxb5 23. Nxb5 Rd7 24. Rdc1 $16) 21. Ne3 Bf6 22. Nb5 Bxb5 23. Bxb5 Qxc2 24. Rxc2 b3 25. Rcd2 Na6 26. Rd7 (26. Nc4 Nc5) 26... Raa8 27. Bxa6 Rxa6 28. Rb7 Bxb2 29. Rxb3 Bf6 30. Rd7 $14 {[%cal Gb3b5] White keeps excellent practical winning chances in this endgame.}) ({Dubious is} 9... b3 $6 10. Qxc4 Ba6 11. Qxb3 c6 {which was also tested in a handful of GM games.} ({Pointless is} 11... Nd5 12. Nc3 Nc6 13. Nf3 $16 {when Black does not have any compensation for the pawn.}) 12. Ne4 $5 $146 {This novelty gives White excellent chances for an advantage.} ({The traditional} 12. Nc3 {is playable as well.} Qxd4 13. Nf3 Qb6 {This position was reached in the game 1/2 (39) Bosiocic, M (2591) -Nisipeanu, L (2674)/Austria AUT 2019/The Week in Chess 1263 At this point, White could have played} 14. Qc2 Nbd7 15. Be3 Qb7 16. Rfb1 {[%cal Gb2b4]} Nd5 17. Nxd5 cxd5 18. b4 Rfc8 19. Qd1 $14 {with a slight but stable advantage.}) 12... Bxe2 ({The alternative} 12... Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Bxe2 {does not solve Black's problems.} (13... Qxd4 14. Nc3 $16) 14. Re1 (14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Qc2+ Kg8 16. Qxe2 Qxd4 17. Rd1 Qb4 18. Nc3 c5 19. Qf3 Qb6 $11 {[%cal Gb8c6]}) 14... Ba6 15. Na3 $1 {This is the key idea. Black cannot develop his queenside without sacrificing the c6-pawn. In this case, the white knight will be ready to occupy the b5-square.} Nd7 (15... Qb6 16. Qc2 $16) 16. Bxc6 Rc8 17. Bg2 Nf6 18. Nb5 $16 {White's advantage is out of question.}) 13. Re1 Ba6 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Be3 Nd7 16. Nc3 Nb6 17. Bxc6 Rc8 18. Bg2 (18. Bb5 Bb7) 18... Bc4 ({In case of} 18... Nc4 19. Ne4 Rb8 20. Qc3 Nxe3 21. fxe3 $16 {Black does not have compensation for the pawn.}) 19. Qd1 Nd5 20. Nxd5 Bxd5 21. b4 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Rc4 23. b5 Bxd4 24. Bxd4 Rxd4 25. Qf3 $14 {The distant passed pawn gives White good practical chances in this endgame.}) 10. Nxc4 c5 ({A positional mistake is} 10... Nc6 $6 {when after} 11. e3 $16 {White has a tremendous advantage. The c6-knight is just blocking the c7-pawn which cannot fight for the center.}) (10... Ba6 $6 11. Rd1 Nc6 (11... c5 12. e4 Nf6 13. d5 $16) 12. b3 $16 {is also bad for Black.}) 11. dxc5 (11. e4 Nb6 $13) 11... Ba6 {The main continuation since the famous predecessor Ding Liren - Carlsen, but another intriguing line has recently made its way into the limelight.} (11... Bxc5 $5 12. e4 (12. Rd1 Nd7 $11) 12... Nb6 (12... Nf6 $6 13. Bg5 Qc7 14. Nbd2 $16) 13. Ncd2 $1 {[%csl Rb6,Rc5][%cal Ga4a5,Gc