ide minor pieces into play than the direct} 20. Be3 Qc2 21. Nd2 Ne5 $13) 20... Nb6 (20... Rfd8 21. Nb3 Qc7 22. Na5 Ne5 23. Bf4 g5 24. Bxe5 Qxe5 25. Qe2 $14) 21. Nb3 (21. Bf3 $5 Rfd8 (21... Qc2 22. Bd1 Qc6 23. Qe2 $16) 22. Kg2 Qc2 23. Qe1 Nd7 24. Bd1 Qd3 25. Nf3 Nc5 26. Bd2 $14) 21... Qc2 22. Nd4 Qc5 23. Be3 ({the time for this move has come;} 23. Nb5 Nc4 24. Nxa7 {as in Pechac - Parkhov, Terme Catez, 2022, can be answered with} Rc7 $1 25. b3 Ra8 26. bxc4 Rcxa7 27. Rxa7 Qxa7 {and the passed b-pawn is an asset, for instance} 28. Bb2 Qa2 29. Qc1 Qb3 $13) 23... Nc4 24. Nc2 Nxe3 25. Nxe3 Rfd8 26. Qe2 $14) 12. Ne3 $1 {Aiming at the proud Nd5, the direct attempts at refutation of the provocative Black's opening strategy do not reach their purpose, for example} (12. Rd1 Nd7 13. c6 Rc8 $13) ({or} 12. e4 Nf6 13. Rd1 Nbd7 $13 14. c6 Rc8 15. Nd6 $140 Bxd6 16. Rxd6 Qc7 17. Bf4 e5 18. Qd1 exf4 19. cxd7 Qxd6 $1 {with original perpetual after} 20. Qxd6 Rc1+ 21. Bf1 Rxf1+ 22. Kg2 Rxf2+ 23. Kg1 Rf1+ 24. Kg2 Rf2+ 25. Kg1 $11) 12... Nd7 $1 (12... Nc6 $2 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. Rd1 $18) 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. c6 Rc8 (14... Nc5 15. Bf4 Rc8 {- 14... Rc8} (15... Ne6 $6 16. Rd1 $16)) 15. Bf4 $1 {Clearly the best - the bishop controls the e5-square and c6-c7 is a permanent threat. Once again Black has sufficient counterchances after the alternatives} (15. Bxd5 Ne5 $132) ({and} 15. Rd1 Ne5 16. Rxd5 Rxc6 17. Qd1 Rd6 18. Rxd6 Bxd6 19. Nd2 Bc5 20. Qe1 Bd4 21. Nf3 Nxf3+ 22. Bxf3 Qf6 $44) 15... Nc5 (15... g5 $2 16. c7 Qe8 17. Bd2 Bc5 18. Qf5 $16) 16. Rd1 $1 {The next precise move!} ({It is still not late to let the opponent think about seizing the initiative by natural moves like} 16. c7 $6 Qd7 17. Nd2 g5 $1 18. Be5 f6 19. Bd4 Rxc7 20. Nb3 (20. Qd1 Ne6 21. Nb3 Bc4 {Ding Liren - Carlsen, Zagreb, 2019,} 22. Be3 d4 23. Nxd4 Nxd4 24. Qxd4 Qxd4 25. Bxd4 Rd8 {Bxe2=}) 20... Nxb3 21. Qxb3 Bxe2 22. Bxd5+ Kg7 23. Rfe1 Rd8 24. Be6 Qxd4 25. Rxe2 Qd3 $11 {Cheparinov - Deac, Douglas, 2019.}) 16... d4 (16... Bc4 {is a major alternative, its assessment is depending on the forced sequence} 17. Nd2 $1 Bxe2 18. Nb3 $1 Bxd1 (18... Nxb3 $6 {is definitely imprecise in the view of} 19. Rxd5 Nxa1 20. Qxe2 $16 {and Be7 is badly hanging}) 19. Rxd1 Qe8 (19... Rxc6 $2 20. Bxd5 $18) (19... Nxb3 $6 {is running into the intermediate} 20. c7 $1 Rxc7 (20... Qe8 21. Qxb3 $16) (20... Qd7 21. Bxd5 Na1 {Predke - Kezin, Cheboksary, 2021,} 22. Qb1 $18) 21. Bxc7 Qc8 22. Bxd5 Bd6 (22... Nc5 23. Ba5 $1) 23. Bxf7+ Rxf7 24. Rxd6 Qxc7 25. Rc6 Nd4 26. Rxc7 Nxc2 27. Rxc2 $16) 20. Bxd5 Nxb3 21. Qxb3 Rxc6 22. Bxc6 Qxc6 23. Rc1 Qf6 24. Kg2 $14 {has taken place in Lehnhoff - Bonatti, LSS email, 2020, White has a small, but lasting pull after both the textmove and} (24. h4 $5)) 17. h4 $1 {One more subtlety.} ({Instead,} 17. Be5 {looks very tempting, the critical position for its verdict arises after} d3 $1 (17... Ne6 18. Qe4 $16) 18. exd3 Bxd3 (18... Nxd3 $2 19. Be4 $18) 19. Qc1 (19. Qd2 Ba6) 19... Re8 $1 (19... f6 $6 20. Bc3 $1 a5 (20... bxc3 21. Nxc3 Kh8 22. Qe3 $16) 21. Qe3 Re8 22. Bd4 Bd6 23. Bxc5 Rxe3 24. Bxe3 $16) (19... Nb3 $2 20. Qe3 $18) 20. Nd2 Be2 (20... Bf8 $2 21. Nc4 f6 22. Qf4 $16) 21. Re1 ({the exchange sacrifice} 21. Nc4 Bxd1 22. Qxd1 {, by which White puts his hopes entirely on the mighty c-pawn, is very promising, then} Nd3 $1 {is initiating an immediate counterplay against the main supporting piece. The entertaining sequence} 23. c7 ({a fantastic counterattack is demonstrated in} 23. Qb3 Nxf2 $1 24. Kxf2 Bc5+ 25. Kf1 Rxe5 $1 26. Nxe5 Qd4 $1 27. Qxf7+ $140 Kh8 28. Bh3 Qg1+ 29. Ke2 Qe3+ $11) 23... Qd7 24. Bh3 Qd5 $1 (24... Qxh3 25. Qxd3 Qe6 26. Rd1 $44) 25. Bxc8 Rxc8 26. b3 f6 $1 {is resulting in an ending with Black's sufficient activity for the missing pawn -} 27. Nb2 fxe5 28. Qxd3 Qxd3 29. Nxd3 Rxc7 30. Nxe5 Rc3 31. Rb1 Bf6 32. Nc4 Kf7 $44) 21... Ba6 $1 (21... Nd3 $143 22. c7 Qd7 23. Bc6 $1) 22. c7 Qd7 23. Nf3 Nd3 24. Rd1 Bd6 25. Bxd6 Qxd6 26. Qd2 Qxc7 27. Ne1 Nxe1 28. Rxe1 b3 $11) 17... h6 $1 {Resuming the possible g7-g5 thrust.} ({It is far from easy to prove equality after} 17... Re8 18. Nd2 $1 {and now:} Bxe2 (18... Bf8 19. c7 Rxc7 20. Bxc7 Qxc7 21. Ne4 b3 22. Qc1 Qe5 23. f4 Qf5 24. Nxc5 Bxc5 25. e4 Qh5 (25... dxe3 $2 26. Rd5 $18) 26. Kh2 Be2 27. Rd2 d3 28. Qc3 Rd8 29. Bf1 Bxf1 30. Rxf1 Be3 31. Qc7 Rf8 32. Rg2 d2 33. Qd7 $16) 19. c7 $1 Rxc7 (19... Qd7 20. Rdc1 Rxc7 (20... Nd3 $2 21. Bc6 $1 Qh3 22. Bxe8 Nxf4 23. Qe4 $18 {Gelfand - Deac, Bucharest, 2019}) 21. Bxc7 Qxc7 22. Re1 {- 19...Rc7}) 20. Bxc7 Qxc7 21. Re1 d3 22. Qc4 Bf6 23. Bf1 $1 (23. Qxb4 Rb8 24. Qc4 Qd6 25. Bd5 Ne6 $14) 23... Bxb2 24. Rad1 $1 {An attractive move in order to overprotect Nd2. Black has still to look for compensation, e.g.} Qe7 25. Nb1 $1 (25. Qxb4 Qe5) 25... Bf6 26. Rc1 Ne6 27. Bxe2 dxe2 28. Rxe2 $16 {G. Kerr - C. Schroeder, FICGS email, 2019.}) (17... Ne6 {is another natural continuation, but Black has yet to find an antidote to} 18. Be5 {, when he seems to lose the fierce fight for the d4-square after} d3 $5 19. exd3 Bd6 20. d4 $1 Bxe5 21. dxe5 Nd4 22. Qd2) 18. Bf3 {The best moment for overprotecting the e2-pawn.} ({The course of the events after} 18. Be5 {is quite similar to the one on the previous move -} d3 19. exd3 Bxd3 20. Qc1 (20. Qd2 Ba6) 20... Re8 {and here the extraordinary idea for} 21. Na3 $5 bxa3 $140 22. b4 {is best met by} Qb6 $1 (22... Nb3 23. Qxa3 Nxa1 24. Bxa1 Qd6 25. Rxd3 Qxb4 26. Qa2 $14) 23. bxc5 Bxc5 24. Rxd3 Rxe5 25. Rb1 Bxf2+ 26. Kh2 Re1 27. Qxe1 Bxe1 28. Rxb6 axb6 29. Rxa3 Kf8 $11) (18. Nd2 $5 Bxe2 19. Re1 d3 20. Qc4 Ne6 21. Be3 Bf6 (21... Qc7 $6 22. Nb3 Rfd8 23. Rxe2 dxe2 24. Qxe2 $16) 22. Bxa7 {has been recently tried:} Qa5 $1 {is defending the own b-pawn before taking the enemy one -} (22... Bxb2 $6 23. Qxb4 $1 Bd4 (23... Bxa1 $143 24. Rxa1 $16 {Tabatabaei - Nihal, Chess.com INT, 2021}) 24. Bxd4 Nxd4 25. Qc5 Qf6 26. Rac1 Rfe8 27. Rc3 Nxc6 28. Bh3 $1 Bf3 (28... Ne7 29. Bxc8 Rxc8 30. Ne4 Qe6 31. Qe3 $16) 29. Rxe8+ Rxe8 30. Rxd3 Re1+ 31. Bf1 Ne5 32. Qc8+ Kh7