{[%evp 0,41,15,20,20,9,7,7,7,-18,2,6,6,10,11,-16,-13,-11,-9,0,-9,15,10,21,19,19,28,16,52,19,27,24,23,-3,34,40,45,39,35,22,25,30,32,33]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4 Nc6 (8... b6 $6 {is dubious -} 9. Ne5 Ra7 (9... Nd5 10. Qxc4 Bb7 11. Nc3 {and the sample line} b5 12. Qb3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 $16 {illustrates well how quickly the difficulties in front of Black can grow up - after the disappearance of both developed pieces his situation is rather grim}) 10. Rd1 $1 ({as soon as it is impossible to protect that pawn, there is no necessity for} 10. Qxc4 Bb7) 10... Bb7 11. e4 $1 {The subtle point of the previous move - it is suddenly hard for Black to come up with a satisfactory reply -} Nc6 (11... Nbd7 12. Nxc4 $16) 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. Nc3 $36 {[%cal Gd4d5,Gc1f4]}) (8... a5 $6 9. Rd1 $1 (9. Na3) (9. Qxc4) 9... Na6 (9... Bd7 10. Ne5 {reveals the subtlety of White's move order, for instance} Bc6 11. Nxc6 Nxc6 {and, due to the reinforcement of the d4-pawn, White can play} 12. Qxc4 $1 Nd5 $140 13. Nc3 $36) 10. Qxc4 Nb4 11. Nc3 ({indeed, White has no particular reason to deviate from the moves in the last note, but, for instance, there is also} 11. Bd2 $5 c6 12. Ne5) 11... c6 12. e4 b6 13. Qb3 Ba6 14. Bf4 $14) 9. Qxc4 Na5 (9... Qd5 {is an important alternative, such a position has already been examined with an extra Bc1-d2 and with the a-pawns still on their initial squares. In the latter case, White has moved the queen to the a4-square, which is now occupied, so} 10. Nbd2 Rd8 ({in the only known game} 10... Rb8 {has been answered with} 11. Qc3 $1 (11. e3 b6) 11... Rd8 (11... Bb4 12. Qc2 {is a sort of critical position -} Nxd4 (12... b6 13. e3 Bb7 14. Ne1 Qd7 15. Nd3 Nd5 16. Nc4 $14) 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Qxc7 Bd7 15. Nf3 Qd6 16. Qxd6 Bxd6 17. Rd1 Bc7 18. Ne1 Nd5 19. Nd3 $14 {with yet another favorable Catalan endgame}) 12. e3 {and the queen has been chased to a different square -} Qf5 13. Nc4 Nd5 14. Qb3 Ndb4 15. Bd2 Bd7 16. Rfc1 $14 {Pinzon - Oen, ICCF email, 2019}) 11. e3 {may transpose to the lines from above, Black has other options at his disposal, but none of them seems to lead to full equality -} Qxc4 (11... Qh5 12. h3 $36 {[%csl Rh5]}) (11... a5 12. b3 $14) 12. Nxc4 Nd5 (12... Bd7 13. Nfe5) 13. Bd2 $14 {[%cal Gf1c1,Gf3e5]}) 10. Qc2 b6 (10... Nd5 $6 11. Bd2 $1 {is going to leave Black's queenside in ruins after} b6 12. Bxa5 bxa5 13. Nbd2 Nb4 14. Qc3 {and the attempt to cut the knot and reach the desired equality by} c5 $5 {is falling short with correct play -} 15. dxc5 Bb7 16. Nb3 Rc8 17. Rfd1 Qc7 18. Nfd4 $1 Bxg2 $140 19. Kxg2 Bxc5 20. Nxc5 Qxc5 21. Qxc5 Rxc5 22. Rac1 $1 Rd5 23. Nb3 $16) 11. Ne5 Bb7 (11... Qxd4 $6 12. Bxa8 Qxe5 {and White has a pleasant choice between 13.Bf4 and} 13. Bf3 $16) (11... Nd5 {is once again met by} 12. Bd2 $1 Bb7 $140 13. Bxa5 bxa5 14. Nc6 Bxc6 ({a very important line goes on with} 14... Nb4 15. Nxd8 $1 Nxc2 $140 16. Nxb7 Nxa1 17. Nxa5 Rab8 18. Nc6 Bd6 19. Na3 Bxa3 20. bxa3 Nc2 21. Nxb8 Rxb8 22. Rc1 Nxd4 23. Bf1 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rc7][%cal Ge2e3,Gc1c7]}) 15. Qxc6 Rb8 16. Nc3 Nb4 (16... Rb6 17. Qc4 $14) 17. Qc4 {with the better pawn structure. The latter can be modified by} Nc2 18. Rad1 Rxb2 19. d5 $1 e5 20. Qxa6 Rb6 21. Qd3 {, White is still on top after} Nb4 22. Qc4 $14) 12. Bxb7 Nxb7 13. Nc6 Qd7 {This interesting novelty was recently played by Caruana.} (13... Qe8 14. Rd1 $1 {Here too, the interpolation of this rook move is very useful.} (14. Bg5 {is very tempting but after} h6 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Qxc7 Na5 {Black can rely on compensation -} 18. e3 Rfc8 19. Qd6 ({the verdict is valid even for a two-pawns deficit -} 19. Qxb6 Nc4 $44 {[%cal Ga8b8]}) 19... Rc6 20. Qb4 Rac8 $44) (14. Nd2 {is worth checking as well -} Bc5 15. Ne4 Qxc6 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. b4 Nd6 18. bxc5 bxc5 19. Qxc5 Qxc5 20. dxc5 Nf5 21. Bb2 Kg7 $14) 14... Bc5 15. Ne5 Bd6 16. Nd2 h6 (16... c5 17. Ndc4 cxd4 18. Nxd6 Nxd6 19. Rxd4 Nf5 20. Rd3 $14) (16... Nd5 17. Nd3 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4]}) 17. b3 $5 Nd5 (17... c5 $2 18. Ndc4 Bxe5 (18... cxd4 $2 19. Nxd6 Nxd6 20. Ba3 $18 {has logically ended in a miniature, Kosakowski - Liyanage, Chess.com INT, 2022}) 19. Nxe5 Qe7 20. Ba3 Rfc8 21. Rac1 $16) 18. Ndf3 Nb4 19. Qb2 f6 20. Nc4 b5 21. Ne3 $14) 14. Rd1 Rfc8 15. b3 $1 {The most challenging reaction. White is getting ready to exchange the dark-squared bishops via a3.} (15. Bg5 {This move was tried in the game Ding-Caruana, Bucharest,2023. In this game, Black managed to easily neutralize White's temporary initiative. Actually, White's last move is a kind of a draw offer. The game went} h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Ra3 Nc5 18. Nb4 Nb7 19. Nc6 Nc5 20. Nb4 Nb7 21. Nc6 Nc5 $11 {with a threefold repetition. This is how the game ended.}) ({The idea behind ...Qd7 is that the natural} 15. Nd2 {can be answered with} Bc5 $1 {In this case, the standard 16.Ne5 does not work since the d4-pawn is hanging. The main line of the computer goes} 16. Ne4 Qxc6 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. b4 Rd8 19. bxc5 Nd6 $132 {Even though at the beginning the engines like this position for White, at higher depth, it becomes clear that Black has an excellent counterplay.}) 15... Bf8 ({The alternative} 15... Na5 {fails to equalize in view of} 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Ba3 Qd7 18. Nc3 $14 {White has a slight advantage. He is ready to follow with e2-e4.}) 16. Ba3 $1 Qd5 {The most active continuation.} ({In case of} 16... Bd6 17. Bb2 Nd8 18. Ne5 Qe8 19. Nd2 $14 {White is slightly better since Black's position seems rather awkward.}) ({After} 16... Nc5 17. Na5 $5 Nce4 18. Bxf8 Kxf8 19. Nc4 $14 {White keeps a considerable edge in view of his better central control and Black's unstable central knight.}) ({Obviously, after} 16... Bxa3 $6 17. Nxa3 $16 {Black is completely busted.}) 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 18. Ne5 Na5 ({Black is not ready to open the position by means of} 18... c5 {I came up with the following sequence -} 19. Nc3 $1 cxd4 20. Nxd5 Rxc2 21. Nxb6 Rd8 22. Rac1 $1 Rxe2 23. Nc6 Rd6 24. Nxd4 Ra2 (24... Re4 25. Nc6 $1) 25. Rc8+ Ne8 26. Nc4 $36 {White has a very strong initiative in this endgame.}) 19. Nd2 c5 ({Accepting the pawn sacrifice with} 19... Qxd4 $6 {is rather dangerous} 20. Ndf3 Qe4 (20... Qc5 21. Qb2) 21. Qc3 $1 c5 (21... Nd5 22. Qb2) 22. Ng5 Qf5 23. f4 $36 {White enjoys complete domination.}) 20. e4 Qb7 21. d5 exd5 22. exd5 $36 {Lesson 19 4...e7-6...dc4 7.c2 a6 8.a4 8...c6 (and rare moves) White is obviously better.} *

