{[%evp 0,45,20,20,20,13,13,7,15,-10,12,6,13,13,6,-17,5,-9,29,29,31,29,50,31,31,31,29,27,17,11,10,15,15,2,2,15,15,19,27,29,23,31,31,30,24,22,22,26]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4 c5 9. dxc5 ({If} 9. Rd1 $6 {, then after} Nc6 10. dxc5 {the trick} Nb4 $1 $15 {is worth remembering!}) 9... Bxc5 10. Qxc4 ({A very ambitious try is} 10. Nbd2 $5 b5 $1 11. Ng5 ({continuing in the same uncompromising style rather than} 11. axb5 Bb7 $11) 11... Ra7 12. Nde4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 (13. Qxe4 f5 14. Qe5 Bd6 $13) 13... Bd4 $1 (13... Bb6 $6 14. Ng5 $1 f5 (14... g6 15. Ne4 $1 {[%cal Gc1h6]} f6 16. Bh6 Rff7 17. b3 $16) 15. Bf4 $36) 14. Ng5 (14. Rd1 $6 Rd7) 14... g6 (14... f5 $2 15. Rd1 $16 {[%cal Gg5e6,Gd1d8]}) 15. axb5 axb5 16. Rxa7 Bxa7 17. Ne4 f5 ({curiously enough, the previously best} 17... Bd4 $6 18. Bh6 Bg7 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Qc3+ f6 21. Qb4 $36) 18. Bg5 (18. Rd1 Qb6 19. Be3 Qc7 20. Bxa7 Qxa7 21. Nd6 Qc5 $11) 18... Qb6 19. Ra1 (19. Nf6+ Kg7 20. Qc3 Qd4 21. Qa5 {and, as the capture of the knight will cost Ba7, Black should better avoid any suffering along the dark squares by just repeating the moves -} Qb6 $11) 19... Na6 (19... Ba6 {is not aesthetic at all -} 20. Be3 Qc7 21. Bxa7 Qxa7 22. Ng5 Qe7 23. h4 Rd8 24. Qc3 $44) 20. Nf6+ (20. Be3 Qc7 21. Bxa7 Qxa7 22. Nd6 Qc5 23. Nxc8 Qxc8 $11) 20... Kg7 (20... Kh8 $6 21. Rd1) 21. Rd1 e5 22. Nd5 $5 (22. Be3 Qxf6 23. Bxa7 Rd8 $11 {[%emt 0:00:19] is much more acceptable for Black than in the note to move}) 22... Qxf2+ 23. Kh1 {An amazing situation - Black is two pawns up, but the queen is in danger of being trapped. However, the material equivalent for it is usually more than enough.} Bb7 ({as we are going to see, the tempting idea} 23... f4 $2 {is working on the next move, while after} 24. gxf4 Bf5 25. Qc3 Bd4 {, as in Gelfand - Pichot, Biel, 2021, White has missed a golden chance to turn the tables by completing a triangle in the middlegame, namely} 26. Qd2 $1 Nc5 27. fxe5 Be4 28. Bxe4 Bxe5 29. Bg2 Ne4 30. Qe3 Qxe3 31. Bxe3 $18) 24. Qd2 (24. Rf1 Qc5 25. Be7 Qc8 26. Bxf8+ Qxf8 $44) 24... f4 $1 25. gxf4 Nc7 26. Rf1 ({or} 26. fxe5 Nxd5 {and the skirmish} 27. Bh6+ Kh8 28. Bxf8 Be3 $1 29. Bc5 $1 Bxc5 30. e3 Qxd2 31. Rxd2 {is finishing in peace after} b4 $1 32. Bxd5 c3 33. bxc3 bxc3 34. Bxb7 cxd2 35. Bf3 $11) 26... Qxf1+ $1 27. Bxf1 Nxd5 28. Bg2 ({or} 28. e4 Nxf4 {and Black seems to have enough counter-chances for the queen -} 29. Bg2 Bd4 30. Qb4 Rf7 31. Bxf4 Rxf4 32. Qxb5 Rf7 33. Qxc4 Bxb2 $11) 28... Be3 $1 29. Qd1 (29. Qe1 $143 h6 ({the trade of the dark-squared bishops} 29... Bxf4 $6 30. Bxf4 Rxf4 {must have brought a deep relief to White in Halkias - Macovei, Arad, 2021,} 31. Kg1 $14) ({instead, Black has a good reason to press for the full point by} 29... c3 $5 30. bxc3 Rc8 31. h4 $140 Rxc3 32. fxe5 Rc1 33. Qxc1 Bxc1 34. Bxc1 b4) 30. Bh4 exf4 $44) 29... Rf7 $1 30. fxe5 (30. h3 Rd7 $44) 30... Bxg5 31. e6 Rf4 $1 32. h3 ({it is never late to blunder, thus} 32. Bxd5 $4 {is brutally refuted by} Rf1+ $1) 32... Bf6 33. e3 Nxe3 34. Qd7+ Kh6 35. Qxb7 Nf5 $44 {/=}) 10... b6 (10... Nbd7 {is taking the e5-square under control, but White can re-route Nf3 to the excellent d3-square by} 11. Ne1 $5 $146 (11. Nc3 b5 12. Qd3 Bb7) 11... b5 12. Qc2 Rb8 13. Nd3 Bd4 14. Nd2 $14 {with typical queenside pressure.}) ({In case of} 10... Qe7 11. Ne5 $5 (11. Nc3) 11... Bd6 12. Ng4 $5 {is bringing originality -} Nxg4 13. Qxg4 e5 14. Qh5 Nd7 15. Nc3 Nf6 16. Qh4 h6 17. Rd1 $14) 11. Ne5 Ra7 12. Nc3 $5 ({The biggest adherent of this system has gradually succeeded to equalize on two occasions after} 12. Nd3 Be7 13. Bf4 Bb7 14. Bxb7 Rxb7 15. Rc1 (15. Nd2 Nd5) 15... Nd5 16. Bxb8 (16. Be5 Bd6) 16... b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. Qb3 Qxb8 19. Nd2 Rc8 20. Ne4 (20. Nf3 g6 $11 {Aronian - Dominguez Perez, Saint Louis, 2019}) 20... h6 21. Rxc8+ Qxc8 22. Rc1 Rc7 23. Rxc7 Nxc7 24. Qc3 Qb7 $11 {Cheparinov - Dominguez Perez, Hengshui, 2019.}) 12... Bb7 {Taking advantage of the inserted moves with the a-pawns.} ({Neverteless,} 12... Qc7 $5 $146 {may well be Black's best shot at equality -} 13. Bf4 {and now:} Nh5 {is the critical continuation, so is with} ({White is obtaining too much material for the queen after} 13... Ng4 $6 14. Nxg4 Bxf2+ 15. Rxf2 Qxc4 16. Bxb8 Rb7 17. Ne5 $1 Qb4 (17... Qc5 18. Ne4 $16) 18. Nd3 Qe7 19. Bf4 $16) 14. b4 (14. Rac1 g5 $13) 14... Bd6 (14... Nxf4 15. gxf4 Be7 ({for} 15... Bd6 16. Qd4 {see 14...Bd6 below}) 16. Rfc1 Qxc4 17. Nxc4 Bb7 {looks like the most natural follow-up, but the fixation of the vulnerable b6-pawn by} ({opening the b-file after} 17... Bxb4 18. Nxb6 Bb7 {may serve better White -} 19. Rab1 Ba3 20. Rd1 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 $14) ({in reply to the logical} 17... Nd7 {the hanging pawn can be offered in return for the penetration} 18. Ne4 $5 (18. b5 {is the alternative, when Black, even though he is about to consolidate after} Rc7 {, has still to play accurately}) 18... Bxb4 19. Ncd6 Ra8 ({Black should tread very carefully, for the impatient} 19... Nc5 $6 {may receive the blow} 20. a5 $1 Nxe4 21. Nxc8 Nc3 22. Nxa7 Nxe2+ 23. Kf1 Nxc1 24. Rxc1 Bxa5 25. Nc6 $16) 20. Rc7 (20. Rd1 Ra7) 20... f5 21. Rac1 fxe4 22. Nxc8 Nc5 23. Ne7+ (23. Nxb6 Rad8) 23... Kh8 24. Rc4 a5 25. Bxe4 Rae8 26. Bc6 Rd8 27. Bb5 $14) 18. b5 {is leaving Black on the defensive side, for example} Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Bf6 (19... axb5 20. Nxb5 $14) 20. Rab1 Bxc3 21. Rxc3 axb5 22. axb5 Rc7 23. Rb4 $1 (23. Rbc1 Rfc8 $11) 23... Nd7 (23... Rfc8 $2 24. Rd3 $18) 24. Ra3 $14) (14... Be7 15. Nc6 Nxf4 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Qxf4 Bb7 18. Bxb7 Rxb7 19. Rfc1 $14) 15. Qd4 Nxf4 (15... Bb7 16. Ne4 Nxf4 17. gxf4 {is just a reversed move order}) 16. gxf4 Bb7 {and Black is getting close to equality by new exchanges -} 17. Ne4 Bxe5 18. fxe5 Bxe4 (18... Nc6 $6 19. Qd6 $1) 19. Qxe4 (19. Bxe4 a5 {and, unlike in the text, Black can effectively reply to 20.Rac1 with 20...Qd8}) 19... Nd7 20. f4 $14) (12... Rc7 13. Rd1 Qe7 14. Qh4 Bb7 15. Bxb7 Rxb7 16. Nd3 $14 {[%cal Gc1g5]}) 13. Bxb7 Rxb7 14. Ne4 Qd4 ({Black will be more or less forced to get rid of the queens after} 14... Be7 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Qe4 $1 (16. Ng4 $143 Bd4 $1) 16... Qd5 (16... Rc7 $6 17. Bf4 $16) 17. Qxd5 exd5 18. Nd3 $5 $146 {is a solid approach for a lasting edge -} (18. Ng4 Bd4 $5 ({an understandable desire to be active even at the cost of the isolated pawn; the latter is a source of concern after} 18... Be7 19. Rd1 Rd8 20. Bf4 $14) 19. Rd1 Nc6 20. e3 Bc5 (20... h5 21. Nh6+) 21. Rxd5 f5 ({the same idea could be realized with} 21... h5 $5 {, when the capture of that pawn is not recommendable exactly because of the text move, therefore} 22. Ne5 Nxe5 23. Rxe5 Rd7 {is expected to come}) 22. Ne5 Nxe5 23. Rxe5 Rd7 24. b3 Rd1+ 25. Kg2 Bd6 26. Re6 Rd8 27. e4 f4 28. gxf4 (28. e5 Bc5 29. gxf4 {has eventually brought victory in Vidit - So, Chess.com INT, 2018, but Black has sufficient counterplay after} a5 $1 30. Rc6 Re1 $44) ({White can rely on compensation for the exchange, but hardly more after} 28. Bxf4 $5 Rxa1 29. Bxd6 Rb1 30. Be5 Rxb3 31. Re7 Kf8 32. Ra7) 28... Bxf4 29. Bb2 R1d2 30. Ba3 $14) 18... Nc6 19. Rd1 $14) (14... Rc7 $6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Qe4 Qf5 (16... Rfc8 17. Bf4 $16) (16... Qe7 17. Bf4 f5 18. Qd3 Rd8 19. Qb3 $16 {led to a flashy win in Blomqvist - Kravtsiv, Stockholm, 2017}) 17. Qxf5 exf5 18. Nd3 $16 {[%cal Gc1f4,Ga4a5]}) 15. Qxd4 {Going for an ending with a better pawn structure is a logical step.} ({Less is promised by the insertion of} 15. Nxc5 bxc5 16. Qxd4 cxd4 17. Rd1 Nbd7 18. Nc6 (18. Nxd7 Rxd7 $11) 18... e5 19. e3 (19. f4 exf4 20. gxf4 Re8 21. Nxd4 Nc5 $44) 19... dxe3 20. Bxe3 Rxb2 21. Ne7+ Kh8 22. Rac1 Ra8 $11) 15... Bxd4 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Nf3 Nc6 (17... Bc5 $143 18. Bh6 Rc8 19. Rac1 Rbc7 20. Rfd1 $14) 18. Bh6 ({The practice has seen} 18. Rd1 Rd8 19. Kg2 Rbd7 (19... Kg7 {is also a solid alternative}) 20. Ra3 Bc5 21. Rxd7 Rxd7 22. Rc3 {Vidit - So, chess.com INT, 2018,} f5 $11) 18... Rd8 19. Rac1 Bc5 20. Rfd1 ({Another promising option is to keep all the rooks -} 20. Rc4 $5 f5 $140 21. Kg2 f6 22. Rfc1) 20... Rxd1+ (20... Rbd7 $2 21. Rxd7 Rxd7 22. a5 $1 $16) 21. Rxd1 Bf8 22. Rc1 $5 (22. Bxf8 $143 Kxf8 23. Rc1 Ne7 $11) 22... Ne7 (22... Bxh6 23. Rxc6 $14 {is the type of endgame White is striving at.}) 23. Bd2 $14 *

