{[%evp 0,47,20,20,20,9,13,18,18,-18,17,13,13,6,10,-2,6,-2,0,5,-9,0,11,8,15,-10,0,11,36,57,55,48,38,38,77,47,42,38,19,-12,0,0,0,0,14,4,16,29,37,6]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bg5 h6 {A popular continuation.} (10... b5 $6 {is not consistent, for example} 11. Qd3 $5 (11. Qc1) (11. Qc2) 11... Nbd7 (11... Be4 12. Qe3 Bb7 (12... Nbd7 $143 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. Nc3 Bb7 15. Ne5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 b4 17. Nc6 Qd6 18. Nxe7+ Qxe7 19. Ne4 $16 {[%csl Rb4,Rc7][%cal Gf1c1]}) 13. Nc3 $14) 12. Rc1 Be4 13. Qe3 Bb7 14. Bxf6 (14. Nbd2 $14) 14... Bxf6 15. Nc3 $14) 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Rd1 $1 {This common move is the best chance to fight for the advantage.} ({Black can confidently enter the complications after} 12. Nc3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 14. Qxc7 (14. Qxd4 Bxd4 15. Bxb7 Ra7 16. Bf3 Nd7 $11) 14... Nc6 15. Qxb7 (15. Ne4 Rab8 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Qxc6 a5 $1 19. Qc7 Rxb2 20. Qxa5 Rxe2 $11) 15... Na5 16. Qc7 (16. Qxa8 Rxa8 17. Bxa8 Qb4 $11) 16... Qd8 (16... Bd8 17. e3) 17. Qf4 (17. Qxd8 Raxd8 $44) 17... Bg5 $5 ({fully playable is} 17... Rb8 18. Rfd1 Qe7 19. Rab1 {Mamedyarov - Wei Yi, Wijk aan Zee, 2018, now} g5 $1 20. Qe4 Rfc8 $44 {looks fine}) 18. Qe4 Qb6 19. Rab1 Nb3 20. h4 Bf6 21. Rfd1 Rab8 $44) 12... a5 {A necessary part of Black's set-up, so his best is to play it at once.} (12... Bd5 $6 13. Qc2 (13. Qd3 $5) 13... a5 14. e4 Bc6 15. Nc3 Na6 16. h4 Nb4 17. Qe2 g6 {So far Ding Liren - Carlsen, chess24.com INT, 2021, when} 18. e5 $5 Bg7 19. h5 $36 {looks quite promising -} Qe7 (19... g5 20. Rac1 Qe7 21. Nh2 $16 {[%cal Gh2g4]}) (19... gxh5 20. Nh4 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 c5 22. dxc5 Qc7 23. f4 Qxc5 24. Ne4 $16) 20. Nh2 Rad8 21. hxg6 fxg6 22. Ne4 $16) (12... Bxf3 $6 13. Bxf3 c6 14. a5 $1 {[%csl Ga5,Ra6,Rb7,Rc6] takes advantage of Black's inaccuracy -} Nd7 15. Nc3 ({it is possible to sellect another route by} 15. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd2b3]}) 15... Qc7 (15... Be7 16. b4 {is likely to transpose}) 16. b4 Be7 17. Na4 Rad8 (17... Nf6 18. e4 $16) 18. Rac1 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4,Ga4c5]}) 13. Nc3 Bd5 (13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 c6 {is the other way to keep the d5-square under control -} 15. Rac1 (15. b4 $5 axb4 16. Qxb4 Ra7 17. e3 Nd7 {Jakovenko - Karjakin, Odessa, 2010} 18. a5 Be7 19. Qb2 $14) (15. Qb3 $5) 15... Na6 16. h4 Nb4 17. e3 $14 {[%cal Gg1g2,Gc3e4,Gc4e2]}) ({In case of} 13... Na6 {[%cal Ga6b4] Black should reckon with the central strike:} 14. e4 (14. d5 $5 $146 exd5 15. Nxd5 Bxb2 (15... Bxd5 $6 16. Rxd5 Qe7 17. Rxa5 c6 18. Rb1 $16) 16. Rab1 Bf6 17. h3 $1 ({or} 17. h4 $44) 17... Qd6 (17... Bxd5 18. Rxd5 Qc8 19. Rxa5 $14) (17... Rb8 18. Nh2 $1 {[%cal Gh2g4]} Bxd5 19. Rxd5 Qc8 20. Rxa5 c6 21. Ng4 $16) 18. Nh2 $1 Qe6 19. Nxf6+ Qxf6 20. Ng4 Qe7 (20... Qe6 21. Qxe6 fxe6 22. Bxc6 bxc6 23. Ne5 $14) 21. Rxb7 $1 Bxb7 (21... Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Nc5 23. Rb2 $16) 22. Bxb7 Nb4 (22... Nc5 23. Bxa8 Rxa8 24. Rd5 $14) 23. Bxa8 Rxa8 24. Ne3 $14) 14... Nb4 15. h4 (15. Rd2 $5) 15... b6 (15... Qb8 {in Giri - Nepomniachtchi, Zagreb, 2021, could be tested by} 16. d5 exd5 17. exd5 Bd7 18. Ne4 Be7 19. Ne5 $36) 16. Rd2 Rc8 17. Qe2 $14) 14. Nxd5 $5 (14. Qb5 Ra6 {may transpose}) (14. Qd3 {creates the threat 15.e4, so it is time to revert to} Bxf3 15. Qxf3 c6 16. e3 $14) 14... exd5 15. Qb3 Ra6 (15... Na6 $6 16. Qxb7 Nb4 17. e3 $16) 16. Ne5 c6 (16... Rb6 $6 {is dubious -} 17. Qxd5 $1 ({of course, the feeble} 17. Qc3 {will justify Black's last move -} Rb4 {etc.}) 17... Qxd5 18. Bxd5 Bxe5 (18... Rxb2 19. Ng4 $1) 19. dxe5 Rxb2 20. e6 $1 ({a logical improvement upon} 20. Rab1 Rxb1 21. Rxb1 b6 22. f4 Rd8 23. e4 Na6 24. Rc1 Nc5 $13 {, when Black has managed to bring Nb8 into play and consolidate, Ding Liren - Carlsen, chess24.com INT, 2021}) 20... fxe6 21. Bxe6+ Kh8 22. Bg4 Rb4 23. Bh5 $1 {[%csl Gh5]} Kh7 24. f4 $36) 17. Ng4 $1 $146 (17. Qxb7 {is equivalent to a draw offer and the repetition has become inevitable after} Rb6 18. Qa7 Be7 $1 19. Nd3 $140 Ra6 20. Qb7 Rb6 $11 {1/2 Xiong - So, Saint Louis, 2018.}) (17. e4 Rb6 18. Qc3 Rb4 $11) 17... Be7 (17... Nd7 $6 18. Qxb7 Rb6 19. Qa7 Rxb2 20. Bh3 $16) 18. e4 Rb6 (18... dxe4 $6 19. Bxe4 Rb6 20. Qf3 $36 {[%cal Gf3f5,Gd4d5] with good attacking prospects.}) 19. Qc3 dxe4 ({Or} 19... Bb4 20. Qc2 dxe4 21. Bxe4 Nd7 {, when the central break} 22. d5 $14 {favours White, whose pieces are better coordinated.}) 20. Bxe4 f5 ({Black is facing similar problems after} 20... Nd7 21. d5 Nc5 22. Bc2 cxd5 23. Ne3 $14 {[%cal Ge3d5,Gd1d5]}) 21. Qc4+ Kh7 (21... Kh8 $6 22. Bc2 {is more or less forcing Black to accept the piece, which threatens to plant on the excellent e5-square.} fxg4 (22... Nd7 23. Ne5 $16) (22... Rb4 23. Qc3 $16) 23. Qd3 Kg8 24. Qh7+ Kf7 25. Re1 $1 c5 26. dxc5 Bxc5 27. b4 $1 {A highly original way to secure the b3-square for the bishop, as Rb6 must protect the 6th rank.} Bxb4 28. Bb3+ Kf6 29. Re4 Bd2 30. Rxg4 Bg5 31. Bc2 Kf7 32. h4 {One more critical position - White is about to regain the sacrificed piece, the sequence} Qc8 33. Bf5 Rh8 34. Bxc8 Rxh7 35. hxg5 hxg5 36. Rxg5 Nc6 37. Rd1 $16 {leads to a favorable ending, in which Black should still be on alert about his monarch and the queenside pawns as well, as in such types the bishop is the stronger minor piece.}) 22. Bc2 (22. Bd3 $6 Rb4 23. Qc2 g6 24. Ne5 Rxd4 25. h4 h5 $13) 22... g6 (22... Rxb2 $6 23. Ne5 g6 24. h4 h5 25. Nd3 Rb6 26. Nf4 $16) (22... Rb4 23. Qe6 $1 g6 24. Re1 Bd6 25. Rad1 Kg7 26. Ne5 Qf6 27. Qa2 $14) 23. Ne5 {Black has defended the g6-pawn in advance, but this knight is really annoying.} (23. Ne3 Bf6) 23... Rb4 24. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gh2h4,Ge5d3,Gd3f4,Ga1a3,Ga3e3]} *

