{[%evp 0,47,20,20,20,9,18,18,15,-18,17,11,6,10,6,0,10,-10,5,-9,5,6,15,15,11,6,5,4,-1,3,20,13,13,20,45,46,32,32,16,17,47,38,99,5,15,19,15,0,0,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bg5 a5 11. Nc3 Na6 {Directing the knight to the b4-square.} (11... Bxf3 $6 {is definitely premature -} 12. Bxf3 c6 13. e4 $16 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf3,Gg5][%cal Ga1d1,Gf1e1]}) (11... Ra6 {[%cal Ga6b6] is quite a common alternative way of exploiting the a6-square and the rook often reaches the same b4-outpost. White has the subtle retreat} 12. Qd3 $1 {[%cal Gd3c2]} ({the tiny, but essential difference to} 12. e3 Rb6 13. Qe2 {is revealed after} Nbd7 {, when} 14. e4 $2 {drops a pawn after} Nxe4 $1) 12... Rb6 (12... h6 13. Bd2 (13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. e4) 13... Nbd7) 13. Qc2 Bxf3 ({here} 13... Nbd7 $2 {is pointless in the view of} 14. e4 $16 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4]}) (13... h6 14. Bd2 Bb4 (14... Bxf3 $6 15. Bxf3 Nc6 16. e3 Nb4 17. Qd1 c6 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 $16 {[%csl Gd2,Ge4][%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5]}) 15. Rfe1 Bxf3 ({Black's previous move has been supposedly connected with an idea for} 15... Bxc3 16. bxc3 Be4 17. Qa2 $14 {, though then Rb6 will be strangely placed}) 16. Bxf3 Nc6 17. e3 e5 18. Bxc6 (18. d5 {is nicely neutralized by} Bxc3 19. Bxc3 Nb4 20. Qd2 e4 $1 21. Bxf6 Qxf6 22. Bxe4 Re8 {with plenty of compensation for the pawn -} 23. Bb1 ({a neat point of Black's operation is} 23. Bg2 Nc2 $1 24. Qxc2 Rxb2 25. Qxb2 Qxb2 26. Rab1 Qd2 $11) 23... Qg5 24. Rd1 Rd6 25. Ba2 (25. e4 c6 $11) 25... c6 26. Bb3 cxd5 27. Rac1 b6 $11) 18... exd4 ({the pawn sacrifice} 18... Rxc6 19. dxe5 Nd5 20. f4 $14 {is arguable}) 19. Bf3 dxc3 20. bxc3 Bc5 {So far So - Adams, London, 2016, , when very interesting is} 21. c4 $1 (21. Red1 $14) 21... Bb4 22. c5 {with the tactical justification} Qxd2 23. Qxd2 Bxd2 24. cxb6 Bxe1 25. bxc7 Rc8 26. Rc1 $1 Ne8 (26... Bxf2+ {is restoring the material balance, but after the forced sequence} 27. Kxf2 Ne8 28. Bxb7 Rxc7 29. Rxc7 Nxc7 30. Ke2 Kf8 31. Kd3 Ke7 32. Kc4 Kd6 33. Bf3 $16 {[%csl Ra5] Black is in big danger of finding himself in zugzwang}) 27. Rxe1 Rxc7 28. Rb1 Nd6 29. Rd1 Rd7 {and here} 30. Bxb7 Rxb7 31. Rxd6 Rb1+ 32. Kg2 Ra1 33. Rd4 $16 {with every chance to convert the extra pawn}) 14. Bxf3 Nc6 15. e3 Nb4 16. Qe2 Nbd5 $5 ({it looks like White cannot keep the pair of bishops for long, e.g.} 16... h6 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Ne4 c6 19. h4 $14 {with "just" spatial advantage}) 17. Rfd1 c6 18. Qc2 Nb4 19. Qd2 Nd7 ({or the familiar} 19... h6 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Ne4 $14) 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. Rac1 $14) (11... Nbd7 {-10...Nbd7}) 12. Bxf6 ({Another popular move is} 12. Rfd1 {, analogously to move 14.}) 12... Bxf6 13. e4 Nb4 14. Rad1 $5 {Intending to place the rooks on the central files.} ({The main continuation is} 14. Rfd1 {d5, so is with} b6 {etc.}) 14... Qd7 $146 {Trying to gain time for the mobilization of the heavy pieces.} (14... g6 {only secures the g7-square for a retreat without taking any measures against the central break -} 15. d5 (15. h4 $5) 15... exd5 (15... Bd7 16. e5 Bg7 17. dxe6 Bxe6 18. Qc5 Qb8 {and the jump} (18... b6 19. Rxd8 bxc5 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. Ng5 Rd8 (21... Rb8 22. Nxe6 fxe6 23. f4 Nd3 24. Nb5 $16) 22. Nxe6 fxe6 23. f4 $16 {[%csl Rg7]}) 19. Ng5 $1 {poses problems again -} Bb3 20. e6 $1 $36) 16. exd5 Bd7 17. h4 (17. Nd4 Re8 18. h4 $14) 17... Ra6 (17... Re8 18. Ng5 {[%cal Gg5e4]}) 18. Rfe1 $14) (14... Rc8 15. Rd2 Qe8 16. Ra1 $14) (14... Qe8 15. d5 exd5 16. exd5 Bxa4 17. Nxa4 (17. Rfe1 Qb8 18. Nxa4 b5 19. Qb3 bxa4 20. Qxa4 Qb6 $11) 17... Qxa4 {transposes to the main text with 14...Qd7}) (14... b6 15. d5 $1 exd5 16. exd5 Bb7 (16... Bd7 17. Nd4 Bxd4 18. Qxd4 $14) 17. Nd4 Bxd4 ({here is some evidence why Nd4 should better be eliminated -} 17... Qd7 $6 18. Ne6 $1 Rfc8 19. Rfe1 Ba6 20. Qg4 $36) ({or} 17... Ba6 18. Ndb5 $14) 18. Rxd4 (18. Qxd4 Ba6 19. d6 Bxf1 20. Bxa8 Qxa8 21. Rxf1 cxd6 22. Qxd6 Qb7 $11) 18... Qd7 (18... Ba6 19. Nb5 Rc8 ({after} 19... Bxb5 $6 20. axb5 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gf1c1,Gg2h3] Nb4 is practically out of play}) 20. Rc1 (20. h4 $14) 20... Qf6 21. Rcd1 $14) 19. Nb5 Ba6 (19... Rac8 20. h4) 20. Rc1 Rac8 21. h4 $14) 15. d5 $1 {The only real winning attempt.} (15. b3 b6 $11) (15. Qb3 b6 16. Rd2 Bb7 $11) 15... exd5 16. exd5 Bxa4 17. Nxa4 Qxa4 18. Qxc7 Qb5 {The main question from here on is how far the created passed pawn is going to progress. The text move is defending the b7-pawn while leaving the capture of its counterpart until the most appropriate moment. Here are the alternatives:} (18... Bxb2 19. d6 Rad8 20. Qxb7 $36 {[%csl Gd6]}) (18... Na6 $5 19. Qxb7 Rfb8 (19... Nc5 20. Qb6 Qb4 21. Qxb4 axb4 22. d6 Rad8 ({right now} 22... Bxb2 $2 {will cost material after} 23. Nd4 $1 {, for instance} Ra6 24. Nc6 b3 25. d7 Bf6 26. d8=Q Bxd8 27. Nxd8 b2 28. Nc6 Rb6 29. Ne5 $18) 23. Rd5 $1 {at once guarantees a lasting advantage after} (23. b3 $5 Nxb3 24. Rd5 {restricts the knight, but Black can initiate counterplay by} Rc8 $1 {, freeing the blockading d8-square for the other rook -} 25. Ne5 (25. d7 Rc3) (25. Rb5 Rb8) 25... Rfd8 26. f4 g6 $11) 23... Ne4 24. Ne5 $1 (24. d7 $143 Bxb2 25. Bh3 g6 $11) 24... Bxe5 (24... Rxd6 $6 25. Rxd6 Nxd6 26. Nd7) 25. Rxe5 Nxd6 26. Rc1 $14 {[%csl Rb4] , when White is enjoying the better minor piece and the b4-pawn is in permanent danger}) 20. b3 $5 (20. Qc6 Qxc6 21. dxc6 Rxb2 $11) 20... Qxb3 21. Qd7 g6 22. Nd2 $1 (22. d6 Nc5) 22... Nc5 23. Qc6 Qb6 24. Nc4 {and Black's best seems to part with a pawn and try to hold due to the opposite-colored bishops after} Qa6 25. Qxc5 Rc8 26. Qxa5 Rxc4 (26... Qxc4 27. Qd2 Ra2 28. Qe3 $14) 27. Qxa6 Rxa6 28. d6 Rd4 29. Rxd4 Bxd4 30. d7 Rd6 31. Bc6 $14) 19. Nd4 $1 (19. Ne5 Rad8 (19... Rac8 20. Qd7) 20. Qc4 Qb6 21. Qf4 Bxe5 22. Qxe5 Rfe8 $11) 19... Qa6 (19... Bxd4 $6 20. Rxd4 Na6 21. Qc3 Rac8 22. Qa3 $16) 20. Nf5 (20. d6 Rac8 21. Bxb7 Rxc7 22. Bxa6 Rd7 $11) 20... g6 (20... Rac8 21. Ne7+ Bxe7 22. Qxe7 Rfe8 23. Qd7 Red8 24. Qa4 Qb6 25. Rd2 $14) 21. Ne7+ Bxe7 22. Qxe7 Rfe8 23. Qc7 Rac8 24. Qf4 $14 