{[%evp 0,47,20,18,18,18,18,23,23,-9,19,11,6,7,8,-3,2,-6,5,12,6,4,4,0,-15,-36,17,22,22,-14,48,26,39,40,30,30,36,24,31,33,27,28,32,21,32,17,7,19,24,26]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bg5 Bd5 11. Qc2 ({A major alternative is} 11. Qd3 c5 $140 12. Nc3 Bc6 13. Rfd1 Qa5) 11... Be4 {Black keeps on chasing the queen before making a key decision of how to develop. Indeed, the bishop will be exposed to Nc3 or Nbd2.} (11... c5 $6 {seems premature in the view of} 12. dxc5 Qa5 (12... Be4 13. Qc1) 13. Nc3 Bc6 (13... Qxc5 $6 {is running into} 14. b4 $1 Qxb4 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Rab1 Qc5 17. Qxc5 Bxc5 18. Rxb7 Nc6 19. Bd2 $16) 14. Nd4 (14. e4 $5) 14... Qxc5 15. Nxc6 Nxc6 16. Be3 Qh5 17. h3 $14) 12. Qc1 ({Another popular move is} 12. Qd1 {, when} c5 {is already fully justified.}) 12... h6 (12... Bxf3 $6 13. Bxf3 c6 14. Rd1 a5 15. e4 ({besides,} 15. Nc3 {transposes to the subline with 12...a5?!, see below}) 15... h6 16. Be3 Na6 {Tkachiev - Kravtsiv, Bastia, 2015,} 17. Na3 $16) (12... Nc6 $5 {has been tested at the highest level:} 13. e3 {The main reply - now the d4-pawn is steadily protected:} (13. Rd1 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Nxd4 15. Kg2 c5 16. e3 Nb3 17. Rxd8 Nxc1 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19. Bxb7 (19. Nd2 Nd3) 19... Ra7 20. Bf3 {So far Carlsen - Firouzja, Zagreb, 2022, when} Nb3 21. Ra2 h6 {is the simplest, e. g.} 22. Bxf6 Bxf6 23. Nc3 c4 $11) (13. Nbd2 {is more principled, even though Black can again take the central pawn with confidence, for example} Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxg2 15. Nxe6 Qd6 $1 ({The point! There is no need for} 15... fxe6 16. Kxg2 Qd5+ 17. Nf3 $14 {- that split will undoubtedly be to White's taste}) 16. Nxf8 (16. Bxf6 Bxf1 {may transpose to 16.Nxf8, see below}) (16. Kxg2 Qxe6 17. Qc4 Qxc4 ({the queenless endgame is balanced, if Black prefers to retain more tension on the board, then} 17... Qf5 $5 {is fully playable}) 18. Nxc4 h6 19. Bf4 Nd5 20. Rfd1 Nxf4+ 21. gxf4 Rfd8 22. e4 Kf8 23. Kf3 g6 $11) 16... Bxf1 17. Bxf6 Bxf8 18. Bxg7 Bxe2 19. Ne4 (19. Bxf8 Rxf8 20. Ne4 Qe5 21. Qe3 Bc4 22. Rd1 Kg7 23. Rd4 Bd5 $11 {with further simplifications in Lazavik - Lysyj, Cheliabinsk, 2023}) 19... Qg6 20. Bxf8 (20. Bc3 Qxe4 21. Qg5+ Qg6 22. Qe5 Bg7 23. Qxe2 Bxc3 24. bxc3 Qc6 25. Qg4+ Kf8 26. Qd4 Kg8 27. Re1 Re8 $11) 20... Qxe4 21. Bh6 Re8 22. Qxc7 (22. Ra3 Qd5 $11) (22. Qc3 Qe5 $11) 22... Bf3 $44 23. Qc3 f6 24. h3 Kf7 25. Qe3 Qf5 26. Qf4 Qxf4 27. Bxf4 $11 {and draw was agreed 7 moves later in Deac - Grischuk, Chess. com INT, 2023.}) 13... Nb4 (13... h6 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nbd2 Bd3 $1 (15... Bh7 16. Nb3 $14) 16. Rd1 Nb4 17. Qc3 a5 18. Nb3 ({possible is} 18. Ne5 Be2 {, when} 19. Bxb7 Bxd1 20. Rxd1 {is a correct exchange sacrifice, to which Black can vigorously give it back by} Bxe5 $1 21. Bxa8 Qxa8 22. dxe5 {in return for a nasty pin after} Rd8 23. Qxc7 Rd3 $44) 18... Bc2 19. Rd2 Be4 (19... Bxb3 20. Qxb3 c6 21. h4 $14) 20. Nc5 Bd5 21. Ne5 Bxe5 22. dxe5 Qc8 23. Nd3 (23. e4 Bc6 $13) 23... Bxg2 24. Kxg2 Nxd3 25. Rxd3 Rd8 26. Rad1 Rxd3 27. Rxd3 (27. Qxd3 b6) 27... c6 28. Rd6 {Black has lost the fight for the d-file, but} b5 $5 {is going to annihilate the whole queenside, e.g.} 29. Qxc6 (29. Rxc6 Qb7) 29... Qxc6+ 30. Rxc6 bxa4 $14 {/=/}) (13... Rc8 $6 14. Nbd2 Bg6 {has led to a quick draw in Zhou Weiqi - Liu Qingnan, China, 2017, but White's chances are preferable after} 15. Nb3 $14 {[%csl Rc5]}) (13... Bb4 $5 14. Nc3 Bxc3 15. bxc3 (15. Qxc3 h6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Nd2 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 e5 $11) 15... h6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Nd2 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Na5 19. Rd1 ({a small refinement over} 19. Qb1 e5 20. Qe4 Rfe8 $11 {Nepomniachtchi - Firouzja, Saint Louis, 2022}) 19... Qd8 {and only now} 20. Qb1 Qd6 21. Qe4 $14) 14. Nc3 Bc6 (14... Bxf3 $6 15. Bxf3 c6 16. a5 $16) 15. Rd1 (15. a5 h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Rd1 Rc8 18. e4 b5 $11) 15... a5 (15... h6 {will probably be of no independent significance after} 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. e4) 16. e4 (16. h4 $5) 16... h6 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. h4 $14) (12... Nbd7 $6 13. Nc3 Bc6 14. Qc2 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Bb4 ({instead,} 14... h6 {surrenders the e4-square and therefore the center -} 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 16. e4 Bb4 17. Rfe1 $14) 15. a5 {and in Cheparinov - Hawkins, England, 2018, Black played the inaccurate} ({seizing space on the queenside; once again} 15. Rfe1 $5 {[%cal Ge2e4]} h6 16. Bf4 {is seriously questioning Black's plans about the center}) 15... Qe7 $6 (15... h6 16. Bd2 $14) {, to which} 16. e4 $1 {could be executed without preparation, a sample line goes on with} h6 17. Bxf6 Nxf6 18. Ne5 Rfd8 19. Nxc6 bxc6 20. e5 Nd5 21. Ne4 $16) (12... a5 $6 13. Nc3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 c6 15. Rd1 {and, just like in the aforementioned subline with 12...Bxf3?!, White can rely on his pair of bishops} h6 16. Bd2 $14 {[%csl Gd2,Gf3]}) 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Rd1 ({Harmless is} 14. Nc3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Qxd4 16. Bxb7 Ra7 17. Bf3 Qb4 $11) ({Another possible move is} 14. Nbd2) 14... a5 (14... Nc6 {should be studied in close connection with 12...Nc6 from above, as well as the subtle} 15. Nbd2 $1 (15. e3 Nb4 {is providing Black with additional possibilities}) 15... Nxd4 {is essential again -} (15... Bh7 16. e3 Nb4 17. Ne1 c6 (17... Rb8 $5) 18. a5 Qe7 (18... Nd3 19. Nxd3 Bxd3 20. Nb3 $14 {[%cal Gb3c5]}) 19. Nb3 e5 20. e4 exd4 21. Ra4 {[%csl Rb4]} Rab8 22. f4 $36) (15... Bxf3 $6 16. Nxf3 $14 {[%csl Rc6]}) 16. Nxd4 (16. Nxe4 Nxe2+ 17. Kf1 Nxc1 18. Rxd8 Raxd8 19. Nxf6+ gxf6 20. Rxc1 c6 $13) 16... Bxg2 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Kxg2 Qd4 $1 ({without the concrete textmove Black may quickly land in a strategically precarious situation, for instance} 18... Qe7 $6 19. Ne4 Rad8 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 21. Qc2 Rd5 22. Rc1 c6 23. Qb3 $16 {[%csl Rb7,Ge4,Re6]}) 19. Nf3 $146 {is the only serious try to claim any opening advantage -} (19. Qc2 Qxb2 20. Qxb2 Bxb2 21. Rab1 Bf6 22. Ne4 (22. Rxb7 Rfd8 {[%cal Gd8d1]}) 22... Rfb8 23. Nxf6+ gxf6 24. Rd7 b5 $11) (19. f3 Qxb2 20. Qxb2 Bxb2 21. Rab1 Bf6 {and here White can make use of the extra f2-f3 on the board by entering} 22. Rxb7 (22. Ne4 b6) 22... Rfd8 23. Rbb1 Rd4 24. Ne4 Rxa4 $11) 19... Qe4 20. Rd2 Rad8 $1 ({Activity above all! White is consolidating after} 20... c6 21. Qc2 $14) 21. Qc2 Qf5 $5 (21... Rd4 {can be met by the cool} 22. b3 {, when} c6 23. Rb1 Qxc2 24. Rxc2 $14 {is analogous to the last note. Besides, Black has a brilliant idea up his sleeve}) 22. Rc1 Rxd2 23. Nxd2 Bxb2 $1 24. Qxf5 $1 (24. Qxb2 $143 Qxf2+ 25. Kh3 Qxe2 $11) 24... exf5 (24... Rxf5 $6 25. Rxc7 Rf7 26. Rc8+ Rf8 27. Rc2 Ba3 28. f4 b5 29. axb5 axb5 30. Rc6 Rd8 31. Nb3 Kf7 32. Rb6 $14) 25. Rxc7 b5 26. axb5 (26. a5 Rf7 27. Rc6 Rf6 $11) 26... axb5 27. Rb7 Bc3 28. Nb1 (28. Nb3 b4) (28. Nf1 $5 b4 29. Ne3) 28... b4 29. Nxc3 bxc3 30. Rc7 {, reaching a rook ending with 4 vs. 3 on the kingside, where the f5-pawn is exposed to some extent -} Re8 31. e3 $14 {/=/}) (14... Nd7 {looks less useful than the text move, White has the usual choice of how to harass Be4.} 15. Nc3 (15. Nbd2) 15... Bh7 (15... Bxf3 16. Bxf3 c6 17. b4 $14) 16. Ne5 ({or} 16. a5 {at once, seizing space on the queenside in either case}) 16... c6 17. a5 $14) 15. Nbd2 ({Similar, though a bit less flexible is} 15. Nc3 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 c6) 15... Bxf3 ({The exchange of the bishop is much more common than} 15... Bh7 16. Nb3 {, when the knights are ready to jump on the c5- and e5-squares respectively:} c6 (16... Nd7 $6 17. Ne5 $1 c6 18. Qc3 Ra7 19. e4 $5 ({a probable improvement upon} 19. Nxa5 Bxe5 20. dxe5 Rxa5 21. Rxd7 Rxa4 22. Rxa4 Qxd7 23. Rd4 Qc7 {Carlsen - Aronian, Wijk aan Zee, 2023} 24. Qc5 $14) 19... Qc7 20. Nxd7 Qxd7 21. Nxa5 Rfa8 22. b4 Qc7 23. Qb3 Be7 24. d5 cxd5 25. exd5 Bc2 26. Rdc1 Bxb3 27. Rxc7 Bd8 28. Rxb7 Bxa5 29. dxe6 $1 Rxb7 30. Bxb7 Rb8 31. e7 $1 Bxb4 32. Rb1 Bxe7 33. Rxb3 Bd8 34. Kg2 $16) 17. Qc3 ({it is possible to play at first} 17. Ne5 $5 Qc7 $140 18. Qc3) 17... Be7 18. Nc5 Qc7 19. Ne5 Na6 $2 ({in a later encounter Black has put his hopes on the cautious} 19... Rd8 {Hammer - Nihal, Stockholm, 2018;} 20. h4 $14) 20. Nxb7 $1 Qxb7 21. Bxc6 Qc7 22. Bxa8 Qxc3 23. bxc3 Rxa8 24. Nc6 Bd8 25. Nxd8 Rxd8 26. f3 $16 {Eljanov - Nakamura, Baku, 2015.}) (15... Bc6 16. Qc3 $14) 16. Bxf3 c6 17. e3 ({In case of} 17. Nb3 {this knight is badly placed, as witnessed by} Na6 18. h4 Qb6 19. Qc4 Rfd8 $11 {[%csl Rb3] and soon a draw was agreed in Markus - Wojtaszek, Skopje, 2015.}) (17. Nc4 Na6 {may transpose.}) 17... Na6 18. h4 $5 ({After} 18. Nc4 Nb4 {the game Meier - Kravtsiv, Berlin, 2015, did not last for long either.}) 18... Nb4 ({Black should better refrain from} 18... g6 19. h5 g5 20. Qc4 Qe7 21. Qe2 Nb4 22. Nc4 Rfd8 23. Rd2 Bg7 24. Rad1 {[%cal Ge3e4,Ge4e5]} Qc7 25. e4 Rac8 26. e5 Nd5 27. Be4 $16 {Giri - Vidit, Kolkata, 2019}) 19. Qc5 $5 {[%cal Gc5h5]} (19. h5 Qc7) (19. Qc4 Qc7) 19... Qc7 ({As mentioned, the weakening of the king's residence} 19... g6 {cannot be recommended -} 20. h5 g5 21. Qc4 $14 {[%cal Gc4e2] , following Giri's plan from above}) ({In reply to} 19... Be7 {, besides the intended 20.Qh5, White can again switch to} 20. Qc4 $5 {[%csl Re7]} Qc7 21. Qe2 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gh4h5]}) 20. Qh5 Rad8 21. Kg2 Rd7 22. Nc4 b6 23. Rac1 Rfd8 24. Be4 $14 *

